<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Debate-Children     10-13 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Debate-Children,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush, Dukakis Bring Up Personal Losses As They Tackle Abortion
Question</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Debate Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Both George Bush and Michael Dukakis recounted
poignant stories about children they had lost as they sought during
Thursday night's debate to justify their opposing views on abortion.
   Bush was asked why a woman should be forced to carry a fetus to
term if she knows it will be born with an illness that consigns it
to a brief, pained existence.
   Bush, who opposes abortion except in cases of incest, rape or
when a mother's life is endangered, began his answer by cautioning:
``I hope it doesn't get too personal, or maudlin. Bar and I lost a
child, you know that. We lost a daughter, Robin.''
   The child died of leukemia before she turned 4.
   Bush said that if the baby were alive today, ``that child could
stay alive for 10 or 15 years, or maybe for the rest of her life.
And so, I don't think that you make an exception based on medical
knowledge at the time. I think human life is very, very precious.''
   Dukakis, in his response to Bush's answer, said he and his wife,
Kitty, ``had very much the same kind of experience that the Bushes
had. We lost a baby _ lived about 20 minutes after it was born.''
   But Dukakis went on to say that ``isn't the real question that
we have to answer ... who makes the decision, who makes this very
difficult, very wrenching decision.''
   He continued: ``I think it has to be the woman, in the exercise
of her own conscience and religious beliefs, that makes that
decision. Who are we to say, `Well, under certain circumstances
it's all right, but under other circumstances it isn't?'''
   Mrs. Dukakis, who became pregnant early in 1964, believes she
must have had German measles during the first trimester of her
pregnancy. The day after a checkup during her seventh month of
pregnancy, she went into premature labor. The baby girl, who lived
just 20 minutes, was anencephalic and would have been gravely
handicapped had she survived.
</TEXT>
