<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Debate-Reax     10-13 0639</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Debate-Reax,0600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Politicians Say Both Candidates Improved; Few See Dukakis
``Knockout''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Politicians from both parties said the rival presidential
candidates seemed more at ease in Thursday's debate than in their
first encounter, but most agreed that Michael Dukakis failed to
deliver the ``knockout'' he needed against Vice President George
Bush.
   ``In the debate itself, there was no clear winner, but in the
continuing war, Bush continues to lead,'' said Republican Rep. John
Rowland of Connecticut. ``This was Dukakis' chance for a knockout
blow, and he merely danced in the ring.''
   Democratic Sen. Alan Dixon of Illinois said Dukakis ``won on
issues answers'' about Social Security, gun control and the
environment.
   But Dixon also said, ``There was no, `You're no Jack Kennedy'
tonight,'' referring to a remark _ seen by many as a telling blow _
that Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen made in his debate with Republican
vice presidential candidate Indiana Sen. Dan Quayle.
   One Democrat who gave the edge to Bush was former Sen. Thomas
Eagleton of Missouri, who was George McGovern's running mate in
1972 until he withdrew from the ticket after it became known he had
undergone shock treamtents for psychiatric problems.
   ``The one home run I heard was Bush's,'' said Eagleton. ``When
they asked who their heroes were, Dukakis was wandering all over
the stage. Bush, with two minutes to think about it, came up with
some solid candidates and ended up with the president.''
   Jack Richardson, Hawaii state Democratic Party chairman, agreed
there was ``no knockout blow by Governor Dukakis, but the governor
definitely won.''
   And a knockout blow was just what some observers said Dukakis
needed. With pre-debate polls giving Bush a narrow lead among
voters nationwide and a strong lead for electoral votes, analysts
had seen Thursday's final face-to-face contest as perhaps Dukakis'
best chance to change voters' minds before the election Nov. 8.
   ``Dukakis had to do something dramatic and I don't think he did
it. I don't think he laid a glove on Bush,'' said Ellen Sauerbrey.
GOP state delegate from Maryland. ``I think barring some unforeseen
gaffe in the next couple weeks or a major world-shattering event. I
think the election is over. This was Dukakis' last chance to really
turn public opinion.''
   ``It's over. The election is over,'' agreed Claibourne Darden,
an Atlanta-based political pollster. ``Bush did extremely well,
much better than he did last time, which wasn't real good ...
Dukakis also did well, attempting to add _ and was successful to a
moderate extent _ a human feeling and sense of emotion to his
character. Both were successful, and consequently, the odds of
George Bush losing have become extremely little.''
   Most Republican observers were clearly delighted about Bush's
performance _ and even found room to praise Dukakis.
   ``Let me pay my respects to Michael Dukakis for a very fine
debate, but on the political points, I think Bush clearly won,''
said Rep. Jack Kemp, R-N.Y.
   Said Gordon Durnil, chairman of Indiana Republican Party: ``That
was the absolute best debate performance by anyone I've sever seen
by George Bush. It was a home run for him.''
   ``Both candidates were more relaxed and perhaps more confident
than before,'' said Massachusetts Republican state Sen. David
Locke, the state Bush co-chair. ``However, Governor Dukakis,
despite performing well, failed to provide the American people with
any reason to change the direction in which we're going.''
   But some elected officials were not excited by what they saw
from either candidate.
   Montana's Democratic Gov. Ted Schwinden said: ``I honestly don't
know who the winner is. But I know who the loser is _ the ones of
us who watch.''
   ``It's getting to the point of who's the best actor on stage and
that's a long way from answering who will be the next president,''
Schwinden said.
</TEXT>
