<1ST_LINE>u p AM-RatingtheDebate     10-13 0712</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rating the Debate,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AP Panel of Judges Gives Debate to Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush won his second and final debate
with Michael Dukakis by hammering at foreign policy issues, an
Associated Press panel of debate judges said Thursday night.
   Some 639 voters polled by ABC News immediately after the debate
also gave the nod to the vice president, with 49 percent saying
Bush won and only 33 percent giving the edge to Dukakis; 18 percent
called it a tie. The survey had a 4 point margin of error.
   The AP panel scored it a 145-141 win for Bush, reversing the
outcome of the first presidential debate, which the AP judges
scored 144-141 for Dukakis. Five of the six judges called Bush the
winner; one sided with Dukakis.
   ABC also asked its survey group before and after the debate who
they planned to vote for. Beforehand they favored Bush, 53-43, with
4 percent undecided. Afterwards, they backed Bush 54-44, with 2
percent still undecided.
   Among the AP judges, Donn Parson, director of graduate study in
the University of Kansas' Department of Communication Studies,
said, ``Dukakis did a very poor job in answering the foreign policy
issues. Bush made good use of Dukakis' support for a nuclear
freeze.''
   James J. Unger, director of the National Forensics Institute at
American University in Washington and chairman of the AP panel,
said, ``George Bush won it. ... Dukakis' concern for an election
breakthrough too often led to a debate breakdown on issues such as
deficit control, defense policy and social programs.''
   William Southworth, director of forensics and professor of
speech at the University of Redlands, Calif., said it was
``catastrophic'' that Dukakis could not counter Bush's argument
that you must negotiate out of strength with the Russians. The
question was raised ``about six different ways ... and Dukakis
still had no answer,'' Southworth said.
   Melissa Maxcy Wade, the director of forensics at Emory
University in Atlanta, said, ``Bush was playing a foreign policy
theme, a world peace theme that went through the whole thing. ...
Bush is not an organized debater, but tonight his confidence made a
difference.''
   Steven P. Mancuso, director of intercollegiate forensics for the
University of Michigan, the sole judge to pick Dukakis, said he
thought the Massachusetts governor ``successfully countered Bush's
use of the label `liberal' ... and painted Bush as being
complacent.''
   James M. Copeland, national executive secretary of the National
Forensic League in Ripon, Wis., said, ``At the end of the debate,
whether you liked it or didn't like it, you knew what Bush's
position was. ... Dukakis just seemed to lack focus.''
   Copeland added, ``The whole debate was truly a mess. As a debate
coach for 25 years, I'm sorry to say that Bush certainly spoke the
truth when he said there should be no more debates. There certainly
should be no more like this last one.''
   The AP judges last week called Democrat Lloyd Bentsen the
winner, 148-125, over Republican Dan Quayle in their vice
presidential debate.
   The judges watched the debate on television, using a scorecard
modeled after the American Forensic Association Debate Ballot for
collegiate and scholastic debates.
   They awarded one to five points in each of six categories:
reasoning, evidence, organization, refutation, cross-examination
and presentation. A 1 was poor; 2 fair; 3 average; 4 excellent, and
5 superior.
   Each judge could award a maximum of 30 points. A perfect score
would have been 180.
   Here are the candidates' combined scores:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Debate Scorecard</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Bush                 Dukakis
</TEXT>
