<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Algeria Bjt   10-13 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Algeria, Bjt,0602</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Proposes Reforms, Referendums to Quell Unrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a week of riots that left hundreds
dead, President Chadli Bendjedid has unveiled a series of reforms
that he says will allow Algerians to change the constitution and
bring this restless nation closer to democracy.
   Bendjedid announced the measures, including a Nov. 3 referendum
that could end the only legal political party's grip on power,
after lifting a six-day state of emergency and curfew imposed as
riots swept the country.
   Despite Wednesday's announcement, however, new reports said at
least 10 people were killed during demonstrations in Tizi-Ouzou,
the provincial capital of Kabylie, in the Berber region about 10
miles east of Algiers.
   An estimated 176 people have been slain during six days of
rioting, according to Information Minister Bachir Rouiz. But
unofficial totals set the number of dead at more than 500, with
more than 1,000 injured.
   More than 3,000 demonstrators and agitators rounded up by police
were being held in temporary detention centers.
   The French news agency Agence France-Presse reported that about
10 people were slain Wednesday following a clash between pro- and
anti-Bendjedid demonstrators in Tizi-Ouzou.
   The agency said anti-Bendjedid demonstrators joined a march by a
group supporting the president, then moved toward a police station
where police were gathering. It said shots were fired shortly
before 4 p.m., and 10 people were slain.
   The district governor of Tizi-Ouzou, Amara Ahmed Salah, denied
there were casualties and said security forces fired only warning
shots, AFP said.
   Algeria's ambassador to France, Messaoud Ait-Chaalal, also
denied on French television that people were killed. Any injuries,
he said, ``were the result of groups of demonstrators among
themselves.''
   The reports came as Bendjedid set forth a three-point plan for
``greater democratization,'' according to Algeria's official news
agency.
   The first step calls for a Nov. 3 referendum for voters to
consider a constitutional change making the prime minister, named
by the president, answerable to Algeria's parliament.
   The prime minister would have enormously increased power,
without interference from the sole legal party, the National
Liberation Front.
   Currently, the prime minister has no specified duties under the
constitution and the parliament is widely regarded as a
rubber-stamp assembly. The current premier is the Front's Abdelhami
Brahimi.
   As a second step, Bendjedid announced measures for a ``greater
democratization of political action,'' to be placed before the
congress of the ruling party before the end of the year. He did not
elaborate.
   As a final step, Algerians would be asked to approve, in another
referendum, modifications these changes would bring to the nation's
constitution. No date was announced for this referendum.
   The reforms were announced two days after the president promised
the nation, in a televised address, that demands would be met with
economic and political reforms.
   Bendjedid predicted major changes in the Algerian leadership to
rid the nation of ``people who were not at the height of their
duties,'' but he gave no details.
   The unrest, which began Oct. 4, was spurred by Algeria's
economic crisis. Demonstrators protested food shortages and rising
prices and demanded an end to Bendjedid's austerity program.
   Algeria's hobbled economy was further weakened by the fall in
oil prices. More than 95 percent of the country's exports come from
oil and natural gas.
   In addition, government officials have admitted that a
demographic explosion does not augur well for this nation of 25
million people, 60 percent of whom are under 20 years of age.
</TEXT>
