<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LibraryFire     10-13 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Library Fire,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Latest Blaze in Central Library Due to `Freak' Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The third fire to hit the downtown Central
Library in less than three years was a freak accident caused by
construction materials ignited by a welding torch during
renovation, a Fire Department official said Wednesday.
   The fire late Tuesday afternoon occurred as the 62-year-old
library was undergoing a $152 million renovation following two
disastrous arson fires that destroyed hundreds of thousands of
books in 1986.
   The material was cut by a welding torch on the fourth floor and
dropped through a hole into the basement where it ignited a large
rubbish pile, said Inspector Ed Reed.
   The Fire Department termed it a ``freak accident,'' Reed said.
``All precautions were being observed by the company on the site.
It's highly unlikely that it will occur again.''
   The fire was confined to the northwest corner of the basement
but smoke spread throughout the building. Reed said there did not
appear to be any structural damage. The extent of potential damage
to the library's huge murals, which were being cleaned of the smoke
damage from the 1986 blazes, was being determined.
   Except for the murals, all the library's books and other
valuables had long since been removed for the renovation.
</TEXT>
