<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 0152EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GloveGlut     10-13 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Glove Glut,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Housewife Trying to Find Way Out of Glove Glut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOMBARD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who used her retirement money to
buy thousands of defective rubber gloves in an attempt to exploit
the growing concern over AIDS admits her business judgment was full
of holes.
   Today, 60-year-old Justine Spiros has 600,000 latex gloves in
her basement, and apparently no way to get rid of them _ let alone
recover her $61,000 outlay to buy them in the first place.
   The grandmother of five said she first realized her business
venture might be getting out of hand when she started looking for
samples to send to prospective customers.
   ``I found gloves with fingers off, with big holes, tears,
stains, streaks and lumps,'' Ms. Spiros recalled recently.
   Things went downhill from there.
   Ms. Spiros can't sell the gloves because huge numbers are
defective, and the seller won't give her a refund.
   She can't even throw them away because the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration is investigating her problem and may impound them.
   ``I wake up at 3:30 in the morning worrying,'' she said. ``It's
such a horrible situation.''
   Ms. Spiros got into the business because with growing concern
about blood-transmitted diseases _ especially AIDS _ demand for
gloves was high and supply was short.
   She already was marketing disposable electrodes out of a home
office that features a washer-dryer alongside a copying machine,
and sanitary gloves looked like a hot new area.
   ``Everyone wanted gloves,'' Ms. Spiros recalled. ``No one could
get enough. I figured they'd sell immediately.''
   She borrowed $41,000 from her own retirement account to cover
part of the cost of her first shipment of 600 cartons.
   After having problems finding enough good samples to use in
drumming up business, Ms. Spiros was forced to recall the one and
only shipment that ever left the basement _ 2,000 gloves sent to a
San Francisco-area ambulance company.
   She hasn't considered her next step, but she's certain no more
gloves will leave her door.
   ``I have my reputation to think of,'' Ms. Spiros said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
