<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeadHusband     10-13 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dead Husband,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>77-Year-Old Woman Survives Eight Days in Ravine Beside Dead
Husband</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SARATOGA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 77-year-old woman spent eight days
trapped in a ravine beside her dead husband after their vehicle
plunged off a highway, but she managed to survive the ordeal.
   Helen Heinrich was listed in critical condition Wednesday, three
days after she was rescued by three men who were looking for
crayfish in a nearby creek.
   Heinrich was driving home from breakfast in Santa Cruz with her
husband of 55 years, Rudolph, when the brakes failed and their car
plunged off the highway into a wooded ravine, she told Highway
Patrol officers in a bedside interview.
   Rudolph Heinrich, 83, died of massive internal injuries shortly
after the crash, authorities said.
   Before she was rescued, Helen Heinrich managed to survive
without food or water for eight days, lapsing in and out of
consciousness.
   One of three men who stumbled upon the wreck said the woman
seemed paralyzed when they found her.
   ``Her eyes were open and blinking and the fingers on her right
hand were moving,'' said Mike Schaffer, 19. ``Otherwise, she was
doing nothing.''
   ``I don't think anyone would have found them for a long time if
we hadn't just happened to go down there,'' he said.
   No one could see the car from the road because of heavy brush,
said police Officer William Waterhouse.
   Officers initially thought the woman had lain injured for only
one day next to her dead husband, but an investigation and
interview with Heinrich, who first remembered the crash Tuesday,
revealed the extent of her ordeal.
   After the car plunged 120 feet Sunday, it tumbled, rolled and
came to rest on its wheels, Waterhouse said.
   Heinrich, who suffered internal injuries, cuts and bruises and a
fractured elbow, crawled out of the wreck and collapsed, said
Waterhouse. When she was found, she was weak and extremely
dehydrated.
   ``She's a strong woman and she just hung on,'' he said. A
spokesman at San Jose Medical Center said Heinrich's most serious
medical concern is kidney trouble related to the dehydration.
</TEXT>
