<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ContraAid Bjt   10-13 0719</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contra Aid, Bjt,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Threatens Special Session Over Contras</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan plans to summon Congress into
a special session to vote on renewed military aid to the Nicaraguan
Contras if he believes the Sandinista government is moving to mop
up remnants of the rebel forces.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, speaking with reporters
Wednesday evening, confirmed earlier reports by sources that Reagan
had settled on a special session as his conditional plan for
seeking new military aid for the Contras.
   Fitzwater described it as a fall-back position to ensure the
Contras' survival into the next U.S. administration, should
Nicaragua's leftist government attack the remnants of the rebel
movement in an effort to eradicate it.
   The White House spokesman acknowledged that there is no chance
to obtain further money for the rebels before the 100th Congress
adjourns. Lawmakers are eager to return home to campaign, and hope
to complete their regular session by the week's end.
   Reagan has the power under the Constitution to call Congress
back to Washington after adjournment. If he thought it necessary to
save the Contras, he would ask Congress to release $16.5 million in
stockpiled weaponry now stored in Honduran warehouses, Fitzwater
said.
   Reagan is expected to make the threat in a statement as early as
today, according to well-placed sources who spoke on condition of
anonymity. They said it is intended as a dual message to Congress
and to the Sandinistas that the president will be scrutinizing
activities in Nicaragua during the remainder of the year when
Congress will not be in session.
   ``The point is to send the message, `Don't you try anything,
'cause I ain't leaving town,'' said one source familiar with White
House planning.
   Under a Pentagon money bill Reagan signed earlier this month, a
procedure was established for expedited congressional consideration
of a new request for military aid for the rebels.
   Despite the gestures, support for the Contras remains at a low
ebb in Congress and even their strongest supporters question
whether the rebels could ever be regrouped into an effective
fighting force.
   From a peak of nearly 18,000 rebel troops inside Nicaragua early
this year, the number has dwindled to fewer than 2,000, according
to intelligence estimates.
   ``They are now reduced to refugee status,'' said Rep. Henry
Hyde, R-Ill.
   Many of the rebels have fled to camps just inside neighboring
Honduras, and others have scattered elsewhere.
   Reagan's hope is to keep up Contra morale and preserve the
potential for reviving the rebels if vice president George Bush
wins his presidential campaign and wants to continue to make the
Contras an arm of his Central America policy, according to the
sources. Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis opposes use of the
Contras as a foreign policy tool.
   The Contras have been without U.S. military support since
February, when it was ended in deference to efforts to forge a
long-term cease-fire between the two sides. The rebels now are
receiving some $27 million in humanitarian aid under the Pentagon
appropriations measure.
   Under the law, Reagan could trigger an expedited vote on the
stockpiled weaponry if he certifies to Congress that two of three
conditions are met: that the Soviet Union continues to funnel
unacceptable levels of military hardware to the Sandinistas; that
the leftist government is violating terms of a regional peace
accord; or that the Sandinistas have launched an unprovoked attack
on the rebels.
   Administration officials maintain that the first two of those
conditions already exist. ``The president will say if anything
approaching the third (condition) occurs, I will call Congress back
into session,'' said one source familiar with the White House
planning.
   ``The idea is to send as strong a warning as he possibly can,''
the source said.
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a Contra supporter, is expected to
offer an amendment to an anti-drug measure now before the Senate
that would reiterate the warning to the Sandinistas and express
congressional willingness to go along with new military aid if
developments warrant, Capitol Hill sources said.
   ``It's the right kind of signal to send to (Nicaraguan
President) Daniel Ortega and the Democrats wh3vtra aid,'' said
Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan. ``The issue hasn't gone
away. The president is right to insist that it stay a priority on
the national stage.''
</TEXT>
