<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Murray; AMs separates moved as a0722 on Nordstrom, as
a0748 on Warren and as a0403 on Murray.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Ursula Nordstrom</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW MILFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ursula Nordstrom, a former publisher
and editor in chief of juvenile books at Harper & Row, died Tuesday
of ovarian cancer at age 78.
   Nordstrom went to work at Harper & Row in 1936. She became head
of the children's book department in 1940 and in 1960 became the
publishing company's first female vice president.
   Her books have won numerous awards, including three Newbury
Medals and two Caldecott Medals, the most prestigious children's
book awards.
   In 1945, Nordstorm edited E.B. White's first children's book,
``Stuart Little.'' Seven years later, White presented her with his
only copy of what became his classic ``Charlotte's Web.''
   She also published Maurice Sendak's ``Where the Wild Things
Are'' and Laura Ingalls Wilder, who wrote the autobiographical
``Little House'' series.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Lucian Warren</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lucian C. Warren, 75, a correspondent who
headed three of the capital's most prestigious press organizations,
died Wednesday of cancer.
   Warren served as Washington correspondent for newspapers in
Buffalo, N.Y., for 33 years, and since 1978 he worked as a
freelance journalist and Washington correspondent for the Frederick
(Md.) News-Post. Warren also wrote for Esquire and Parade magazines
and appeared on television and radio news programs.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Warren was former president of the National Press Club and the
Gridiron Club and was once chairman of the Standing Committee of
Correspondents, which regulates the congressional press galleries.
As president of the press club, he led the campaign for admission
of the first black member.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>H.A. Michael</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   H.A. ``Mike'' Michael, a former managing
editor of the El Paso Herald-Post, died Monday at the age of 89.
   In 1926, Michael joined the El Paso Post, which later merged
with the El Paso Herald. He was a reporter and city editor before
being made managing editor in 1957.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>William Allan</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Allan, a labor reporter who was
sentenced to prison during the McCarthy era in 1953, died Monday of
a heart attack. He was 81.
   Allan, who joined the Communist Party in 1935, covered labor for
nearly six decades, first with the Daily Worker in Detroit. He
moved to Oakland in 1978 and worked for the Peoples World in San
Francisco, which later became the Peoples Daily World.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Ken Murray</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ken Murray, an actor whose 30-year career
spanned the vaudeville stage and films including the 1962 motion
picture ``The Man Who Shot Liberty Valance,'' died Wednesday of
natural causes at age 85.
   Murray's is best remembered for his long-running Hollywood stage
appearances in ``Ken Murray's Blackout,'' which ran from 1942 to
1949. He produced ``Bill & Coo,'' a feature-length fantasy film
about birds that received a special Academy Award in 1947 for
``novel and entertaining use'' of the film medium.
   Murray also starred, produced and directed television's ``The
Ken Murray Show.'' Other television credits include ``Hollywood
Without Makeup,'' ``Hollywood, My Home Town,'' and ``El Coyote.''
   His motion picture debut was in ``Half-Marriage'' in 1929. Other
films included ``Leathernecking,'' ``You're A Sweetheart,'' 1937;
``A Night at Earl Carroll's,'' 1940; ``Juke Box Jenny,'' 1942;
``Son of Flubber,'' 1963; ``The Power,'' 1968 and ``Ken Murray's
Shooting Stars.''
   Murray also wrote books including ``The Body Merchant,'' ``Life
on a Pogo Stick,'' and ``The Golden Days of San Simeon.''
</TEXT>
