<DOCNO> AP881013-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 0158EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Lobbying     10-13 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lobbying,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ethics Bill Clears House; Senate Prospects Good</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House-approved government ethics bill
contains the first-ever restrictions on lobbying by former members
of Congress, and the bill's sponsor says Senate approval is likely.
   The restrictions are contained in legislation to tighten federal
rules against influence peddling by former top officials of the
government.
   The House passed the measure 374-19 on Wednesday, sending it to
the Senate. Approval in that chamber is 90 percent likely, said
Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., the bill's author.
   Frank said ``some of the senior members aren't too excited about
the bill. But there is a sense that it is not right for Congress to
apply laws to others from which it is exempt.''
   For the first time, conflict-of-interest rules would be applied
to members of Congress and their top staff members.
   Former members and their staffs would be banned for one year
from contacting the legislative house in which they served. The
bill would cover lobbying, along with any communication done for
pay to influence federal decisions, including writing letters,
filing motions, or seeking grants.
   The legislation also proposes a lifetime ban on former executive
branch members from advising anyone on a matter in which the
employee was ``personally and substantially'' involved.
   The changes are aimed at closing the ``revolving door'' through
which government employees leave for higher-paid civilian jobs
based on access to their former government colleagues.
   The most often-cited example is that of Michael K. Deaver,
President Reagan's former chief of staff, who began lobbying the
White House for his clients shortly after he resigned from the
government.
   Deaver was convicted of lying about his lobbying activities, but
never was charged with substantive violations of the current law
restricting post-employment lobbying in the executive branch. He
was sentenced to three years' probation and 1,500 hours of
community service, and fined $100,000.
   ``This is a very collegial place; we work with each other every
day,'' Frank said. ``I don't want to go from working with someone
one day to being lobbied by them the next day. We're talking about
a cooling-off period _ a transition time before we change
relationships.''
   Opponents said the restrictions were too broad and argued that
there had been no examples of abuses or improper influence being
wielded by former lawmakers.
   The bill would create exemptions from the lobbying ban for
former lawmakers who make speeches or offer personal advice to
former colleagues.
</TEXT>
