<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Iran-Contra     10-13 0756</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Contra,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hakim Seeking To Bar Lawyer From Testifying Against Him</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arms dealer Albert Hakim is trying to invoke
attorney-client privilege to bar a Geneva-based lawyer from
testifying against him and three co-defendants in the Iran-Contra
case.
   Defense lawyers are seeking a court hearing to determine if any
of the information that lawyer and financial adviser Willard Zucker
gave Iran-Contra prosecutors violated his attorney-client privilege
with Hakim, according to papers ordered unsealed Wednesday by U.S.
District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell.
   A U.S. citizen, Zucker operates a Swiss company called Compagnie
de Services Fiduciares SA (CSF) that helped move thousands of
dollars generated by the U.S.-Iran arms sales through offshore
shell companies and bank accounts to prevent the funds from being
traced.
   Zucker, a former Internal Revenue Service attorney, received
immunity from prosecution in return for cooperating with the
investigation of independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh, according
to the court papers.
   In the motion ordered unsealed by Gesell, Hakim contends that
his longstanding business relationship with Zucker is protected not
only by attorney-client privilege but by confidentiality imposed on
Zucker by Swiss privacy laws.
   The defense is trying to force Walsh to detail the information
he received from Zucker so defense lawyers can determine if Zucker
breached the privlege.
   The information ``is meant to provide the basis for further
action by the court that may well result in the suppression of any
effort by the government to introduce at any trial either the
testimony of Mr. Zucker or any information derived directly or
indirectly from government contacts with Mr. Zucker.''
   ``Production of such information may lead Mr. Hakim to request
that the court impose sanctions upon the government for
prosecutorial misconduct,'' the defense said.
   While ``Hakim is reluctant to make allegations of improper
behavior'' against prosecutors or Zucker, his lawyers said ``the
sequence of known events, however, raises a spectre of impropriety
that merits full illumination through the court's process.''
   The defense also threatened to try to suppress any testimony by
Zucker at the trial of former National Security Council aide Oliver
L. North, the first defendant scheduled to be tried on the
Iran-Contra conspiracy charges.
   No date has been set for North's trial.
   Hakim is charged with conspiring with his former business
partner, retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Richard V. Secord, North and
former national security adviser John M. Poindexter to illegally
divert proceeds from the arms-for-hostage deals to the Nicaraguan
rebels.
   Additionally, Hakim and Secord are charged with conspiring to
pay illegal gratuities to North, including an offer to create a
fund to finance the college education of the retired Marine
officer's children. Zucker is an unindicted co-conspirator with
Hakim and Secord, according to the court papers.
   The aim of the conspiracy was to ``give things of value'' to
North to encourage him to stay on the National Security Council
staff and help ensure that Hakim and Secord ``would continue to
receive opportunities for substantial revenues and profits in
connection with lucrative activities referred to them by North,''
said the indictment.
   According to the indictment, Zucker traveled to Philadelphia in
March 1986 to discuss the plan with North's wife, Elizabeth.
   Hakim told the congressional committees last year that he
suggested the meeting, relating that Zucker had told Mrs. North an
anonymous admirer of her husband wanted ``to help out with the
university and educational expenses of the children.''
   The congressional committees said they found no evidence the
fund was ever set up, though $15,000 was transferred to an account.
The transmittal order bore Zucker's handwritten notation ``Mrs.
Bellybutton.''
   Hakim's lawyers said that they protested in writing to Walsh and
Zucker after learning late last year that the Geneva-based attorney
was talking to prosecutors. But neither Zucker nor prosecutors
acknowledged such cooperation, the defense said.
   Zucker's cooperation came to light earlier this year in
pre-trial hearings following the indictment.
   ``Mr. Hakim has long utilized the services of Mr. Zucker and CSF
in the conduct of his legal and business affairs,'' defense lawyers
said. ``In so doing, he has often entered into confidential
communications with Mr. Zucker for the purpose of security both
opinions on law and legal services.''
   ``Mr. Hakim has insisted that all communications with respect to
those services remain confidential,'' defense lawyers N. Richard
Janis and Lawrence H. Wechsler said in their pleading.
   The defense claimed that as a Swiss fiduciary, Zucker ``owes
certain duties of loyalty and confidentiality to Mr. Hakim, the
abrogation of which might render him subject to prosecution in
Switzerland.''
</TEXT>
