<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CrashTests     10-13 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash Tests,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NHTSA to Crash Test 34 Vehicles In 1989 Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-four 1989-model autos will be slammed
into a barrier at 35 mph to help the National Highway Traffic
Safety Administration judge how the occupants would fare in the
event of an actual crash.
   All auto models are crash-tested by their manufacturers to
ensure they comply with federal safety standards, but the results
are held secret by the companies.
   The 35 mph test conducted under the government's public
crash-test program, intended as a guide to consumers, is 5 mph
faster than the speed required for compliance with the safety
standards, the agency said Wednesday.
   The results will be measured by dummies wired with instruments
that show the force on the head, chest and upper legs. The dummies
will be protected by seat belts or air bags.
   Passenger cars to be tested under the public crash-test program
are the Audi 80, Chevrolet Caprice, Chrysler Fifth Avenue, Dodge
Daytona, Dodge Spirit, Eagle Medallion, Eagle Premier, Ford Probe,
Ford Thunderbird, Geo Metro 2-door and 4-door, Honda Civic CRX,
Hyundai Sonata, Lincoln Continental, Mercury Tracer, Mitsubishi
Galant, Mitsubishi Mirage, Nissan 240 SX, Nissan Maxima, Peugeot
505, Plymouth Acclaim, Toyota Corolla, Toyota Cressida and
Volkswagen Fox.
   Pickups, vans and multi-purpose passenger vehicles to be tested
are the Chevrolet Astro, Chevrolet S-10 Blazer, Ford Bronco II,
Isuzu Trooper II, Jeep Cherokee, Mazda van, Mitsubishi van, Suzuki
Sidekick, Toyota pickup and Toyota van.
</TEXT>
