<1ST_LINE>r w PM-VAHospitals     10-13 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-VA Hospitals,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>VA Denies it Fudged Hospital Death Data</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Veterans Administration's chief medical
officer denies a published report that he ordered changes in a
study of death rates at VA hospitals to avoid bad publicity.
   ``That is not only grossly inaccurate but is a totally
outrageous accusation,'' John A. Gronvall said of the report in The
Washington Post on Tuesday.
   Gronvall, the VA's chief medical director, said the results of a
sophisticated statistical analysis ``were and are intact.'' The VA
said the methods in the analysis were praised by the General
Accounting Office, the investigative arm of Congress.
   ``The Post accuses me of `directing researchers to produce a
smaller number of questionable hospitals,'' Gronvall said in a
statement issued by the VA. ``I personally initiated this study so
that if we found problems in VA's quality of care we could correct
them.''
   The Post said the initial study had found that as many as 12
percent of VA facilities had excessively high death rates and that
the rate was dropped to just 3.5 percent by using a more rigorous
statistical standard in a revised study.
   The Post said Gronvall acknowledged in an interview that he
ordered VA officials to come up with a lower percentage because he
feared the VA could not withstand the criticism that would follow a
comparison with mortality rates at private hospital.
   Terry L. Thomas, a VA epidemiologist who directed the study, was
quoted by the newspaper as saying she wasn't too happy with it.
   The VA said, however, that she was misquoted.
   ``There was absolutely no pressure applied to me to change
results,'' she is quoted by the VA. ``I never made the remark
attributed to me that I `wasn't too happy' ... or that I saw `too
many red flags.'''
</TEXT>
