<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Plane     10-13 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Plane,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Says Air Traffic Error Possibly Responsible for Close Pass</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal officials are investigating the
possibility that an air traffic control error led a commuter plane
to fly too close to Air Force One while President Reagan was
traveling from Philadelphia to Newark, N.J.
   White House and Federal Aviation Administration officials
stressed that the president was in no danger during the incident
Wednesday afternoon, with the FAA saying the two planes came no
closer than two miles horizontally and 500 feet vertically.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the president was
not aware of the incident until later.
   Fitzwater said the FAA had indicated to White House officials
``that the operational error was related to the air traffic control
system.''
   FAA spokesman Bob Buckhorn said the incident occurred at 2:35
p.m. EDT, northwest of Trenton, N.J.
   ``We're investigating a possible operational error with a Bar
Harbor Airlines aircraft,'' Buckhorn said. ``We are not talking
about a near miss. Preliminary reports indicate there may have been
an operational error.''
   Buckhorn said the error involved a ``separation violation. In
that particular area the separation should have been three miles
and it was allowed to close to two miles.''
   Weinberg said Air Force One pilot Col. Robert Ruddick felt that
no one aboard the presidential plane was endangered.
   Bar Harbor Airlines spokesman Steve Mason said Continental
Express flight 3494, an ATR-42 aircraft, was en route from
Baltimore to Newark with 33 passengers and three crew members
aboard when the incident occurred.
   ``It's our understanding that our airplane was in its normal
flight path when it passed a little over a mile from Air Force One
which was making some sort of change in routing to allow another
aircraft to pass first,'' said Mason. The airline is based in
Bangor, Maine.
   In September 1987, an escort helicopter in Reagan's entourage
headed from New York City to Newark International Airport flew
within 500 feet of a private plane after a communications mixup
kept the copter's pilot from contacting air traffic controllers.
   Earlier this year, an Army private was convicted of lying to
officials investigating an August 1987 incident in which the pilot
entered prohibited airspace and flew too close to a helicopter
carrying Reagan to his ranch near Santa Barbara, Calif.
