<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 0139EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Czechoslovakia     10-13 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Czechoslovakia,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Czechoslovak Government Sworn In</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Czechoslovakia's new premier,
sworn in a day after the most sweeping leadership changes in 20
years, displayed less enthusiasm than his predecessor for reforms
sweeping the Soviet Union.
   Premier Ladislav Adamec was sworn in Wednesday along with his
Cabinet. He replaces Lubomir Strougal, 64, who resigned Monday
after 18 years as premier and also gave up his seat on the ruling
Communist Party Politburo.
   President Gustav Husak, replaced as party chief in December by
Milos Jakes, administered the oath. Husak had led the party since
1968, when Alexander Dubcek was ousted and his liberal ``Prague
Spring'' cut short.
   ``We must carry out the program of restructuring,'' Adamec said
in an acceptance speech, according to a report by the official news
agency CTK. But he added: ``We have no magic wand with which we
could change things overnight.''
   Adamec's remarks appeared to confirm expectations that he would
not have Strougal's enthusiasm for the ``perestroika,'' or
restructuring being promoted by Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev in
his country.
   Czechoslovakia has paid lip service to Gorbachev-style reforms
but has not attempted an extensive overhaul of its economy or
social structure. One of Adamec's first jobs will be to work out a
program for submission to the next session of parliament.
   The country has fared well in comparison to Hungary and Poland,
whose large foreign debts and stagnant economies have reduced
living standards, but economic growth has slowed recently.
   Adamec, a 62-year-old former premier of the Czech Republic and
deputy federal premier, often has criticized poor economic
performance. He said Wednesday the government wants to function as
a ``unified economic center'' with firm control over all branches
of the economy.
   Jakes said Tuesday the Politburo membership had been increased
from 12 to 15 ``temporarily'' to aid in ``restructuring ...
ideological work itself.'' He spoke to the closing session of the
two-day Central Committee meeting at which the personnel changes
were made.
   His speech as reported by CTK emphasized the need to strengthen
the ``leading role of the party.'' He said the leadership must
fight ``shortcomings, bureaucracy, inertia and conservatism'' and
cooperate more closely with the Soviet Union.
   Jan Fojtik, the party's new chief ideologist, said personnel
changes were necessary to change the government's style, overcome
inertia and revamp the sluggish national economy.
   Last April, the Cabinet was reduced from 26 members to the
current 20 by combining several ministries.
   Ten members of Adamec's government are new to the federal
Cabinet, including Jaromir Johanes, who replaced veteran Bohuslav
Chnoupek as foreign minister. Johanes had been Chnoupek's deputy
since July 1987 and previously served as ambassador to Canada and
the United States.
   The Czech and Slovak parliaments chose new premiers Wednesday.
Frantisek Pitra replaced Adamec in the Czech republic and Ivan
Knotek was named in Slovakia to succeed Peter Colotka, who resigned
his government and party posts Monday along with Strougal.
   Pitra and Knotek automatically become deputy federal premiers.
</TEXT>
