<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     10-13 0686</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0717</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kenneth Lain's discovery of a hidden $75,300
treasure while following a trail of cockroaches has officials
bugged.
   Tempe officials have been unable to decide who should get the
money and have asked the Superior Court to make the decision.
   Lain, 25, said he found the money June 12 while hunting bugs in
his rented home here.
   ``I was just getting some chores done and I thought, `I'm really
going to get these guys,''' said the account executive for a credit
bureau. ``I decided to spray under the air-conditioning vent
because it looked buggy under there.''
   When Lain stuck a mirror into the air-conditioning vent to check
on what was inside, he saw a white, dusty bag.
   ``I thought it was a bag of toys some children had left, because
it was quite heavy,'' he said.
   It was full of $10, $20, $50 and $100 bills.
   ``You're filled with adrenalin,'' he said of his reaction.
``You're shaking all over.''
   Under Arizona law, Tempe is required to give the money to ``any
person who makes a valid claim'' if the true owner has not claimed
it within 50 days.
   Receipts from a Chicago restaurant were found in the bag, but
that led investigators nowhere. Investigators also contacted
several previous owners and renters of the house, but nobody knew
where the money came from.
   Fifty days went by, but Lain still could not celebrate.
   His landlord filed a claim with Tempe police, saying that
because the money was found on his property, it belonged to him.
   No hearing date has been set in Maricopa County Superior Court.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ARVADA, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Seuss author Theodore Geisel, who
created such children's best sellers as ``The Cat in The Hat'' and
``Green Eggs and Ham,'' will be getting a creative ``thank you''
from a group of Arvada school children.
   The sixth-graders at Campbell Elementary School are mailing a
book containing Seuss-like characters to the famous author as
thanks for allowing his works to be displayed at Denver's
Children's Museum.
   Six students were selected to create the book because of their
strong writing and illustrating abilities. Among the things they
came up with:
   _The Cusslater, a machine that cleanses the abusive vocabulary
of children who call other children names.
   _The Spitasaurus, which spits on people who spit on their
friends. The Spitasaurus, a rainbow-striped giraffe, gives good
children a ride. But spitters only get a dose of their own bad
behavior.
   _The automatic dresser for teachers, which helps them get ready
more quickly in the morning.
   The monthlong Seuss exhibit here includes more than 300 rough
sketches, paintings, color proofs and posters.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The source of a 13-year-old prank in stained
glass at the University of Washington has been uncovered: The
architect did it.
   University spokesman Tom Griffin says architect David Wright is
responsible for a portrait of George Washington at the school's
Health Sciences cafeteria that bears the inscription, ``Num Me
Vexo?''
   For non-Latin scholars that means, ``What, Me Worry?'' And, yes,
it was inspired by Alfred E. Neuman, the grinning, big-eared symbol
of Mad magazine.
   Wright was the designer of the south campus center where the
stained glass portrait of Washington hangs.
   Griffin's research answered questions raised by a weekly
newspaper story that called ``Num Me Vexo?'' the strangest Latin
inscription in Seattle. Griffin said the inscription came about
because students, who paid for the building in the 1970s, wanted a
picture of a revolutionary there.
   Washington was selected and ``Num Me Vexo?'' was Wright's
contribution. He asked a friend for the Latin translation and had
artist Michael Kennedy add it to the portrait, Griffin said.
   Wright said Wednesday that no questions were raised at the time
of installation, although a university official did ask him about
the window's significance about six months later.
   Wright said he got rid of the official by explaining the
portrait was taken from a $1 bill, while the Latin inscription was
meant to convey confidence in the currency.
   Wright also said he was pleased his joke was finally discovered.
</TEXT>
