<DOCNO> AP881013-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 0141EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Reagan-Quayle Bjt   10-13 0672</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Quayle, Bjt,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Identifies With Quayle's Debate Struggles</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Few know precisely what was said when the
great communicator sat down with the green candidate.
   But one can imagine what happened when President Reagan sat down
to talk privately with embattled vice presidential candidate Dan
Quayle.
   To hear White House chief of staff Kenneth Duberstein tell it,
the president did most of the talking and the senator, running
nationwide for the first time, did most of the listening.
   Duberstein said Quayle had sought out Reagan to get a few tips.
He said the president obliged with delight, inviting the senator to
the White House on the Saturday before his debate with Democrat
Lloyd Bentsen.
   ``I don't think it's so much that he's (Reagan) a mentor, but
Sen. Quayle wanted to talk to the president who had done so well in
debates _ the great communicator _ to get his advice on techniques,
camera angles,'' he said.
   ``They talked generally about what the president had done in his
debates, more so than what Sen. Quayle should do, but what worked
for Reagan,'' Duberstein said, declining to elaborate.
   When Quayle gave a less than dazzling performance last week, few
in public life were more in a position than Reagan to spring to his
defense. The president can look back to the political firestorm he
created in his initial 1984 debate with Democrat Walter F. Mondale
by giving erratic and stumbling answers to several questions.
   Reagan has been dropping Quayle's name incessantly since the
Omaha, Neb., debate. Before that, the president had barely alluded
to the young Indiana senator since he lauded Vice President George
Bush's choice during a campaign rally on Aug. 24 in Los Angeles, a
week after Quayle was selected.
   White House officials sought to minimize notions that Reagan
began speaking out more fiercely for Quayle only after the Omaha
debate. But the presidential speech record and Reagan's own
off-the-cuff remarks show otherwise.
   Reagan, for instance, was quick to assail as ``a cheap shot''
Bentsen's putdown of Quayle's statement comparing himself with John
F. Kennedy.
   When Quayle boasted Wednesday that ``I am my own campaign
handler,'' and said he was breaking away from Bush campaign
managers, Reagan noted that ``very often in a campaign, there's got
to be debate about what's the right thing to do.''
   A similar break occurred after Reagan's spotty performance four
years ago.
   Both Reagan and Quayle emerged from their initial debate tests
with supporters complaining that they had been over-programmed by
their campaign handlers. Reagan broke away from his handlers four
years ago _ as Quayle says he has done now.
   ``What have you done to Ronnie?'' The Washington Post quoted
Nancy Reagan as saying to White House aides when the president left
the Louisville, Ky., stage. Reagan's close friend and confidant,
Paul Laxalt, said that the next time around, ``we will let Reagan
be Reagan.''
   That 1984 faceoff also had stirred up the ``age issue'' _ the
flip side of an issue that has dogged Quayle.
   In Reagan's case, the question was whether the president was too
old for another term, rather than whether he was mature enough to
shoulder this responsibility.
   Quayle's youth seems to intrigue Reagan, who so often has spoken
to audiences of young people as he stumps for Bush and Quayle.
Perhaps he sees Quayle as the ultimate heir to the Reagan
revolution.
   ``Reagan seems to be fascinated'' with Quayle, said Democratic
campaign consultant Robert Keefe. ``He's (Reagan) just a pleasant,
not-too-serious kind of guy. And that description also fits Quayle.
I can see that he and Reagan would get along well.''
   As for Quayle's fondness for Reagan, Keefe said, ``Remember that
he came in to the Senate on Reagan's coattails in the president's
landslide election in Indiana in 1980.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
