<1ST_LINE>r p PM-BlackVote     10-13 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Black Vote,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black Leaders Announce `Get Out The Vote' Campaign</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of black organizations are kicking off
a coast-to-coast tour in an effort to boost the minority vote and
halt Reagan administration policies that they believe have hurt
blacks.
   Minorities can have an effect on the presidential and
congressional elections Nov. 8 ``if our people recognize our stake
in protecting ourselves from the train that is coming down the
track,'' Walter Fauntroy, a Democrat who is the non-voting delegate
from the District of Columbia, said at a news conference Wednesday.
   The campaign is expected to center on at least 15 states and 44
cities, he said, adding that the aim is to convince blacks to
``vote now as never before.''
   Although many of the black leaders' activities will be
non-partisan, the group has received $50,000 from the Democratic
National Committee and includes members from former Democratic
presidential candidate Jesse Jackson's National Rainbow Coalition,
said Fauntroy, who heads the National Black Leadership Roundtable.
   If black voters cannot get excited about voting for Democratic
nominee Michael Dukakis, ``let's get angry about what policies have
been implemented'' by the Reagan administration in the past eight
years, Fauntroy said.
   Blacks must vote ``if for no other reason than to slam the door
on eight years of Reagan-Bush policies that would be continued by a
Bush-Quayle-Reagan administration,'' Fauntroy said.
   Martin Luther King III said church leaders would be involved in
local efforts to back up the black leaders' tour, which is expected
to begin Friday in Baltimore and end Nov. 7 in San Diego, Calif.
   Black leaders are being asked to join the tour that also is to
stop in Pennsylvania, New Jersey, New York, Michigan, Ohio,
Illinois, Tennessee, Virginia, Georgia, North Carolina, Alabama,
Louisiana and Texas. Other states could be added later.
   Comedian and political activist Dick Gregory said his message to
black voters would be simply ``You don't got no choice'' but to
vote.
</TEXT>
