<DOCNO> AP881013-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 0216EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Quayle     10-13 0734</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle's `Break' With Handlers May Be More Style Than Substance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Tops prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MISSOULA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dan Quayle's public break with some of
his handlers in the George Bush camp may be more a matter of style
than substance, but the Republican vice presidential candidate
clearly is exhibiting some independence these days on the campaign
trail.
   The Indiana senator declared Wednesday that he was fed up with
the rigid control and anonymous sniping from Bush aides and is now
``my own handler.''
   ``It was a very controlled environment. I don't operate very
well in a controlled environment,'' Quayle told reporters on his
campaign plane en route here.
   But whether there'll be any real changes in his campaign or
whether _ as the Democrats are suggesting _ this new tack is the
ultimate in handling by master strategist James A. Baker III, is
not yet clear.
   As Quayle travels to Oklahoma and Arkansas today, his campaign
is being watched closely to see what if any changes the candidate
has to offer.
   Quayle has been much more relaxed and accessible to the press
this week than at any previous time in his campaign, chatting with
reporters on his plane and allowing himself to be questioned on an
impromptu basis at campaign stops. But he still has not had a
formal news conference in more than a month.
   On Wednesday, Quayle even started shouting back at hecklers in
Rapid City, S.D., calling them ``SDI naysayers'' when they objected
to his support for the Strategic Defense Initiative.
   On his plane, Quayle cited his SDI comments as an example of his
new ``controlled spontaneity.''
   And he kept up his good-natured jabs at the press, waving a
lethal-looking pick ax he was given at the rally and saying, ``I've
got a few targets for this. Where's the media when I'm looking for
them?''
   Such freewheeling gestures would not have been seen on this
campaign in the past. But they do not necessarily mean true
independence.
   His schedule is still determined by Bush strategists, and even
Quayle said he would continue to read the speeches prepared for
him. Those are cleared, at least in early draft form, by the Bush
campaign.
   His aides, many of them Baker intimates, are openly delighted
that Quayle's declaration of independence has become news.
   They reject the suggestion from Michael Dukakis' camp that the
new Dan Quayle is yet another Baker ploy to prop up a weak
candidate.
   ``Coming from the campaign that has used every ploy in the book
to prop up their own weak candidate at the top of the ticket, they
should know,'' said Quayle's spokesman, David Prosperi.
   Quayle seems delighted at the new turn of events.
   ``I'm going to have fun, and I'm going to say what's on my
mind,'' he said.
   He said he was ``not mad at anybody in the Bush campaign,'' but
he has previously expressed irritation at published reports quoting
unidentified Bush aides as calling him a liability for the ticket.
Over the weekend, he complained to Baker about the sniping.
   Quayle told reporters he will still coordinate with Bush
officials and ``stay in close communication with them.''
   ``They're going to suggest things that I say, suggest things
that I do, and I'm going to take that under consideration,'' he
said.
   ``I've done it their way this far and now it's my turn,'' he
added.
   He stressed that he had cordial relations with Baker, the
campaign chairman. The two men spoke at length on Tuesday night.
Baker said he understands ``why he (Quayle) would be steamed'' over
the sniping by Bush aides.
   Baker also said that anyone caught criticizing Quayle will be
fired.
   ``If I could find out who was putting them out, we'd have fewer
people working in the campaign,'' the Bush campaign chairman said.
``We're going to make a little effort'' to find out who on the
staff provided those anonymous criticisms to the news media.
   Quayle's unhappiness with the sniping came to a head last
Friday, two days after the debate, when anonymous Bush aides were
quoted as saying he had not done well in the debate with Democrat
Lloyd Bentsen and was a liability to the ticket.
   ``I think there is a snapping point that everyone goes through
and it snapped about Friday sometime, last Friday,'' Quayle said.
</TEXT>
