<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Reagan-Politics     10-13 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Politics,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Urges `Reagan Democrats' to Vote Republican Again</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST ORANGE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan is urging those
Democratic voters who put him in the White House to vote again for
the Republican candidate and even consider joining the ranks of the
Grand Old Party.
   Reagan campaigned at a $20-a-plate, Italian-American dinner on
Wednesday, pitching the cause of George Bush and Dan Quayle to
several thousand voters, in an area where many Democrats crossed
party lines to vote for the GOP candidate in 1980 and 1984.
   The president, munching on pasta and salad, beamed amid the rows
and rows of diners as dozens stood to snap his picture and one man
leaped to his feet and boomed out, ``President Reagan, We love
you.''
   The president, never one to shy away from a good audience,
confided in his speech that he wanted ``to tell you something I
have never said before. You know I am a former Democrat.''
   The president loves to regale his fans _ particularly those he
hopes to snare for Bush _ with his own conversion from a follower
of Franklin D. Roosevelt to leader of the nation's conservative
forces.
   ``And it is often said that the once-proud Democratic party of
F.D.R. and Harry Truman is dead and gone _ that the Democratic
Party has been taken over by the left. ... But there is something
you should know _ the party of F.D.R. and Harry Truman couldn't be
killed,'' Reagan said.
   The president argued that ``the party that represents people
like you and me, that represents the majority of Americans, this
party hasn't disappeared _ the fact is we are stronger than ever.''
   ``You see, the secret is, that when the left took over the
Democratic Party, we took over the Republican Party,'' Reagan said,
evoking a round of hearty cheers and lengthy applause from his
audience.
   Reagan boasted that due to this revolution, the Republican Party
has become ``the party of working people, the family, the
neighborhood, the defense of freedom, and, yes, the American flag
and the Pledge of Allegiance to `one nation under God.'''
   ``The party that so many of us grew up with still exists, except
today it's called the Republican Party, and I'm asking all of you
to come home and join me,'' Reagan said.
   Reagan's trip took him to two hotly contested Northeastern
states _ Pennsylvania and New Jersey _ where Bush and Democrat
Michael Dukakis are slugging it out for a combined total of 41
electoral votes.
   After urging a group of high school students to help get out the
vote for Nov. 8 in suburban Philadelphia earlier in the day, Reagan
attended a Republican fund-raising reception and had lunch with
Archbishop Anthony J. Bevilacqua of Philadelphia.
   He then flew to New Jersey for another fund-raiser in Newark
before attending the Italian-American event in West Orange.
   Asked at one point how important the Bush-Dukakis debate tonight
will be, the president replied: ``I think we have to wait and see
the debate. I know who the winner is already.''
   Federal Aviation Administration officials said that as Reagan
was en route to New Jersey, Air Force One and a commuter plane may
have flown too close to one another, but the president was in no
danger.
   The president's plane and a Bar Harbour Airlines plane came no
closer than two miles horizontally and 500 feet vertically, but
should have been three miles apart, said FAA spokesman Bob
Buckhorn. The FAA is investigating the incident, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
