<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Islam     10-13 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Islam,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Islam Information Ministers Want Different World View of Moslems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JIDDAH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Information ministers from 43
Islamic lands met for two days at this Red Sea port with the
objective of removing barriers to the non-Moslem world and of
improving the exchange of news among themselves.
   The director general of the Islamic Educational, Scientific and
Cultural Organization, Professor Abdelhadi Boutaleb, told the
ministers that the world's estimated 800 million Moslems must be
educated against outside influences that included ``foreign media''
characterizations of ``backwardness, ignorance and fanaticism as
the main features of our peoples.''
   However, the communique issued at the end of the conference _
attended by representatives from all the nations within the Islamic
Conference Organization except Iran and the Maldives _ barely noted
concern over anti-Moslem sentiment.
   It endorsed instead known Moslem views on Palestinian
self-determination, Lebanon, Afghanistan, South African apartheid,
an Iran-Iraq peace accord and other issues.
   The communique, without mentioning Iran by name, singled out
that country for harsh criticism for activities detrimental to
Islam's image.
   It said the meeting ``expressed its opposition to extremism and
violence which have projected Islam as though it were a religion of
bloodshed, war, dissension and violation of mosques and other
peaceful places of worship.''
   The reference in part appeard to be to the riots last year
involving Iranian pilgrims to Mecca in which more than 400 people
died.
   Sharifuddin Pir Zadeh, the Pakistani secretary-general of the
Organization of Islamic Conference, complained at a closed session
on Tuesday that reports from Western news agencies ``ignore or
deliberately distort'' Islamic issues.
   Saudi Arabia does not as a rule grant entry to foreign
journalists. Western news agencies appeared to be the only outside
media allowed to cover the conference, except for a U.S. television
crew from Cairo.
</TEXT>
