<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Debate-Scene     10-13 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Debate-Scene,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush, Dukakis Tour UCLA Debate Site</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The lecterns, stage and backdrop were
familiar fixtures for George Bush and Michael Dukakis as they made
their separate ways today around Pauley Pavilion, the UCLA
basketball arena quickly turned into a forum for a presidential
contest.
   The two candidates were each visiting the hall today for about
90 minutes _ the length of tonight's second and final presidential
debate _ to get acquainted with the surroundings and the doubly
backed-up sound systems.
   Moderator Bernard Shaw and the three panelists, whose
microphones had only one backup, were also holding a practice
session of their own and were counting on having time enough to
fire off at least 22 questions.
   To make sure that the television lighting was uninterrupted
along with the sound, organizers of the event made sure that every
fixture aiming a TV spotlight had a backup light, said Ed Fouhy,
executive producer of the bipartisan Commission on Presidential
Debates.
   Fouhy said Wednesday that preparations had gone fairly smoothly
since UCLA was selected last Friday for the debate site because it
was ``a big time university with a big time staff.''
   The 34,000-student university is accustomed to mega-events,
having hosted gymnastic competition for the 1984 Olympics as well
as serving as the Olympic village to house the athletes. Last
year's visit by Britain's visiting Prince Andrew and the Duchess of
York was another exercise in tight security and logistics.
   The sprawling, palm tree-dotted University of California campus
was chosen after the League of Women Voters withdrew as debate
sponsor in a dispute with the Bush and Dukakis campaigns. The
league had planned to hold the debate in the old Shrine Auditorium.
   The debates commission, established by both campaigns to handle
the first presidential debate in Winston-Salem, N.C., on Sept. 25,
and the vice presidential debate last week, was asked to sponsor
the Los Angeles event.
   With the commission sponsorship came the red-carpeted stage, the
deep blue backdrop and oak lecterns that were inaugurated in
Winston-Salem. The fixtures were trucked in straight from Omaha,
Neb., where they were used for the debate between Lloyd Bentsen and
Dan Quayle.
   On Wednesdady, the Los Angeles City Council voted 11-2 to give
$25,000 to help fund the debate. Among those dissenting was
Councilman Ernani Bernardi, who said ``I would have supported it if
it was open to the public.''
   As it stands, the audience of 1,500 people in the 12,000-seat
arena will consist of selected Republicans and Democrats as the
debate is played out for the more important television viewers.
   The basketball court was carpeted in blue and partitioned off to
create a cozier atmosphere and better TV look.
   Debate commission director Janet Brown said Wednesday she has
collected at least $350,000 in private donations to help offset the
$500,000-plus cost of the debate. The largest commitment was
$100,000 from the Times-Mirror Corp.
</TEXT>
