<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Burma     10-13 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two New Political Parties Form</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two more political parties have registered
with the government, but diplomats say pro-democracy forces now may
be too splintered to defeat the ruling party in national elections.
   State-run Radio Rangoon said Wednesday that the Union Karen
League and the United Peace Democracy Party registered with the
election commission, bringing the number of new parties to 14.
   The Union Karen League is the first party representing an ethnic
minority.
   The Karen, one of a dozen major ethnic minority groups among
Burma's 38 million people, number about 2 million. Karen guerrillas
have been fighting the central government for more than four
decades.
   Upon seizing power Sept. 18, a military government under
hard-liner Gen. Saw Maung suppressed anti-government demonstrations
but declared it would allow the formation of political parties and
general elections in about three months.
   Western diplomats in Rangoon say the sudden emergence of small,
weak opposition parties rather than one united group may spell
defeat for pro-democracy forces.
   The opposition groups will face the National Unity Party, which
under a different name has ruled for 26 years. Saw Maung's
government says the party is no longer synomymous with the state
and arrangements are reportedly being made to transfer state-owned
buildings, funds and vehicles once held by the party back to the
government.
   Western diplomats and some opposition leaders say they doubt
free and fair elections can be held under current circumstances. By
the government's own admission, about 450 people have been killed
since Sept. 18 in Saw Maung's drive to quell demonstrations.
   The nationwide uprising against the repressive government began
in late July and involved massive street protests, a general strike
and a bloody backlash in which army troops killed hundreds.
   While Rangoon has remained relatively calm in recent days,
thousands of students have fled to the Thai-Burmese border, seeking
refuge and military training from the Karen and other ethnic
minorities up in arms against the Rangoon government.
   The minorities have been fighting for greater autonomy from the
central government and have announced their support for the
pro-democracy side.
   Rebel officials say about 9,000 students and others have joined
their side and some are being given basic guerrilla training at
bases along the frontier.
   Karen leader Gen. Bo Mya has said his insurgent group, the Karen
National Union, has 17,000 troops.
</TEXT>
