<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 0110EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Haiti     10-13 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Haiti,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Considers Filing Charges Against Ex-Mayor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Authorities say they are
investigating the former mayor of Port-au-Prince for allegedly
masterminding the massacre of worshipers during a Sept. 11 church
service.
   The slaughter at the St. Jean Bosco Roman Catholic Church came
shortly before a coup by rank-and-file soldiers against the
government of Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy, who was forced into exile.
   Franck Romain, the mayor of this capital city, sought refuge in
the Dominican Embassy during the purge.
   Coup leaders said they were revolted by the massacre and accused
Romain and Namphy of engineering it. St. Jean Bosco's pastor was a
frequent critic of the Namphy government.
   Hospital officials say at least 12 parishoners were killed and
70 wounded when thugs armed with knives and guns randomly shot and
stabbed parishioners. The government and radio stations have put
the number of dead at 13.
   Yves Barbot, second-in-command at the Ministry of Justice, said
Wednesday that the government had ``initiated penal action against
Franck Romain and his accomplices.'' But he said it was premature
to say whether Romain would be tried.
   Barbot said the magistrate handling the case had three months to
decide to indict Romain.
   Romain was elected mayor in fraud-ridden elections run by Namphy
on Jan. 17. During the 29-year Duvalier family dictatorship, Romain
served as police chief and army colonel.
   Prosecutor Jacaman Charles said in an interview with the Voice
of America, broadcast in Haiti Tuesday, that Romain would soon be
summoned to appear in court, but he did not say when.
   President Joaquin Balaguer of the Dominican Republic said
earlier this month that the Haitian government has refused to issue
an exit visa to Romain.
   Arnold Antonin, head of the National Network for the Defense of
Human Rights, said Wednesday that indictment of Romain would be the
first step toward demanding his extradition from the Dominican
Embassy. Haiti and the Dominican Republic share the Caribbean
island of Hispaniola.
</TEXT>
