<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Zimbabwe-SpyTrial     10-13 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Zimbabwe-Spy Trial,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alleged Agents Deny Murder, Terrorism Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANGUS SHAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three alleged South African agents have
pleaded innocent to charges of murder, terrorism and sabotage in
connection with a car bomb attack on African National Congress
officials.
   The three Zimbabwean nationals _ two whites and a black _ on
Wednesday denied involvement in the Jan. 11 car bombing outside a
house in Bulawayo, administrative capital of western Matabeleland
province and Zimbabwe's second-largest city.
   The explosion killed the man driving the car and seriously
injured an unnamed ANC official inside the house. The ANC is the
main guerrilla organization fighting the white-minority government
in neighboring South Africa.
   Paramilitary police armed with automatic weapons patrolled the
High Court building in downtown Harare as the defendants _ Kevin
Woods, 36, Michael Smith, 34, and Philip Conjwayo, 54 _ were
brought to the hearing in a convoy of armored cars escorted by
troops with submachine guns.
   Acting Attorney-General Andrew Chigovera told Judge President
Wilson Sandura an unemployed man hired to drive the booby-trapped
Renault 5 car died in the blast and one unnamed ANC official among
six occupants of the house in the Bulawayo suburb of Trenance was
seriously injured.
   Chigovera said Woods resigned as a member of Zimbabwe's Central
Intelligence Organiztion security police in 1986, three years after
South African security services recruited him to gather information
on South African refugees living in Zimbabwe.
   Smith is a former soldier in the Rhodesian Light Infantry and
Conjwayo was a onetime agent of the Rhodesian Special Branch.
   The prosecutor said the state will provide evidence Conjwayo
hired Obert Mwanza at a Bulawayo employment agency to drive a
Renault 5 saloon car wired with explosives to the suburban house.
The explosives were allegedly detonated by Smith in a nearby car
using a remote control device, killing Mwanza.
   The three defendants were arrested Jan. 15.
   The state named 16 witnesses it will call in the first major
trial against alleged South African agents since white-ruled
Rhodesia became black-governed Zimbabwe April 18, 1980.
   The uprecedented security cordon at the courthouse follows an
attempt June 30 by alleged South African commandos to free the
Zimbabweans on their way to a remand hearing from Chikurubi Maximum
security prison near the capital Harare.
   A stolen Zimbabwe airforce helicopter was used in the abortive
rescue bid.
</TEXT>
