<1ST_LINE>r w PM-LateCongress 1stLd-Writethru a0428 10-13 0586</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Late Congress, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0428,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>This Congress Just Can't Say Go</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, bgng House Speaker, to correct Foley's
title; picks up 4th graf, Over in</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LEE GOULD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 100th Congress, the reluctant Congress,
isn't quite ready to go home.
   Despite growing election pressures to get home and campaign,
Congress may have to remain in town into next week to deal with the
year's hottest campaign topic _ drug abuse and the war against it.
   House Majority Leader Tom Foley, D-Wash., delivered the bad news
to anxious-to-campaign colleagues Wednesday night. ``It is doubtful
the drug bill will be ready to be voted on before next Tuesday or
Wednesday,'' he told groaning House members at a night session.
   Over in the Senate, Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va.,
tried late Wednesday night to get agreement on how to proceed with
the bill. His plan wasn't even out of his mouth before Sen. William
Armstrong, R-Colo., interrupted to say he would be ``dumbfounded''
if Byrd could get everyone to agree to any single plan of attack.
   Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas warned that at the rate the
Senate was moving, ``we're going to need a week and half more on
the drug bill. ''
   ``I'm not running this year. I'll be right here,'' Dole added.
   ``The best thing we can do for the country is to shut the
Congress down and go home and make the people safe until next
January,'' said Sen. Jake Garn, R-Utah.
   Even if the Senate passes the massive bill by Friday, Foley said
it would take days to iron out differences between the Senate and
House versions. That would propel the Congress into the third week
of October.
   Election Day for all 435 House seats, and 33 Senate seats, will
be only three weeks away next Tuesday. Members of the House and
Senate had hoped to be back home by early October, or this coming
weekend at the latest.
   Instead, with the weekend approaching, the Senate spent much of
the day in repeated recesses and time-eating quorum calls. That
left the Senate floor free for senators to come in and talk about
issues dear to their hearts, their states or both.
   In fact, Congress could have gone home at midnight Friday, Sept.
30, the end of fiscal 1988. At that time, it finished work on the
13 appropriation bills needed to keep the government operating
through fiscal 1989. No must-pass legislation remained.
   But the session resumed the following week, working on what
members refer to as ``cats and dogs,'' non-pressing bills of
particular interest to individual members. This week, the Senate
passed a tax bill, but even that faces a tough battle in
negotiations with the House.
   Looking at the 100-odd amendments to the drug bill, Byrd told
his colleagues he understood the ``proclivity on the part of
senators to try to load everything onto these last-minute trains
that are leaving the station.''
   ``I hope we will not let this debate on the drug bill
deteriorate into a political sideshow where we will all be taking
political potshots, where we will be trying to indicate who can be
the toughest, and who can be the John Wayne of the drug war,'' Byrd
said.
   He urged fellow senators to try to limit amendments, ``then, say
no more amendments, just debate this bill, and go home.''
   Across the Capitol, Foley told reporters, ``We are watching with
interest what the Senate is doing.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
