<HEAD>Energy, Ecology Officials Defend Controversial Nuclear Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government says it will fire up Mexico's
first nuclear power plant next week, but critics are demanding a
national referendum on the twin-reactor project.
   Jose Luis Alcudia, the assistant energy secretary, told the
Chamber of Deputies on Wednesday that the Laguna Verda reactor is
ready for low-level operational testing.
   Officials maintained that the plant poses no threat to the
environment and that testing would begin next week.
   ``The environmental controls of the nuclear plant are
guaranteed,'' assistant ecology secretary Sergio Reyes Lujan told
the chamber.
   But opposition lawmakers disputed their testimony and called on
the government to hold a national referendum on the plant.
   The plant, 200 miles east of Mexico City in Veracruz state, has
been ready for the loading of radioactive fuel since December,
according to the federal Electricity Commission.
   But President Miguel de la Madrid postponed the start-up in an
apparent attempt to calm protests by environmental groups and to
minimize the issue during Veracruz state's municipal elections.
   The elections, held Oct. 2, were largely won by the ruling
Institutional Revolutionary Party. Newspapers have since carried a
flurry of unconfirmed reports that the loading is imminent.
   Officials of the Energy Department, state-owned Federal
Electricity Commission and Urban Development and Ecology Department
spoke to senators on Tuesday and testified in the Chamber of
Deputies on Wednesday.
   Alcudia said the plant is part of a long-range plan to diversify
energy sources.
   The first of the two 657-megawatt reactors is ready for
low-level power tests and that there are no technical obstacles to
loading fuel, he said.
   Sen. Porfirio Munoz Ledo of the leftist National Democratic
Front and leaders of the Group of 100, an ecological group of
artists and intellectuals, walked out of Tuesday's session, the
newspaper La Jornada said.
   Munoz Ledo questioned the economics of the plant considering the
decline in income from oil exports. He also questioned the safety
of the plant.
   ``Why the rush to load the reactor?'' he asked.
   Construction on the plant began in 1973. The second of the two
reactors is to be ready by 1991.
</TEXT>
