<HEAD>Dukakis Upbeat and Optimistic for Debate with Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Walk through of debate hall at 3:30 p.m. EDT; May stand for
PMs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis debates presidential rival
George Bush for the second and final time tonight in what could
prove the crucial test of whether the Democrat can reassert himself
in the race for the White House.
   Dukakis was spending most of today in final preparation for the
showdown, taking a brief afternoon break to visit the University of
California at Los Angeles auditorium where he and the Republican
vice president will meet face-to-face at 9 p.m. EDT in a nationally
broadcast encounter.
   Dukakis has been loose and upbeat heading into the debate
despite the widely held belief that a strong performance is vital
to his hopes of overcoming what polls show is a close horserace but
a strong Bush lead in the Electoral College count.
   ``We're going to win, period,'' was the Massachusetts governor's
optimistic assessment Wednesday when asked if he thought it
possible that he would win the popular vote but lose the presidency
to Bush in the electoral count.
   That comment came during a game of catch with press secretary
Dayton Duncan, during which Dukakis, using baseball metaphors,
joked about his planned repertoire for the debate.
   ``Fastball, curve, slider _ maybe a knuckler,'' he said when
asked what he planned to throw at Bush tonight.
   Candidates and aides generally try to lower their expectations
going into a debate but Dukakis predicted a win.
   ``We're ahead 2-0 and we're going to make it a clean sweep,'' he
said, claiming victory in his prior debate with Bush and the recent
matchup between the vice presidential nominees, Democrat Lloyd
Bentsen and Republican Dan Quayle.
   Quayle, the conservative Indiana senator, will be a prime
Dukakis target in tonight's encounter, with the Democratic nominee
looking to both question Quayle's qualifications to step in as
president and Bush's judgment in selecting the 41-year-old senator.
   ``Gingerly,'' Dukakis said with a broad grin when asked how Bush
should handle debate questions about Quayle.
   Aides said Dukakis also planned aggressive responses to any
questions about the Massachusetts prison furlough system, a
favorite Bush target in his effort to paint Dukakis as soft on
crime.
   Dukakis aides believe their candidate has gained some momentum
in recent weeks, particularly through the vice presidential debate,
and hope a strong performance tonight will give Dukakis a boost to
carry him through the final 25 days of the campaign.
   In that period Dukakis will target the Northeast, the industrial
heartland, the West Coast and selected Southern, border and Midwest
and Rocky Mountain states in hope of breaking the GOP's electoral
lock.
   ``I think you see a scenario, a very reasonable, rational
scenario, that indicates this thing is nowhere near over,'' said
senior Dukakis adviser Ron Brown, who said most targeting decisions
would be made within a few days after the debate.
   Dukakis was attending a rally with supporters after the debate
and also attending two private receptions. He was campaigning
Friday in California and Washington state, including a joint
appearance with Bentsen in Sacramento.
</TEXT>
