<1ST_LINE>r p PM-VermontGovernor Bjt   10-13 0703</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vermont Governor, Bjt,0722</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Despite Successes, Kunin Faces Tough Re-election Race</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER GRAFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Madeleine Kunin couldn't ask for a
better backdrop as she seeks a third two-year term: the nation's
lowest unemployment rate, surging revenues and a doubling of state
aid to schools in four years.
   Yet, Kunin's re-election next month is not assured.
   The Democratic incumbent is favored to defeat Republican Michael
Bernhardt for the two-year post, but a poll for Bernhardt last
month found one-third of the voters undecided, with Kunin leading
Bernhardt 38-32 percent.
   Of even greater concern to Kunin was the fact that, according to
the survey, the number of people who disapproved of her performance
had climbed to 38 percent.
   The governor has belatedly acknowledged that the challenge by
Bernhardt is more serious than first anticipated. ``I think this is
going to be closer than what most people think,'' Kunin said
recently.
   Close elections are nothing new for Kunin. The state's first
female governor was elected in 1984, narrowly defeating the
then-attorney general by gaining 50.02 percent of the vote.
   Two years ago, she gained 47 percent of the vote in a three-way
race and forced the election into the Legislature, as the
Constitution requires when no one receives a majority of the
popular vote.
   Kunin believes Bernhardt's inroads have come through negative
campaigning. ``It has an effect in every race,'' she said. ``I
think we have seen that nationally. I don't think I am immune.''
   But Bernhardt believes his campaign is catching on because
Vermonters are tired of being told what to do by the state. The
centerpiece of his campaign is a pledge to erase many of the rules
and regulations drawn up during the Kunin administration.
   ``The role of state government is a helping hand, not an iron
fist,'' said Bernhardt as he and Kunin met last week in their first
televised debate.
   To Bernhardt the election is a ``referendum on what Vermonters
want as a form of government. Do we want a continuation of the
direction you have taken us in, state control, big state spending,
more mandates, or do we want a government founded on people?''
   This is Bernhardt's first bid for statewide office. A
businessman from Londonderry, he has served in the Vermont House
for eight years, most recently as the Republican leader.
   Kunin says she is proud of what her administration has
accomplished and believes she will do well if she can ``get the
word out on what we have done,'' especially in the area of the
environment and education.''
   ``I am glad I am a strong environmentalist; that I have put my
neck out on these laws and I am going to fight to put them there
and not backtrack,'' she said.
   Chief among the environmental successes cited by the governor is
a highly controversial law adopted this year designed to ease
development pressures in this state of 548,000 people.
   Passage of the law stemmed from growing fears among many that
development, primarily vacation homes and resorts, was threatening
to destroy the small-town simplicity of the nation's most rural
state.
   Bernhardt, although supportive of the growth law in concept, has
tried to tap Vermonters' love of the small town by painting the
Kunin growth bill as an attempt to rob local governments of their
powers.
   He says the law gives too much say over local planning to
regional planning commissions and the state. Kunin disputes that,
saying towns can elect whether or not to participate in the
planning.
   Kunin's greatest asset is the strength of Vermont's economy.
Vermont, with its small population, has always had a very high per
capita tax burden. New England's recent economic boom has changed
that, raising income and lowering tax burden. Even so, state
coffers are so full that aid to education has doubled in four years.
   The latest unemployment rate was 1.7 percent, the lowest ever
recorded by a state under the present calculation system and the
nation's best.
   ``I'm proud of what we have done,'' said Kunin. ``We have gone
from deficit to surplus; we have a record low unemployment rate,
and we have done it all while protecting our environment.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
