<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>K mart Recalls Toys</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   K mart is recalling two types of squeeze toys
and some telephone-shaped rattles which could pose choking hazards
for children.
   The Consumer Product Safety Commission said Wednesday some
81,000 ``Baby's First Squeeze Toys'' and about 75,000 ``Baby's
First Playball'' squeeze toys, plus about 33,000 plastic
``Telephone Receiver Rattles'' are being recalled.
   All three products went on sale in late 1987, the agency said.
The squeeze toys cost about $1 and the rattles $2. Parents were
urged to remove all three toys from use and to return them to K
mart for a refund.
   Baby's First Squeeze Toy came in three shapes: telephone
receiver, barbell and dumbbell, while the playball came in the form
of a baseball, basketball or soccer ball.
   Persons needing more information can call the Safety Commission
at 1-800-638-2772.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Superpowers Plan Disinformation `Hotline,' USIA Chief Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American and Soviet officials are setting up a
``hotline'' to prevent accusations against each other's countries
from escalating into worldwide propaganda campaigns, Charles Z.
Wick, head of the U.S. Information Agency said.
   ``Agreement to work toward the establishment of an `early
warning system''' to challenge disinformation was among the results
of U.S.-Soviet information talks in Moscow Sept. 26-28, said Wick.
   The ``early warning system'' would be ``designed to give the
United States a mechanism to challenge disinformation efforts
before they become part of a worldwide campaign,'' Wick said in a
speech Wednesday at the National Press Club.
   Wick said the Soviets have ``curtailed dramatically''
circulation of disinformation, but recalled hearing only a few days
ago a Moscow Radio broadcast about ``Western countries buying
children from impoverished South American countries and treating
them as slaves.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
