<DOCNO> AP881013-0064 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 0324EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     10-13 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Stocks Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar plunged against the Japanese yen and
most major currencies in Tokyo on Thursday while share prices
dipped on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   After opening at 127.90 yen, sharply down from the previous
day's close of 129.65, the dollar moved in a range of 127.75-128.35
yen. It closed at 127.98 yen, down 1.67 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, the main index
in the Tokyo Stock Exchange, lost 136.07 points, or 0.50 percent,
to close at 27,273.30.
   Exchange dealers attributed the dollar's decline to market
perceptions that the U.S. economy was slowing down and to
nervousness over the August U.S. trade report scheduled to be
released later Thursday in Washington.
   ``The market appears to be over-reacting a bit, but there were
various elements since last week which could push the dollar
down,'' said Toshikazu Kotoge, a dealer at Yasuda Trust Bank in
Tokyo.
   Kotoge cited the lower-than-expected level of U.S. employment
rates released last week and growing speculation that the U.S.
trade deficit was worsening as negative elements affecting the
market last week.
   Kyodo News Service quoted Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa as
saying the yen's appreciation had been ``somewhat too steep.
   ``If the fluctuation is too wide for one day, it better be tamed
down,'' Miyazawa was quoted as saying.
   Miyazawa denied speculation that the United States had changed
its policy of favoring a dollar stronger than the current levels,
Kyodo reported.
   But dealers said it was unlikely the dollar would dip below the
125-yen level, as market players were likely to start buying the
dollar at that rate.
   The dollar's opening Thursday morning was the lowest since June
22, when the currency opened trading at 126.70 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, securities dealers said
uncertainties in the foreign exchange market sidelined investors.
   ``Most export-oriented shares are down because of the strong
yen, but domestic shares are doing all right,'' said Ichitaro
Watanabe of Nikko Securities Co. ``But either way, the market is
not going to move too much today (Thursday) ahead of the release of
U.S. trade numbers.''
</TEXT>
