<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Sundstrand Bjt   10-13 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sundstrand, Bjt,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contractor Agrees To $115 Million Settlement For Defrauding
Pentagon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A defense contractor agreed to a $115 million
fine in the largest Pentagon fraud settlement after admitting it
billed the Defense Department for things like babysitting, country
clubs and servants for its executives, officials said.
   In agreeing to plead guilty to defrauding the Pentagon by
overbilling for airplane parts, Sundstrand Corp. also said its
employees wined and dined Defense Department officials and then
submitted those expenses for reimbursements, U.S. prosecutors said
Wednesday.
   No company or Pentagon employee has been charged in the
overbillings, which spanned from 1980-86, but Sundstrand agreed to
cooperate with investigators, said U.S. Attorney Anton Valukas. The
investigation should be completed by January, said Valukas, who
declined to estimate how much Sundstrand's actions cost the
government.
   ``It was the object of the conspiracy to improve Sundstrand's
ability to market hardware to the Defense Department by giving
gratuities to Defense Department personnel and their spouses while
concealing (their) identity,'' the government said.
   Sundstrand employees gave an estimated $100,000 worth of liquor,
meals, motel rooms, golf outings and tickets to the theater,
hockey, football and baseball games, the government said. They then
submitted expense reports identifying the Defense Department
workers they entertained only as a ``customer'' or ``government
employee,'' the complaint said.
   Some government employees are being investigated for allegedly
accepting the gratuities, said Larry Wilson, a spokesman for the
department's Defense Logistics Agency.
   The company also admitted it submitted fraudulent claims to the
Defense Department for what it called ``general and administrative
costs'' on its contracts.
   These claims included millions of dollars in unallowable costs
for such things as ``liquor, babysitting, gifts, travel by
executives' spouses, cigarettes, candy, saunas, golf, tennis,
country club dues, movies, jewelry, clothes, ... snowplowing at
executives' homes, radar detectors, ... entertainment, ... and
servants for executives and their spouses,'' the government said.
   Evans W. Erikson, Sundstrand chairman and chief executive
officer, said in a statement the agreement to plead guilty at an
undetermined date was a ``major step toward putting this
unfortunate chapter behind the company.''
   Sundstrand makes flight-data equipment and other electronic
equipment for military and commercial aircraft. It also makes the
``black box'' equipment installed on aircraft to preserve flight
information in the event of a crash.
   Rockford-based Sundstrand had set aside $130 million in
anticipation of settling the federal investigations, said company
spokesman Claude Vernam.
   Sundstrand said it already had paid or agreed to pay a total of
$127.3 million to settle overbillings in Illinois and Washington
state.
   The Defense Department accounts for 42 percent of Sundstrand's
$1.4 billion in annual sales, and Sundstrand acknowledged that it
could be suspended or barred from future work on federal contracts.
   ``What you have, in a sense, is a tragedy,'' Valukas said at a
news conference. ``You have a company that set out to defraud the
government.
   ``The only way that type of activity can be deterred is through
swift legal action,'' Valukas said.
   The penalty set for the company is the largest single Pentagon
fraud settlement ever, Valukas said.
   The previous record was in March, when Bell Helicopter Textron
Inc. agreed to return $90 million to the government to settle
allegations it fraudulently overcharged the Army on helicopter
spare parts, according to the Pentagon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881013-0067 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 0353EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Philippines-Marcos     10-13 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Marcos,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aquino Says No Fixed Timetable For Charging Marcos</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Philippines will file criminal
charges against Ferdinand Marcos for alleged offenses committed in
office but no specific time had been set, President Corazon Aquino
said today.
   Mrs. Aquino also said Marcos, who was president of the
Philippines for 20 years but fled to exile in Hawaii in 1986, will
be allowed to return to the Philippines to answer the charges.
   Mrs. Aquino issued a statement to reporters one day after a
Filipino official indicated the government might delay filing
charges against the ousted president until U.S. authorities decide
whether to prosecute him.
   ``Sometime in the future, we will file a criminal case or cases
against Mr. Marcos,'' Mrs. Aquino said. ``At that time, we will
have to allow him to return to face the trial. No definite time
frame can be given as of now for this.''
   The Philippine government alleges Marcos and his associates
stole up to $10 billion before his administration was toppled in
the 1986 uprising that swept Mrs. Aquino to power.
   Filipino officials have filed no criminal charges against Marcos
for fear he would demand his right to return home for trial.
Philippine law bars criminal trials in absentia.
   On Tuesday, the Los Angeles Times said the U.S. State
Department's legal officer, Abraham Sofaer, recommended Marcos be
offered a deal to avoid prison by surrendering millions of dollars
allegedly embezzled during 20 years in power.
   The newspaper said U.S. officials feared Marcos would seek to
embarrass American and Filipino authorities by disclosing improper
or illegal conduct if he were indicted.
   The plea bargain proposal reportedly involves an investigation
of Marcos by U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani in New York into
alleged illegal money transfers and other activities.
   On Wednesday, Mateo Caparas, chairman of the Presidential
Commission on Good Government, said the Aquino administration would
not ``seek to obstruct justice in other lands'' or permit filing of
charges here ``to be used as an excuse by Mr. Marcos to escape his
indictment abroad.''
   Caparas said efforts by Marcos to return were ``either an excuse
to get out of America or a part of his campaign to destabilize the
present government.'' The official said Marcos could face charges
here even if he accepted a U.S. plea bargain.
   Caparas' commission is in charge of recovering money allegedly
taken by Marcos. He told reporters that Mrs. Aquino had asked him
to issue the statement.
   Mrs. Aquino has repeatedly refused to allow Marcos to return to
the Philippines, citing national security.
   Today, Mrs. Aquino said she was confident that her government
would ``be able to handle the return of Mr. Marcos when the time
for it comes.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
