<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Germany-Auschwitz     10-13 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Auschwitz,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Warns Against Holocaust Comparisons with Other
Atrocities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Richard von Weizsaecker
is urging fellow West Germans to recall the horrors of Auschwitz,
rejecting attempts to compare the Nazi Holocaust with other
atrocities in human history.
   ``What is it supposed to mean for us, whether Auschwitz can
stand up to a comparison of the horrifying destruction of other
peoples?'' Weizsaecker said in the northern Bavarian city of
Bamberg on Wednesday.
   ``Auschwitz remains unique. It happened in the name of the
Germans, by Germans. This truth is irrefutable, and it won't be
forgotten,'' he said.
   In recent years, West Germans have come to use the name of the
Nazis' Auschwitz death camp synonymously with the Holocaust.
   Weizsaecker addressed a national conference of prominent
historians, as towns and cities across West Germany plan solemn
ceremonies marking the 50th anniversary of the infamous 1938
``Crystal Night'' violence aimed against Jews.
   The comments by the highly popular West German president on
Wednesday marked the first time he has entered a bitter public
debate over whether the Nazi killings of 6 million Jews and
hundreds of thousands of others stand alone in history.
   Conservative historians led by Ernst Nolte of West Berlin argue
the Holocaust can be ``relativized'' by comparisons with
Stalinist-era atrocities and other mass-killings in history.
   Jewish leaders angrily claim the conservative historians'
ultimate goal is to diminish the horrors of Adolf Hitler's Nazi
regime in the eyes of future generations.
   Speaking of the Nazi era, the 68-year-old president said: ``It
(Germany) was led by criminals, and it let itself be led by
criminals.''
   ``It (the German people) knows this, especially where it would
rather not know,'' he said in a copy of the speech distributed to
the news media by his office in Bonn.
   During the Nazi era, Weizsaecker's father, Ernst von
Weizsaecker, was the No. 2 official in the Foreign Ministry and was
sent to prison for his conviction at one of the Nuremberg war
crimes trials. However, the president often has defended his father
in public, saying he did his best to head off World War II.
   The West German president spoke exactly four weeks before the
50th anniversary of ``Crystal Night,'' when hundreds of Jewish
synagogues were burned down, thousands of Jewish homes and
businesses plundered, and 30,000 Jews sent to concentration camps.
   It took the name ``Crystal Night'' because of the shards of
broken glass during the action Nov. 9-10, 1938. German Jewish
leaders have begun referring to it as the ``Pogrom Night,'' saying
that is a more appropriate word for it.
   Commemorative plaques are being erected at important Jewish
buildings, panel discussions are being held and a major ceremony is
scheduled in Frankfurt to mark the 50th anniversary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881013-0070 </DOCNO>
