<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Koreas 1stLd-Writethru   10-13 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Koreas, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0484,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North, South Korea Resume Standoff</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout with details of talks, comments; no pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South and North Korean delegations met
for the first time since the Olympics today, but failed to make
progress in their efforts to find ways to reunite their divided
land.
   Each side accused the other of blocking progress during the
two-hour meeting, but agreed to resume talks on Nov. 17.
   ``The northern side took an insincere stand throughout, and
there was no progress,'' Lee Han-dong, a South Korean delegate,
told a news conference.
   ``The South's position was basically the same as before and they
made no concessions at all,'' said the chief North Korean
negotiator, Chon Kum Chol.
   Today's meeting was aimed at arranging formal talks between the
two Koreas' legislatures on reuniting the peninsula.
   North Korea, slightly revising its earlier stand, suggested that
the proposed legislative talks include one-third of the lawmakers
from the north, or 218 people, and one-half of the south's
lawmakers, or 150 people.
   South Korea came up with a new proposal calling for largely
ceremonial opening and closing ceremonies attended by all members
of the two sides' legislatures and a smaller ``select'' committee
charged with actual negotiations.
   Previously, North Korea had called for a joint meeting of the
nearly 1,000 members of the two sides' parliaments. South Korea has
sought a smaller meeting, saying it would allow for more practical
negotiations.
   The nations first began discussions on Aug. 21 on possible
formal talks between their parliaments, but made no major progress
in four meetings. In the fourth session on Aug. 26, each accused
the other of blocking agreement, but they agreed to resume the
discussions after the Olympics.
   South Korean delegates, elated by their country's success
hosting the games, said just prior to today's talks that they would
be more willing to compromise.
   But afterward, South Korea's senior delegate Park Joon-kyu told
reporters: ``The North Koreans remain unchanged for the past 30
years. My feeling is that they need time to study our proposals.''
   Park said he thought that ``the atmosphere (of today's meeting)
is a little better now, after the Olympics.'' He said the North
``might have sensed our sincerity.''
   But bitterness over the games was still evident today.
   ``The Olympics are supposed to be a festival of peace and
goodwill,'' Chon said. By hosting the Olympics alone, he said South
Korea ``had split the nation.''
   North Korea had demanded that it co-host the Olympics, but the
International Olympic Committee rejected the bid, saying the
Olympics are awarded to a single city and cannot be shared.
   The peninsula was divided in 1945 into communist North Korea and
capitalist South Korea. They fought the bloody three-year Korean
War in 1950-53.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
