<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 0538EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Hostages     10-13 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Hostages,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Secretary Optimistic About Hostages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kidnappers in Lebanon have increasingly fewer
reasons to hold British hostages and the prospects for their
release continue to improve, Foreign Secretary Geoffrey Howe said
today.
   Howe said an easing of tensions in the Middle East should
improve the climate for the release of the hostages.
   ``I think that if we continue to see progress towards a calmer
state of affairs in all the troubled areas in the Middle East, then
the reason _ and there is no justifiable reason _ that people are
being held hostage, begins to disappear,'' Howe said.
   Howe met four former French hostages Wednesday in Brighton,
where his Conservative Party is holding its annual convention. He
spoke today on British Broadcasting Corp. television.
   ``There are reasons to believe that the prospects (of release)
are getting better rather than worse,'' he said. ``But I don't want
to raise false hopes. I have no news today or tomorrow of any
significant change in the position.''
   Britain seeks the release of three of its nationals believed
held in Lebanon by pro-Iranian Islamic fundamentalists: Anglican
Church envoy Terry Waite, journalist John McCarthy and teacher
Brian Keenan. Keenan, from Belfast, Northern Ireland, has dual
British and Irish nationality.
   Howe reiterated that while Britain continued to ``press and
probe and search'' in every way possible to secure their release,
``it would not be right to engage in deals or bargains or surrender
to blackmail.''
   Nine Americans are among the foreign hostages missing in Lebanon.
   The longest held hostage is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent of The Associated Press. He was kidnapped on March
16, 1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
