<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Israel     10-13 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Israel,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Ministry Denies Israeli Reports of Warming Relations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's Foreign Ministry denied today reports
from Jerusalem that the two countries, which have no diplomatic
relations, are upgrading political, trade and cultural ties.
   Ministry spokeswoman Li Jinhua, at a weekly briefing, said
``there's no such a thing'' when asked about a statement by Israel
Foreign Ministry Director-General Avraham Tamir that full
diplomatic relations will be established ``in the very near
future.''
   Tamir said on Israel television Wednesday that diplomatic ties
with China depend on progress in Middle East peace talks, and would
be realized soon because the peace process cannot be stopped.
   China now allows some trade with Israel and Israeli Foreign
Minister Shimon Peres has held talks with his Chinese counterpart
at the United Nations the past two years.
   But China also has close relations with the Palestine Liberation
Organization and many Arab states, and says it will not normalize
relations with Jerusalem until Israel returns land occupied since
the 1967 Middle East War.
   Spokeswoman Li, asked about Israeli media reports confirmed by
Tamir that Israel would set up an academic center in Beijing, said:
``As far as I know there's no such a thing as establishing academic
centers in Israel or China.''
   She also gave qualified denials to Israeli reports that Yitzhak
Minervi, top economic official in the Foreign Ministry, recently
signed a trade agreement in Beijing, and that a Peking opera
delegation would soon visit Israel.
   ``So far as I know there's no such a thing,'' she said about the
Minervi visit, adding ``China has no economic and trade relations
with Israel. There's no such a thing either about the visit of the
Peking opera delegation to Israel.''
</TEXT>
