<1ST_LINE>u i PM-China-Economy     10-13 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Economy,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Premier Denies China Scrapping Economic Reforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Li Peng criticized reports that China,
faced with soaring inflation and economic turmoil, has abandoned
the modernization of its economy, the official news media reported
today.
   Li denied at a meeting of the State Council, or cabinet, that a
recently announced program to cool off the overheated economy is a
setback for China's market-oriented reforms.
   He said ``some domestic figures and members of the foreign
press'' have suggested that China's decision to ``improve the
economic environment and rectify the economic order'' over the next
two years means a halt in the reforms.
   ``All these doubts or hesitations show that such people have not
yet arrived at a full understanding of the relationship between the
key tasks of creating economic stability and bolstering reform,''
he said.
   Li's comments were made Tuesday and carried today by the
official Xinhua News Agency.
   The agency quoted him as saying soaring prices have ``made many
people uneasy'' and ``are affecting social security and people's
confidence in reform'' and that a period of stability is needed to
keep the reforms on track.
   Li told the ministers they must ``change their work style and
establish a strict responsibility system.'' The council and its
departments must take the lead in reducing construction of office
buildings, hotels and meeting halls, controlling consumer funds and
rooting out corruption in government.
   He told the State Planning Commision to take charge of cutting
investment, the Finance Ministry to control financial deficits and
purchasing by government groups, and the Materials Ministry to
punish government-backed companies profiteering in hard-to-get
materials.
   Last month, the Communist Party Central Committee outlined the
two-year period of belt-tightening to bring under control an
economy hit by overspending, serious shortages of raw materials and
consumer goods, and an inflation rate of at least 20 percent.
   Li's warning to the State Council comes after past failures by
the central government to reduce the frantic pace of construction
around the country that has far outstripped the nation's financial
capabilities.
   Capital investment has grown at a rate of 18.8 percent over the
past three years, a major factor in shortages and inflation that
threaten to disrupt senior leader Deng Xiaoping's 10-year program
of reducing the role of central planning and running the economy
based on market principles.
</TEXT>
