<2ND_LINE>PM-Baudelaire Auction, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0487,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poet's Book And Drawings Sold For $1.6 Million</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to CORRECT prices to reflect current
exchange rates; no pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A book and drawings by 19th century French poet
Charles Baudelaire sold at an auction for a total of $1.6 million,
the Druout auction house announced.
   The National Library bought the book ``My Naked Heart'' for
$350,000 at Salle Druout, the premier French art auction house.
   Several drawings with China ink and feather issued by Baudelaire
were sold to the Orsay Museum. They included ``Portrait de Jeanne
Duval,'' sold for $99,000, ``A Wife for Asselineau'' for $104,000
and another ``Jeanne Duval'' for $72,000.
   The items were sold from the Armand Godoy collection. Godoy was
a minor French poet but major collector who was born in Havana in
1880 and died in Lausanne, Switzerland, in 1964.
   Baudelaire, 1821-1867, is known for his collection of poems
published as ``The Flowers Of Evil'' in 1857. His poetry, classical
in form, introduced symbolism by establishing symbolic
correspondence between sensory images.
   He was said to be obsessed by death and debauchery.
</TEXT>
