<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PreschoolMolest     10-13 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Preschool Molest,0545</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Will Push To Dismiss 60 to 70 per cent of McMartin charges.
^Eds: Court Session Skedded at 1:30 p.m. No Lead expected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense attorneys in the abruptly reduced
McMartin preschool molestation case welcomed the prosecution's
reduction of charges and said they will push for dismissal of 60 to
70 per cent of the allegations.
   Superior Court Judge William Pounders, acting on a prosecution
request, on Wednesday dismissed 27 counts, nearly a third of the
charges, against Raymond Buckey and his mother, Peggy McMartin
Buckey.
   Those counts were based on claims of molestation made by three
child witnesses who failed to testify. Prosecutors also sought
dismissal of eight other charges linked to children who did testify.
   The prosecution said the absentees were too traumatized to come
to court. The defense contended the youngsters were purposely
excluded because their testimony was too bizarre to be believable.
   It was the second time in the tumultuous five-year history of
the McMartin case that prosecutors moved to substantially diminish
the scope of their charges.
   In 1986, after a two-year preliminary hearing, District Attorney
Ira Reiner moved to dismiss charges against five former teachers
originally arrested. He said evidence against them was ``incredibly
weak.''
   Instead of alleging that 41 children had been molested, the
prosecutors then scaled it down to 14 children. Wednesday's
alteration reduced it yet again to a total of 11 children. Only
nine of those testified at the trial.
   Deputy District Attorney Lael Rubin said the eight pending
dismissal requests are based on ``a review of the evidence,''
indicating an apparent finding of insufficient proof.
   ``We conformed the pleadings to what was testified to in
court,'' he said.
   Defense attorney Danny Davis said he and co-counsel Dean Gits
will urge Pounders today to throw out more charges, claiming the
acts of molestation alleged by at least four children occurred
beyond the six-year statute of limitations for prosecution.
   ``If the statute of limitations argument holds, we'll see 60 to
70 per cent of the case (thrown) out,'' he said. ``We have a little
math game to play.''
   Pounders recessed the case until this afternoon in order to
study law on the subject.
   Buckey, 30, and his 61-year-old mother had been charged with 100
counts of molestation and conspiracy until Wednesday. Then
prosecutors unveiled a new complaint which contained only 65 counts
- 52 accusations against Buckey and 12 against Mrs. Buckey as well
as one joint charge of conspiracy.
   The move came after the last witnesses had testified in the
17-month prosecution case. The defense is scheduled to begin Monday.
   Ms. Rubin and Deputy District Attorney Roger Gunson asked
Pounders to approve substitution of the new complaint. He did not
immediately accept it but dismissed 27 of the original charges and
delayed ruling on the eight others until arguments are heard.
   Some children who had been toddlers when they attended the now
defunct McMartin Pre-School in Manhattan Beach were pre-teen-agers
by the time they testified. Davis and Gits based their statute of
limitations challenge on the four oldest witnesses who they contend
were at the school before Raymond Buckey worked there.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881013-0092 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 0727EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Italy-Politics     10-13 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Italy-Politics,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Wins Key Vote to Scrap Secret Balloting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Ciriaco De Mita's coalition today won a
crucial vote to abolish most secret balloting in Parliament. De
Mita had threatened to resign if the measure failed.
   The Chamber of Deputies voted 323 to 58 in favor of the measure
during balloting that itself was secret. The main opposition
Communist Party said it would abstain.
   The proposal needed 316 votes to pass.
   The Christian Democrat leader staked his 6-month-old coalition
on the reform measure, which is aimed at eliminating one of the
principal causes of Italy's government instability.
   De Mita indicated last week that he would resign if the measure
was rejected. Socialist leader Bettino Craxi, whose party is the
second largest in the coalition after the Christian Democrats,
pushed hard for passage.
   The Senate will now take up the reform measure.
   Italy was one of the few Western democracies where most
parliamentary votes were secret and citizens had no certainty about
how their representatives voted on issues.
   The open vote is expected to strengthen the executive system and
create a more stable political climate in a country that has had a
succession of revoling-door governments. De Mita's is Italy's 48th
post-war government.
   Previously, governments have been plagued by lawmakers who used
the secret ballot to vote against their party line, particularly to
ensure passage of pet spending projects.
   De Mita's predecessor, Giovanni Goria, resigned after his
government was repeatedly defeated in attempts to trim Italy's
budget deficit, which now stands at $87 billion.
   The Communists, who had wanted to limit open voting to financial
measures, said they would abstain in an attempt to show up
government party deputies who vote against their own coalition.
   The five parties have 377 seats in the 630-seat Chamber of
Deputies.
   Under the chamber's reform, voting still will be secret when
dealing with special government bodies such as the organized crime
commission, when the vote involves a specific person, or when it
deals with such issues as abortion or personal liberties. Proposed
substantive changes to the constitution also be would excluded from
open ballots.
   But the majority of chamber votes, especially on financial
issues such as the annual budget, will be open.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881013-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 0732EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-OkeechobeeSuit     10-13 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Okeechobee Suit,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Attorney Files Suit Over Pollution Of Everglades, Lake
Okeechobee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal suit charges that the state has allowed
water pollution to endanger and possibly destroy federal wildlife
areas in the Everglades and Lake Okeechobee.
   The Everglades system ``is an international environmental
treasure,'' said U.S. Attorney Dexter Lehtinen. ``The degradation
over a number of years is a tragedy. They will be lost to future
generations.''
   The suit filed by Lehtinen Wednesday charges the state
Department of Environmental Regulation and the South Florida Water
Management District with allowing the operation of pumps without a
permit, failing to maintain water quality standards and violating
contracts to supply clean water to Everglades National Park.
   Dan Thompson, general counsel to the state Department of
Environmental Regulation, said he hadn't seen the suit, but added,
``We don't know what to make of it. We are strongly supportive of
trying to improve the environment.''
   The suit is an attempt to force the state and the water district
to end a nine-year standoff with dairy farmers and sugar-cane
growers, whose agricultural runoff is polluting rivers and canals
that feed the environmentally sensitive Everglades, which covers
much of South Florida.
   Thompson disputed Lehtinen's contention that his agency has the
legal authority to make farmers comply with water quality standards.
   Lake Okeechobee, at 700 square miles the nation's largest
fresh-water lake outside of the Great Lakes, has for years been
receiving pollution.
   Levels of phosphates and nitrates as much as 120 times higher
than natural levels are pouring into the area, producing
fish-killing algae blooms in the lake and changing the face of
Everglades National Park, according to park Superintendent Michael
Finley.
   ``This action is a pre-emptive strike _ what we are talking
about without action is ecological collapse,'' Finley said. He
described the damage already done as ``almost irreparable.''
   The park provides sanctuary to rare and endangered wildlife,
such as the Florida panther, Southern bald eagle, woodstork,
American crocodile and Cape Sable sparrow.
   Finley said the agricultural pollutants are slowly moving south
through rivers and canals in ``a cancer descending on the park''
and the adjoining Loxahatchee National Wildlife Refuge.
   Water district officials said that others _ including federal
agencies _ are part of the pollution problem.
   ``Both the state and federal governments were involved in the
development of Lake Okeechobee and the rest of South Florida's
surface water and drainage system,'' said John Wodraska, executive
director of the district, who is also named in the suit. He added
that the district is working on an anti-pollution plan.
</TEXT>
