<2ND_LINE>PM-Neighbors Help,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmer's Assailant Surrenders; Neighbors Harvest Crop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GILLIAM, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former farm hand accused of killing a
young cotton grower who had employed him turned himself in to
police, and friends and neighbors finished harvesting the farmer's
400-acre crop.
   Felix A. Williams, 29, of Gilliam was booked for second-degree
murder and held on a $150,000 bond for allegedly stabbing Tommy
Hutto, 26, of Belcher during an argument Monday.
   Williams also was booked with aggravated battery for allegedly
stabbing Hutto's wife, Terri, in the hand when she tried to
intervene, said Caddo Parish sheriff's investigators.
   Hutto's sister, Dianna White, said Williams took three checks
from Hutto's farm account book Friday, forged one, and cashed it.
She said Hutto closed the account as soon as he realized checks had
been stolen and then told the sheriff's office of the theft.
   Williams came to Hutto's home Monday when he realized
authorities were looking for him, and the fatal argument began,
White said.
   When word spread Tuesday about Hutto's death and the plight of
his widow, farmers and neighbors from the northwest Louisiana area
showed up to pick his 400 acres of cotton.
   ``Tommy was such a nice, hard-working man,'' farmer Tommy
Stinson of Belcher said Tuesday. ``Twenty-six years old, just
getting started. Several people quit picking their own cotton to do
this.''
   ``We didn't ask a soul,'' Stinson said. ``Everybody just sent
their men, machines and trailers, and the farmers pulled the cotton
to the gin.''
   They picked about 200 acres of Hutto's crop Tuesday, and came
back for the rest Wednesday.
   Retired farmer Dan Logan, now in his 80s, had especially fond
memories of Hutto. Hutto was only 19 when Logan contracted with him
to farm 100 acres of Logan's land.
   Progressive Farmer magazine featured a story of the tie between
Logan and Hutto in its July issue.
   ``In three years, he was successful _ had his tractors paid for
and was farming 400 acres,'' Logan said.
</TEXT>
