<HEAD>Givens Suffered Miscarriage in June, Doctor Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Robin Givens' doctor has released a
letter stating that she suffered a miscarriage in early June when
she was in her second month of pregnancy.
   But the letter from Dr. Sheldon Cherry, a Manhattan
gynecologist, did not address the question of whether Givens was
pregnant when she married world heavyweight boxing champ Mike Tyson
in February.
   Givens filed for divorce Oct. 7. However, Tyson is reportedly
considering seeking an annulment on the grounds that he married
Givens believing she was pregnant when she was not.
   The letter was released Wednesday through divorce lawyer Raoul
Felder, who is representing Givens.
   Felder had said Tuesday he would get a medical report from
Cherry that would prove Givens was pregnant when she married Tyson.
But on Wednesday, Felder denied that Givens had told Tyson that she
was pregnant before April.
   However, Tyson announced in Tokyo in March that Givens was
pregnant.
   Felder, a prominent Manhattan divorce lawyer, and his California
associate Neal Raymond Hersh said they were hired by Givens on
Sunday. She was originally represented by celebrity divorce lawyer
Marvin Mitchelson, who won the ``palimony'' case against the late
actor Lee Marvin.
   On Tuesday, Givens' lawyers said they will seek an out-of-court
property settlement but indicated there is still a chance the
marriage can be saved.
   Felder insisted that Givens is not a gold digger seeking Tyson's
assets, which are valued at about $40 million.
   Givens' divorce suit was filed in California because, Felder
said, the couple spent 70 percent of their eight-month marriage
there.
   California is a community property state, which means a
divorcing couple's assets are divided evenly. But Hersh said that
``a settlement out of court in a community property state can be
anything two people want.''
</TEXT>
