<HEAD>Blackout Hits Manila And Main Philippine Island</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with officials saying full restoration may
not come until Friday. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A massive electric power blackout
struck Manila and the main Philippine island of Luzon today in what
a spokesman for the electric company described as a systems
blackout.
   Power was restored to scattered areas of the city and in Baguio,
130 miles north of the capital, officials said. They said they
hoped to restore electricity to 60 percent of the island by Friday
morning.
   The power failure struck Manila about 5:20 p.m., causing massive
traffic jams at the height of the evening rush hour.
   ``It's a systems blackout, meaning no power plant is in
operation,'' Francisco de Leon, spokesman for the Manila Electric
Company, told radio station DZRH. ``We're trying to find out what
happened.''
   Officials said operations at Manila's Ninoy Aquino International
Airport were unaffected because emergency generators were used to
power runway and terminal lights as well as communications
equipment.
   But private television station GMA said there was no power at
Malacanang Palace, President Corazon Aquino's office compound.
