<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DrugPhones     10-13 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Phones,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beach Community's Drug Dealers Can't Reach Out And Touch Somebody</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City officials hope they pulled the plug on
much of the drug dealing at Venice Beach this week by disconnecting
25 pay telephones used almost exclusively by local traffickers.
   ``It was a significant problem,'' police Capt. Jan Carlson said.
``Some dealers tied up two to four phones at a time.''
   City Councilwoman Ruth Galanter, who represents Venice, asked
General Telephone Co. to remove all but six of the 31 phones along
a one-mile stretch of Ocean Front Walk after residents complained.
   ``I don't think drug dealers want to stand in line to make their
calls,'' said the councilwoman's spokesman, Rick Ruiz. ``And with
so few lines available, maybe they'll go away.''
   The tactic appears to be working, residents and merchants said.
   James Hoyt, who works at an Ocean Front Walk art gallery, said
the drug dealers are starting to disappear.
   ``You should see the looks on their faces,'' he said. ``It's
like, `Hey, where are the phones?' There's no place for anybody to
hang out anymore.''
   The phones were yanked out after a previous plan to shoo away
the push-button pushers didn't work.
   General Telephone had tried to placate residents and police last
month by replacing the regular phones with models equipped to allow
only outgoing calls.
   But it turned out that most dealers wear beepers and have little
need for incoming calls.
   Duane Nightingale, a GTE district manager, said the company went
along with the second plan because ``we wanted to be good
citizens,'' even though the phones made a lot of money.
   He foresees only one problem: that the thousands of Venice Beach
tourists will have a hard time finding a phone.
   ``People are going to want telephones and they're not going to
be there,'' he said.
</TEXT>
