<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MoneyLaundering     10-13 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Money Laundering,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BCCI Says It Was Never Knowingly Involved In Laundering</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head office of the Bank of Credit and
Commerce International has denied any involvement in laundering
Colombian cocaine profits and pledged its full cooperation with
federal authorities.
   Representatives in BCCI's central offices in London said
Wednesday that the financial institution ``is wholly unaware of any
alleged violation and denies all allegations against it.''
   ``The bank ... will do everything in its power to assist the
concerned authorities in resolving these serious allegations,''
bank managers said in a statement.
   U.S. Customs Service agents announced Tuesday that
Luxembourg-based BCCI Holding, two of its subsidiaries and nine
bank officials were among 85 accused of participating in an
intercontinental ring which allegedly laundered $32 million in
profits for the Colombian cocaine trade.
   Federal agents alleged that $14 million was funneled through
BCCI.
   ``The amount of $14 million hardly suggests that it could have
helped a bank of $20 billion to enhance its financial position,''
the London BCCI office said.
   BCCI, founded in 1972, has 14,000 employees and reserves of $1.5
billion, and operates in 73 countries.
   Forty-one suspects have been taken into custody. Undercover
agents posed as financiers during a two-year sting that involved
operations in 10 cities in the United States, London and Paris.
   During hearings for defendants arrested in Tampa, prosecutors
said Syed Aftrab Hussain, BCCI's operations officer in Panama,
showed agents how to use BCCI to better service drug clients.
   Prosecutors allege that Hussain was part of a group of BCCI
officials who courted drug accounts. They said the group was led by
Amjad Awan, 41, of Coral Gables, assistant director of BCCI's Latin
American Division.
   Comments by prosecutors during Awan's hearing Tuesday raised
questions about the Colombian drug trade's ties to Panama's
military ruler Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Mark Jackowski said that Awan, who
managed BCCI's Panamanian office between 1981 and 1985, was a
witness last February in a U.S. Senate subcommittee investigation.
   Noriega's former political adviser and top aide Jose Blandon
reportedly testified that Noriega sold his influence to Colombian
cocaine cartels and that some of the money got to him through BCCI.
</TEXT>
