<2ND_LINE>PM-Library Fire,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Latest Central Library Fire Could Delay Building's 1992 Reopening</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire caused by renovation work at the
arson-ravaged Central Library could delay the building's reopening
if historic murals in the lobby were damaged, officials said.
   ``We're concerned _ terrified as a matter of fact _ that there
is enough smoke damage to put another film on the murals,'' city
librarian Wyman Jones said Wednesday.
   Construction materials in the basement were ignited Tuesday by
hot scraps that had been cut by a welding torch, said fire
Inspector Ed Reed.
   Except for the murals, which were recently cleaned at a cost of
$400,000, all of the library's books and other valuables had been
removed.
   If the murals _ painted in 1920 and depicting California's
history _ need another cleaning, the library's scheduled reopening
date in 1992 could be delayed, Jones said.
   The fire broke out as the 62-year-old library was undergoing a
$152 million renovation following two disastrous arson fires that
destroyed hundreds of thousands of books in 1986.
   The renovation had not reached the point of installing fire
sprinklers, fire and library officials said.
   The first of the two arson blazes that gutted the library was
set April 29, 1986, and spread quickly, destroying 375,000 books
and causing $22 million in damage. A second fire struck on Sept. 3,
1986, and destroyed 25,000 books.
</TEXT>
