<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BarricadedNuns     10-13 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Barricaded Nuns,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bishop Says Barricaded Nuns Causing `Scandal' Within Church</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLIFTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bishop Frank Rodimer says five nuns who
remain barricaded in a monastery to protest changes in their way of
life are causing a scandal in the Roman Catholic Church.
   Rodimer, the head of the Paterson diocese, said Wednesday that
the nuns could be relieved of their vows if the standoff at the
Morris Township monastery does not end.
   ``It's a possibility,'' he said at a news conference. ``But I
don't foresee that. ... They've broken the vow of obedience, and I
suppose it's a scandal in that sense.
   ``My hope is that they'd be able to come around and live
together in peace.''
   The Vatican has asked the Rev. Kevin Culligan of Milwaukee, a
Carmelite priest, to help resolve the dispute. The nuns also belong
to the Carmelite order.
   Rodimer denied claims by the nuns that he was trying to close
the Monastery of the Most Blessed Virgin Mary of Mount Carmel, but
added that their actions could end the Carmelite order in the
diocese.
   The nuns barricaded themselves in the monastery's infirmary on
Oct. 4 in protest of changes including the introduction of sweets,
radio and television.
   ``Very profound issues,'' Rodimer said sarcastically.
   He said nuns didn't have electricity or telephones in the 16th
century, but that the protesters never objected to those additions
to the order's life.
   ``For all the sisters to remain together and remain seriously at
odds with one another would be a course of action that could,
potentially, lead to the closing of the Carmel, an outcome that no
one wants,'' he said. ``People cannot pray together unless they can
live together in charity.''
   The protesters have said that all 13 nuns at the monastery
should strictly adhere to the traditional Carmelite life, which
stresses prayer and silence.
   One of the barricaded nuns, Sister John of the Cross, has said
the nuns were upset after Rodimer took the ``highly irregular''
move of putting Mother Teresa Hewitt in charge of the monastery
without consulting the nuns who live there. She said the nuns are
supposed to elect their own prioress.
   Culligan is to meet with the prioress and all of the nuns
individually to hear their views on the dispute, Rodimer said. The
bishop said he will make a final decision on how to resolve the
matter.
</TEXT>
