<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon-Politics     10-13 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Politics,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moslems And Christians Appoint Rival Security Chiefs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Moslem government today appointed a
Shiite Moslem as acting chief of security today after rejecting a
Christian appointed by the rival Christian government.
   Police Superintendent Assad Taqsh was named acting chief of
security by Abdulla Rassi, interior minister in interim Prime
Minister Salim Hoss' Syrian-backed Cabinet, which is predominantly
Moslem.
   A Moslem politician, speaking on condition of anonymity,
described the naming of two rival security chiefs as the ``most
dangerous step in the direction of formalizing Lebanon's
partition.''
   The country's de facto partition into sectarian cantons followed
Parliament's failure to elect a successor to President Amin
Gemayel, whose six-year term expired Sept. 22.
   The Hoss government rejected the appointment of Police Brig.
Gen. Nadim lteif to the post of security chief by army commander
Gen. Michel Aoun and his Cabinet, the rival Christian government.
   Aoun on Tuesday appointed lteif, a Greek Catholic, chief of
security after dismissing Jamil Nimeh, a Gemayel supporter.
   The double appointment to the position of chief of security, who
issues passports in Lebanon, may present a legal problem.
   ``Who would issue the Lebanese passports now? Lteif or Taqsh?''
asked the Moslem politician.
   ``The Moslems would presumably have passports signed by Taqsh
and the Christians' passports would be issued by lteif. I wonder
which of the two passports would be accepted by foreign
countries?'' he said.
   Taqsh's appointement came shortly after U.S. Ambassador John
McCarthy held separate talks in west Beirut with Hoss and
Parliament Speaker Hussein Husseini, a Shiite Moslem, on ways to
break the political deadlock.
   Parliament has failed three times since Aug. 18 to elect a
successor to Gemayel after Christian deputies boycotted sessions to
prevent the needed 51-member quorum from gathering. The Christians
wanted to block the election of a pro-Syrian candidate as president.
   Gemayel appointed Aoun to head an interim military government
pending the election of a president. Syrian-backed Moslem leaders
rejected Aoun's appointment and declared support for Hoss, who had
been premier under Gemayel.
</TEXT>
