<1ST_LINE>u i PM-ShroudofTurin 5thLd-Writethru a0574 10-13 0726</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shroud of Turin, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0574,0742</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dating Tests Indicate Shroud Not Burial Cloth Of Christ</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to ADD detail of shroud image, move up
denial that it is a forgery. Pick up 13th graf, `Laboratories at...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TURIN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientific tests on the Shroud of Turin
indicate it is no more than 728 years old and cannot be the burial
cloth of Christ, the archbishop of Turin announced today.
   But the shroud is not necessarily a fake, the archbishop's
scientific adviser said.
   Scientists are ``95 percent'' sure of the accuracy of tests
dating the shroud between 1260 and 1390, the archbishop, Cardinal
Anastasio Ballestrero, told a news conference. ``I see no reason
for the church to put these results in doubt,'' he said.
   Luigi Gonella, the scientific adviser, bristled at suggestions
the shroud is a forgery.
   ``A forgery is for the specific purpose of deceiving people. It
could be possible, but there is no proof,'' Gonella said. ``This
could be a medieval icon. We don't even know how it was made.''
   The shroud _ 14 feet, 3 inches long and 3 feet, 7 inches wide _
bears a faint yellowish negative image of the front and back of a
man with a thorn mark on the head, flogging lacerations on the
back, bruises on his shoulders and knees, and wounds in the side,
wrists and feet.
   For centuries it has been revered by some as the burial cloth of
Jesus and dismissed by others as a clever forgery.
   Ballestrero repeated that the Roman Catholic Church never
claimed the shroud to be a holy relic. But he and Gonella said the
image on the shroud has great symbolic importance.
   Ballestrero said he personally saw the shroud as the
``revelation of the face and the body of Christ.''
   ``The church believes in the image and not in the history
because this image of Jesus Christ in fact is very interesting and
the people believe deeply in Jesus,'' Ballestrero said.
   News reports for weeks have said the carbon-14 tests dated the
shroud to the Middle Ages and therefore it could not be Christ's
burial cloth.
   Gonella today attacked those reports, especially in the British
press, and said they made the ``unfair insinuation that the church
was afraid of science and was trying to hide (the) results.''
   He added that ``the church does not fear science. It agreed to
do these tests. The results confirm that the shroud is medieval. As
for history, it is a date, but for the faith, the shroud is the
face of Christ and those things don't change.''
   Laboratories at the University of Arizona, the Swiss Federal
Institute of Technology at the University of Zurich and Oxford
University conducted the carbon-14 tests on postage-stamp size
pieces of linen snipped from the shroud in April.
   The tests give a scientific basis for the age of the shroud but
do nothing to solve the enduring riddle of how the image was
created.
   American scientists who subjected the linen to its most rigorous
chemical, computer and photographic analysis concluded in 1981 that
it was ``a real human form of a whipped and crucified man and not
the product of an artist.''
   They speculated it resulted from chemical changes in the linen
while it was in contact with a body. Such changes could be
duplicated to a degree in the laboratory, they said. But they added
no method could adequately explain the shroud's image.
   The carbon-14 tests were supposed to be conducted as a blind
study. Each of the three laboratories was given one piece of the
shroud and one piece of linen with a known date. The labs were not
to know which was which, but the distinctive herringbone pattern of
the shroud could have given its sample away.
   Scientists have said the triple carbon dating should reveal the
age of the cloth within a 200-year range.
   The first mention of the possible existence of Christ's shroud
came from French crusader Robert of Clari, who wrote that he saw it
in 1203 in the imperial palace in Constantinople.
   But the first actual records of the Shroud of Turin trace it
only to Lirey, France in 1354.
   The shroud was bequeathed to the pope by former King Umberto II
of Italy upon his death in 1983.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881013-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 1010EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HitlerParties     10-13 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hitler Parties,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hotel Owner Says He Will Sell Nazi Material</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM DAHLBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hotel owner with an extensive collection of
Nazi memorabilia who came under fire for hosting Hitler birthday
parties says he has painted over a controversial mural and will
sell the artifacts, rather than put them on display.
   Imperial Palace owner Ralph Engelstad also said he will sell his
collection of World War II German vehicles instead of opening a
wing of his automobile exhibit for them.
   Engelstad reported his decision to get rid of his
multimillion-dollar collection in a letter Tuesday to the Jewish
Federation of Las Vegas. He had met with with Mayor Ron Lurie the
day before.
   ``I now feel I have done what I can and apologized for what I
cannot do,'' Engelstad said in the letter.
   Alan Hilburg, a Dallas public relations specialist in ``crisis
communication'' who is representing Engelstad, said, ``I think what
he has tried to do is arrive at a solution that meets the needs of
the entire Las Vegas community and will allow Las Vegas to get back
to business.''
   Last week, Engelstad apologized for the Hitler parties he held
for employees, saying they were ``stupid, insensitive and held in
bad taste.'' He denied that he had any sympathy for Hitler or Nazi
ideology.
   He said then that he was still considering opening his private
``war room'' collection of Nazi and Axis memorabilia to the public.
   ``Over the weekend he spent quite a bit of time wrestling with
this and decided it (selling the collection) was the best thing to
do,'' said Hilburg.
   The resort owner has already had the mural in the ``war room''
painted over and is making plans to get rid of his collection, the
spokesman said.
   In his letter to the Jewish Federation, Engelstad complained of
``a degree of unfair treatment'' by the media, but acknowledged he
had not been successful in convincing the community that his
apology was ``heartfelt and sincere.''
   ``I realize that what was missing in my apology was an
acknowledgement of the specific hurt and pain felt by the Jewish
community over this issue,'' he said. ``And I am prepared to
publicly do that.''
   Engelstad also is under investigation by the state Gaming
Control Board for allegations that he ordered the destruction of
Imperial Palace security records and other documents that have
become a point of contention in a civil lawsuit.
   Gaming agents recently inspected the ``war room'' as part of an
investigation into Engelstad's suitability as a casino owner. Last
week, they found a printing plate at the hotel used to make
hundreds of bumper stickers bearing the words ``Hitler Was Right.''
The board wants to know if Engelstad ordered the bumper stickers
printed.
</TEXT>
