<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Britain-Politics     10-13 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Politics,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tories Promise More Tax Cuts, Lower Inflation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIGHTON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury chief Nigel Lawson today
promised more tax cuts ``when it is prudent'' and forecast a drop
in inflation next year.
   But in his address to his Conservative Party's annual
convention, he warned that interest rates, now at 12 percent, would
remain high for ``quite a while.''
   The third day of the gathering in this English seaside town was
highlighted by a promise of more cash for nurses _ whose pay
dispute is one of the most serious now facing the government _ and
birthday greetings to Prime Minister and party leader Margaret
Thatcher, who turned 63 today.
   Lawson, who is chancellor of the exchequer, the equivalent of
treasury secretary, said inflation, now running at 5.7 percent,
would begin to drop next year.
   He also pledged to cut the basic income tax rate, now 25
percent, to 20 percent ``as and when it is prudent.'' But interest
rates, which had been raised to dampen a consumer spending boom
brought on partly by Lawson's previous tax cuts, would remain high
``for quite a while,'' he said.
   Health Secretary Kenneth Clarke delighted delegates with an
offer of $235.45 million to boost nurses' pay and spare the
nation's health authorities from having to cut back services.
   This year, many nurses joined in an unprecedented one-day strike
for higher pay, and because they enjoy considerable public
sympathy, their demands have put Mrs. Thatcher's budget-cutting
strategies to a severe test.
   Clarke denied he had caved in to the nurses, saying they were
``worth every penny of it.''
   Hundreds of delegates rose to their feet and started singing
``Happy Birthday'' as Mrs. Thatcher arrived in the convention hall.
   Mrs. Thatcher looked genuinely surprised as an electronic organ
blared out the song and party members shouted out good wishes.
   Dressed in a blue checked suit, she smiled broadly when Tory
Party senior vice-chairman Sir Stanley Odell handed her a large
bouquet.
</TEXT>
