<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 1025EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Yugoslavia 2ndLd-Writethru a0560 10-13 0787</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslavia, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0560,0809</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rallies Banned In Southern Republic; Top Leaders Named In Coming
Shake-up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with Politburo reacting to criticism of Tito.
No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities in the southern republic
of Montenegro today banned street rallies after demonstrations by
nationalists escalated into anti-government protests.
   Belgrade newspapers said three Communist Party leaders probably
would be ousted during a meeting of party leaders Monday. The
bosses have promised a shake-up aimed at ending the economic crisis
and ethnic conflict.
   The ruling Politburo sharply denounced attacks on the late
President Josip Broz Tito. Some prominent intellectuals blame Tito
for the problems.
   Inflation stands at 217 percent, unemployment at 15 percent and
the foreign debt is $21 billion. Living standards have fallen by at
least one-half since 1980, according to official figures.
   In addition, ethnic Serbs have been agitating for more Serbian
control over the autonomous provinces of Kosovo and Vovodjina,
alleging harassment by the majority ethnic Albanians.
   Some of the biggest rallies have occurred in the southern
republic of Montenegro.
   A statement from the republic's ruling Politburo urged citizens
to stay away from ``scheduled mass demonstrations'' this weekend.
The statement was carried by the state-run Tanjug news agency.
   Tanjug also quoted Marko Orlandic, a Montenegrin member of the
national Poliburo, as saying: ``The state presidency of Montenegro
has introduced urgent measures to stop all gatherings which could
jeopardize the security situation, property and lives of citizens.''
   In Montenegro's capital, Titograd, numerous riot police were on
patrol this week.
   Security has been stepped up among police, army and civilian
defense units in at least some regions of the country, according to
sources who asked not to be identified.
   Belgrade dailies reported at least two scheduled nationalist
rallies were called off in Serbia and Montenegro this week. This
appeared to be a reaction to a warning from President Raif
Dizdarevic on Sunday that further unrest could provoke unspecified
emergency measures.
   The Communist leadership is meeting in each of Yugoslavia's six
republics and two autonomous provinces this week to prepare for
Monday's Central Committee session in Belgrade.
   The announcement of the probable ouster of three top leaders
from the party's Central Committee was made during a meeting of top
Communists in the northern republic of Slovenia on Wednesday,
Belgrade newspapers reported today.
   The reports identified the three _ all from the republic of
Slovenia _ as Stane Dolanc, currently Yugoslavia's vice president,
Marjan Orozen, head of the official trade unions, and Janez
Zemljaric, one of the nation's two vice premiers.
   They were the first people named as being likely to be removed
during the meeting of the 165-member Central Committee.
   Stefan Korosec, a national Central Committee secretary, was
quoted in Belgrade newspapers as telling the Slovene Central
Committee that the three men ``are among those who are likely to be
replaced.''
   He added that several other leaders from Yugoslavia's other
republics would lose their posts but said he did not want to name
them.
   Dolanc has frequently been named in recent weeks as a leader
Serbian nationalists wanted to see fall. The Serbs allege Dolanc
was not tough enough on ethnic Albanians after racial riots erupted
in Serbia's province of Kosovo in 1981, when Dolanc was interior
minister.
   Zemljaric has been involved in economic policy for much of the
1980s, when inflation spiraled out of control.
   As head of the trade unions, Orozen is also a target for
criticism amid growing worker unrest over austerity measures that
are slashing wages but failing to stem price hikes.
   On Wednesday, Slovene Communist leader Milan Kucan criticized
Serbian Communists and nationalist rallies.
   The attack followed a strong defense of the rallies Tuesday by
Serbian Communist Party leader Slobodan Milosevic, who has support
among the hundreds of thousands who have attended the gatherings.
   In Belgrade, Ivica Racan, a member of the Politburo from the
republic of Croatia, today said attacks on Tito amount to attacks
on Yugoslavia's political system. He spoke during a meeting of
party leaders.
   A 19-member Committee in Defense of Intellectual Freedoms, in a
statement to the Yugoslav leadership June 27, said Tito was to
blame for creating an undemocratic, repressive political system
``which has thwarted the progressive development of the society.''
   Tito, who died in 1980 after ruling for 35 years, is revered by
Yugoslav authorities and public criticism of his policies can be
prosecuted.
   ``There can be no way out of the present economic, political and
moral crisis affecting Yugoslav society without a thorough critical
evaluation of past Yugoslav policies,'' the statement said.
   According to Tanjug, Racan said several government organizations
and officials have denounced the committee's statement, calling for
political or even criminal responsibility of the authors.
</TEXT>
