<HEAD>Three Killed in Small Plane Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MARIA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small plane crashed on a
fog-shrouded hill as the pilot prepared for an instrument landing,
authorities said, and all three people aboard were killed.
   The final communication between the single-engine Piper Cherokee
and the Santa Maria Airport tower came at 10:06 a.m. Wednesday when
the pilot asked for routine landing instructions, said Federal
Aviation Administration spokesman Fred O'Donnell.
   The plane was found nearly an hour later on a hill called
Solomon Peak, about five miles southeast of the airport and 150
miles northwest of Los Angeles. There were no survivors, said Santa
Barbara County Fire Department spokesman Keith Collum.
   The pilot was identified as Theodore Talbot Culpepper, 67, of
San Luis Rey Downs, and the passengers were identified as Raymond
Kawano, 50, of Oceanside, and Ronald W. Fisk, 33, of San Diego,
said Deputy L. Hess of the Santa Barbara County Sheriff's
Department.
   ``The two passengers had hired Culpepper to fly them to Santa
Maria on agricultural business,'' Hess said.
</TEXT>
