<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChryslerWill     10-13 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chrysler Will,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chrysler Money Goes To Museum, Art To Nephew</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chrysler Museum will get a $1.6 million
endowment and the majority of a family trust fund from the estate
of Walter P. Chrysler Jr., but a major portion of the art works now
on loan to the museum will go to a nephew, according to a museum
official.
   David Steadman, director of the museum, disclosed the provisions
of the will Wednesday. Of the 785 works on loan, 768 will go to
Jack Forker Chrysler Jr., a nephew and ``the only male of his
generation bearing the Chrysler name,'' Steadman said.
   Steadman said, however, only between 10 percent and 15 percent
of the works going to Jack Chrysler have ever been displayed at the
museum. He said the majority of the Chrysler collection, including
the most valuable and important works, already were the property of
the museum through previous Chrysler donations.
   The museum will get ownership of the remaining 17 American and
European paintings on loan, plus the endowment and 76 percent of
the family trust fund, thought to be less than $10 million,
Steadman said. That fund was established by Walter P. Chrysler Sr.,
founder of the Chrysler Corp.
   Steadman declined to put a value on the 17 new paintings,
including Albert Bierstadt's ``The Emerald Pool,'' Walt Kuhn's
``American Beauty,'' Robert Motherwell's ``The Golden Fleece'' and
John Hoppner's ``Portrait of Mrs. John Farthing.''
   Chrysler, 79, who died last month, had not discussed the
provisions of his will with the museum, Steadman said.
   ``I never had a clue about anything about Walter,'' he said.
``He was a very complex individual.''
   Steadman estimated that since 1971 Chrysler had donated about
$100 million worth of art to the museum.
</TEXT>
