<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Women-CivilRights     10-13 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Women-Civil Rights,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leaders: Women's Civil Rights Roles Will Help With Future
Strategies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The status of women remains a critical issue for
the civil rights movement, says Coretta Scott King.
   ``Human survival in the future will depend on the political
empowerment of women,'' the widow of Martin Luther King Jr. said
Wednesday at the opening of a a four-day conference on ``Women in
the Civil Rights Movement.''
   ``We women stood in the background and held things up, to keep
them going, over the years,'' Mrs. King said. ``We have a
tremendous job to do each time we communicate with younger people
to help them understand what the conditions were so that they can
appreciate the progress that's been made and is continuing.''
   About 75 people joined Mrs. King and civil rights figure Rosa
Parks at the opening session at the Ebenezer Baptist Church, where
King and his father preached. Mrs. Parks sparked the modern civil
rights movement by her refusal to move to the back of a segregated
bus in Montgomery, Ala., in 1955. The subsequent bus boycott by
blacks in Montgomery was led by King, then a young preacher.
   Dorothy Height, president of the National Council of Negro
Women, said a forum to address issues concerning black women is
important in the current political climate.
   ``The righteous indignation that poured out across this country
is not there,'' she said. ``And we've got a job to do.''
   Mrs. King noted that women hold 23 of 435 House seats and two of
100 Senate seats. Only one of those 25 women, Rep. Cardiss Collins,
D-Ill., is black.
   Organizers of the conference, being held at the nearby Martin
Luther King Center for Nonviolent Social Change, say it is the
first national conference on women's role in the civil rights
movement and will be used as a forum to address issues that affect
women worldwide.
</TEXT>
