<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0467,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Back in Congress to Urge Democrats to Get to Work</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 6 grafs new with Bentsen touring Capitol; picks up pvs
4th graf bgng, ``It's a call.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice presidential candidate Lloyd Bentsen
returned to the Capitol today and urged his Democratic colleagues
to get down to work for their party's national ticket.
   The Texas senator met with House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas,
and then spoke at a closed-door meeting of House Democrats. He
received loud applause several times in what attendees described as
a ``fire-'em-up'' address.
   He then strolled over to the Senate, where reporters were
allowed in for the beginning of his session with Democrats there.
   Bentsen received a standing ovation when introduced by Senate
Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va. With a slip of the tongue,
Byrd seemed to express the feelings of many senators that Bentsen _
not Michael Dukakis _ should head the ticket.
   ``My colleagues, it's my pleasure to present to you the next
president _ the next vice president,'' Byrd said to roars from his
fellow Democrats.
   With Congress close to adjourning for the year, and attention
focused on tonight's final presidential debate, Bentsen took time
out from campaigning to spend most of the day in Washington.
   ``It's a call to arms,'' said Joe O'Neill, Bentsen's chief of
staff.
   The Democratic ticket this year has had much more support from
locally-elected officials than Walter Mondale did four years ago.
But aides say a total commitment is needed to squeeze out a victory.
   ``We can win this thing, but it's got to be everybody pulling
together,'' said O'Neill.
   Enter Bentsen, who regardless of his position on the ticket, has
tremendous clout because of his chairmanship of the Senate Finance
Committee. He declined to elaborate on what pitch he would throw to
get the Democrats in Congress moving.
   ``Oh, I don't want to tell them ahead of time,'' he said.
   Bentsen said he would be calling Dukakis on the telephone today
to wish him luck in the debate. He expressed confidence in the
Massachusetts governor, but denied there was any more pressure on
the Democrat than there is on Bush.
   ``I think it's important for both of them _ no more important
for Mike than it is for Bush,'' he said.
   Asked what advice he'd have for Dukakis, he said, ``I'm going to
say just what he said to me. Be yourself.''
   ``Hang loose,'' he added.
   Dukakis is not known for ``hanging loose,'' and has often been
criticized for being cold and aloof. Bentsen scoffed at reporters'
questions on that topic.
   ``He's going to do good, let's watch it, he'll do great,'' he
said.
   Bentsen planned to fly tonight to Houston to watch the debate
and then attend a post-debate rally there. On Friday, he's
scheduled to fly to California for a joint rally with Dukakis.
   On Wednesday, Bentsen campaigned in Missouri and Arkansas,
highlighting issues such as economic nationalism and Bush's choice
of Dan Quayle as a running mate which the Democrats hope Dukakis
can hammer home during the 90-minute, nationally broadcast debate.
   Bentsen told a crowd outside the courthouse in Columbia, Mo.,
about Quayle's assertion that ``America is still the envy of the
world.''
   ``But not because of people like Dan Quayle and George Bush, who
refuse to stand up for the American economy,'' he said.
   ``Today I read in the newspaper that Dan Quayle says he's going
to be his own campaign manager ... be his own ``Dr. Spin
Control,''' he said. ``That may be his pitch, but I'll bet it's
thrown George Bush a real curve ball.''
   Bentsen said Bush's choice of Quayle was another example of how
the vice president ``swings and misses.'' In the war against drugs:
``No runs, no hits, no progress,'' he said.
</TEXT>
