<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AirBaseCrash     10-13 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Air Base Crash,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air Force Plane Crash Sends Shock Waves Through Air Force Base</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSCODA, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jet tanker crash that killed six crewmen
and injured 10 other people probably was not weather-related, Air
Force officials said, but one serviceman said strong wind had
rocked the plane.
   ``The wind was blowing so hard. He (the pilot) tried to land but
the plane was rocking back and forth. The wings were going up and
down,'' said the crew chief of a nearby B-52 bomber.
   The witness, who spoke to the Detroit Free Press on the
condition his name not be used, was working on his plane about 300
yards from the site where the KC-135 Stratotanker went down Tuesday
at Wurtsmith Air Force Base.
   The Air Force has begun its investigation of the crash and it
could take months to complete, Air Force Capt. Robin Crumm said.
Air Force spokesmen have said weather probably played no part in
the crash.
   The crash was the worst accident involving the KC-135 since
March 13, 1987, when another jet tanker crashed near Fairchild Air
Force Base in eastern Washington, killing seven people.
   Flags across Oscoda, near the base in the northeastern Lower
Peninsula, flew at half-staff. A private memorial service was
scheduled for 10 a.m. Friday at the base chapel.
   ``Most of us knew the people on the plane,'' Staff Sgt. Pat
Hoover, a jet engine mechanic, said Wednesday. ``There's a lot of
emotion around the base.''
   One of the victims, plane commander Capt. Jeffrey Giles, 27, had
been married only one month and had just moved into a house with
his wife, Lorraine Giles.
   ``They were a neat couple with the whole world out in front of
them, and just as happy as they could be,'' said Kim Fullerton, who
sold them the house.
   The crash also killed Capt. Gerald Earhart, 33, of Montague;
co-pilot Capt. David B. Greene, 26, of Lakewood, Colo.; 2nd Lt.
Scott J. Szuter, 29, of Kirtland, Ohio; Airman 1st Class Robert L.
Parham, 23, of Fayetteville, N.C.; and Capt. William G. Russell,
33, of Panama City, Fla.
</TEXT>
