<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NuclearTest     10-13 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nuclear Test,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blast Shakes Buildings in Las Vegas, 80 Miles Away</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major nuclear weapons test today
registered 5.8 on the Richter scale and shook high-rise hotels and
apartment buildings in this gaming capital, 80 miles from ground
zero.
   The 5.8 reading on the measure of ground motion at the National
Earthquake Information Center in Golden, Colo. was one of the
highest from a nuclear test in some time, according to center
spokesman Russ Needham.
   The 7 a.m. blast prompted calls to operators at some Las Vegas
resorts, with guests asking if there had been an earthquake.
   The test, code-named Dalhart, was the 11th conducted this year
at the Nevada Test Site and the 686th announced blast at the remote
desert site since testing began there in January 1951.
   The nuclear device was buried 2,100 feet beneath the surface of
Yucca Flat.
   Energy Department spokeswoman Barbara Yoerg, who was in a
control building 12 miles from ground zero at the time of
detonation, said the building was still swaying perceptibly 20
seconds afterward.
   Ms. Yoerg, who has been at the site for many of the blasts, said
today's was one of the strongest she has felt.
   She said the test had an explosive force of less than 150
kilotons, the limit set by U.S.-Soviet treaty. The shot would have
been near the upper limits based on the Richter reading and the
building motion described by Nevadans.
   Dora Rosso, a switchboard operator at the Energy Department
office west of the Las Vegas Strip, said, ``Venetian blinds started
moving side by side, then we could feel the chair moving side by
side.''
   ``This is the first one we've felt in a long time at ground
level,'' she said. ``You were very aware of it. There was a
quivering motion for about a minute.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
