<1ST_LINE>u p PM-PresidentialPolls 3rdLd-Writethru a0527 10-13 0771</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presidential Polls, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0527,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ABC-Post Poll Shows Big Bush Lead in Electoral Votes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUB 4th graf to add differing poll results bgng ``Voter
sentiments...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 50-state survey involving nearly 10,000 likely
voters has found George Bush leading solidly in the presidential
race that counts _ the state-by-state contest for electoral votes.
   Surveys have found a close race between Republican presidential
nominee Bush and Democrat Michael Dukakis across the nation as a
whole. But the ABC News-Washington Post poll examined their
standings in each state, where the election actually is decided.
   The result: Bush led firmly in 21 states with 220 electoral
votes _ just 50 short of the total needed to win, ABC reported
Wednesday. Dukakis was ahead in three states and the District of
Columbia, for 30 electoral votes.
   Voter sentiments can change before the Nov. 8 election and some
polls have indicated different outcomes than the ABC-Post survey,
which was notable for its size and scope.
   Bush called the survey ``interesting and encouraging,'' but said
he would stick to his strategy. He told ABC: ``If polls are
encouraging it makes me feel good, but I also remember when they
weren't.''
   The poll was conducted among 9,778 likely voters in the 50
states and the District of Columbia from Sept. 21 through Monday.
Margins of error varied with differing sample sizes in each state,
and ABC would not disclose them.
   ABC and the Post also conducted a standard national survey that
put the race at 51 percent for Bush to 45 percent for Dukakis. A
CBS News-New York Times poll Wednesday had nearly the same margin
for Bush: 47-42.
   National polls measure sentiment across the nation as a whole.
But in the election each state gives its electoral votes to the
winner in that state, so state-by-state standings are more relevant.
   Such surveys rarely are done because polling in all the states
requires a far larger sample than surveying the nation as a whole.
The ABC-Post poll interviewed 100 to 500 voters in each state.
   Sampling error was high for the poll with the margin of error
for each state ranging from five to 10 percentage points. Pollsters
for the network said they had large enough samples to characterize
the state races.
   Those they put firmly in Bush's column included Texas, where
recent state polls have given him a 10-point lead; New Jersey,
where he led by eight points in a state poll last week; and Ohio,
where he led in a state poll a month ago by just four points. The
states they said were leaning toward Bush included New York, where
most other recent polls have shown a slight Dukakis lead; and
California, where most recent polls have found a tie.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Following Material Embargoed for 6 a.m. EDT Release</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A survey released today by The Buffalo News found Dukakis
holding a 9 percent lead over Bush _ 49 percent to 40 percent _ in
New York state, including a commanding 62 percent to 28 percent
lead in the New York City area.
   Political-Media Research Inc. of Washington, D.C., conducted the
survey of 850 registered voters Monday and Tuesday. The poll had a
margin of error of plus or minus four percentage points.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>End of Embargoed Material</HEAD>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ABC gave this breakdown:
   _Firm for Bush: Alaska, Arizona, Florida, Georgia, Idaho,
Indiana, Kentucky, Maine, Michigan, Mississippi, New Hampshire, New
Jersey, New Mexico, North Carolina, North Dakota, Ohio, South
Carolina, Texas, Utah, Virginia and Wyoming.
   _Leaning for Bush: Alabama, California, Connecticut, Delaware,
Iowa, Kansas, Louisiana, Maryland, Missouri, Nebraska, Nevada, New
York, Oklahoma, South Dakota and Tennessee.
   _A tossup: Arkansas, Colorado, Montana, Rhode Island,
Washington, West Virginia, Wisconsin.
   _Firm for Dukakis: Hawaii, Massachusetts and Minnesota, and the
District of Columbia.
   _Leaning for Dukakis: Illinois, Oregon, Pennsylvania and Vermont.
   The CBS-Times poll, meanwhile, found increasing doubt about Sen.
Dan Quayle's qualifications to serve as president. By a 2-1 margin,
probable voters in the poll said they would worry about Quayle, the
Republican vice presidential nominee, if he had to take over as
president.
   The poll indicated the concern was keeping the race a close one
in terms of the contest nationally. When respondents were asked
their preference if they could vote for president only, without a
running mate, support for Dukakis dipped from 45 percent to 41
percent. Bush's remained at 50 percent.
   The CBS-Times poll was done Oct. 8 through Monday among 1,009
probable voters; The smaller, national ABC-Post poll was done Oct.
5 through Tuesday among 1,187 likely voters nationwide. Both had
four-point margins of error.
</TEXT>
