<1ST_LINE>r p AM-MichiganSenate     10-13 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Michigan Senate,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Candidate Sues Own Party Over Campaign Promise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF HOLYFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican U.S. Senate candidate Jim Dunn
has filed suit against his own party, saying a national GOP
committee crippled his campaign by breaking a promise to contribute
$638,000.
   The former congressman said he filed the lawsuit in U.S.
District Court in Lansing on Wednesday as a last resort to get the
money in time to pay for television ads before the Nov. 8 election.
   The Democratic incumbent, Sen. Donald Riegle, holds a 2-1 lead
over Dunn in the latest polls.
   Dunn's lawsuit names as defendants the Republican National
Committee and one of its arms, the National Republican Senatorial
Committee. It seeks an emergency injunction ordering the senatorial
committee to come up with about $438,000 for his campaign.
   Dunn, an East Lansing home builder, said he had received
$200,000 from the committee, but had been told he wouldn't get the
rest, even though his financially strapped campaign couldn't afford
television ads without it.
   Dunn has spent $250,000 of his own money on his campaign and
said the promise of $638,000 from the senatorial committee was one
of the reasons he decided to enter the race.
   He said he didn't know why the senatorial committee had reneged
on its promise. ``They won't return my phone calls,'' he said.
   Tom Mason, a spokesman for the senatorial committee in
Washington, said it would have no direct comment on the lawsuit or
the commitment to Dunn.
   ``We don't like to fight in public with any of our guys. We
think it doesn't help anybody ... on the other hand, we don't
criticize them for anything they do if they think it will help
their campaign,'' Mason said.
</TEXT>
