<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Taiwan-Protest,0172</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fishermen Force Shutdown Of Petrochemical Complex</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A petrochemical complex in southern Taiwan
remained closed Thursday, a day after angry fishermen protesting
industrial pollution invaded the site and switched off the
electricity, officials reported.
   The 2,000 fishermen said chemical pollutants from the Linyuan
Industrict District, about 200 miles south of Taipei, have
destroyed their fishing grounds, said Yang Shih-chien, head of the
Industrial Development Bureau.
   Some fishermen remained at the complex Thursday to prevent
workers from entering its 18 factories, officials said.
   On Wednesday, the fishermen attacked several guards and workers,
who suffered minor injuries, and destroyed some factory equipment,
officials said.
   Lee Ching-chung, deputy director of the Environmental Protection
Bureau, blamed the pollution on a water waste treatment plant.
   The fishermen want the factories to pay them $25 million in
compensation.
   The companies, including one operated by the state-run Chinese
Petroleum Corp., are major producers of ethylene, propylene and
other raw materials for textile and plastic industries.
</TEXT>
