<HEAD>Iraq Rebuilds School Hit By Iranian Missile</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials on Thursday inaugurated a new
school built next to one destroyed by an Iranian missile that
killed 34 children last year.
   The ceremony in Dora'a, a suburb of Baghdad, was part of a
nationwide celebration of Children's Day, which marks the
anniversary of the missile attack.
   Iraq's minister of culture and information, Latif Nussayif
Jassin, opened the $1 million two-story building constructed 900
feet from the former Balat al-Shuhada'a school.
   The Iranian missile hit the school Oct. 13, 1987, killing 34
children and wounding 10 others.
   The new school has a swimming pool, ice skating rink and a
museum.
   A United Nations-sponsored cease-fire in the 8-year-old
Iran-Iraq war went into effect Aug. 20.
