<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Soviet 1stLd-Writethru a0451 10-13 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Soviet, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0451,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US, Soviet Experts To Cooperate on Medical Research</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: First 5 grafs new with signing ceremony; picks up 5th graf
pvs, He said</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and the Soviet Union today
signed a five-year agreement providing for joint research programs
to combat AIDS, drug abuse, alcoholism and polio.
   Signing for the Soviet side, Valentin Pokrovsky, president of
the Soviet Academy of Medical Sciences, expressed hope that the
ceremony will mark the ``beginning of a wonderful long road which
we will travel together.''
   Samuel O. Thier, president of the National Institute of
Medicine, signed for the United States. The ceremony at the
National Academy of Sciences featured champagne toasts and numerous
expressions of friendship and good will.
   The initial plans call for several joint activities in 1989,
including a symposium in the United States on AIDS research and a
meeting in the Soviet Union on the health effects of radiation.
   At a news conference Wednesday night, Pokrovsky said the last
summit meeting between President Reagan and Soviet President
Mikhail Gorbachev and the ``general political atmosphere'' have
contributed to closer cooperation. He wore a lapel pin displaying
the Soviet and American flags.
   He said AIDS and nuclear radiation are two logical areas for
cooperative research.
   Pokrovsky said American experts are particularly interested in
learning about the Soviet experience following the disaster at the
Chernobyl nuclear power plant in April 1986. Dozens of persons are
reported to have died in that accident.
   ``It would be gross negligence not to research in detail all
aspects of this accident,'' Pokrovsky said.
   At the same time, he said, Soviet doctors are eager to learn
more about how the American medical community deals with the AIDS
problem.
   He said there has been only one Soviet fatality since March 1987
as a result of AIDS, but 81 persons who are not yet sick have been
diagnosed as carrying AIDS antibodies. He acknowledged that the
percentage of Soviet citizens who have been tested for AIDS is
relatively small _ 11 million.
   There have been about 300 cases of non-Soviet citizens in the
Soviet Union afflicted with AIDS, primarily students from African
countries where there is a high incidence of the disease, Pokrovsky
said.
   While the AIDS problem ``has acquired almost catastrophic
dimensions'' in the United States, he said, it is only a
``localized infection'' in the Soviet Union.
   He suggested that one reason is that Soviet drug users are far
less susceptible to AIDS than their American counterparts.
   ``The incidence of drug abuse through a needle is very low in
the Soviet Union,'' he said.
   The research on drug abuse and alcoholism, Pokrovsky said, will
focus on the circumstances of addiction, possible genetic origins
and the effects on future generations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881013-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 1258EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-SudanAid 2ndLd-Writethru a0616 10-13 0895</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sudan Aid, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0616,880</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: First 3 grafs new with announcement; picks up 4th graf pvs,
The relief</NOTE>
<HEAD>Sudan Allows US Aid To Famine-Struck South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States today began airlifting food
and medical supplies to thousands of sick and starving people in
famine-ravaged southern Sudan after the Sudanese government agreed
to let the aid go thruough, the State Department said.
   The airlift got underway after a meeting in Khartoum of Sudanese
Prime Minister Sadek el-Mahdi, U.S. Ambassador G. Norman Anderson
and Walter Bollinger, an official of the U.S. Agency for
International Development.
   The agreement breaks a deadlock between the Sudanese government
and foreign aid donors. State Department spokesman Charles Redman
said food and medical supplies are being airlifted to prepositioned
storage points.
   The relief plan was drawn up by a team from the State
Department's Office of Foreign Disaster Assistance, the Sudanese
government and other donors, including private groups, according to
a cable from the U.S. ambassador in Khartoum. A copy was obtained
by The Associated Press.
   The cable quoted the Sudanese prime minister as saying:
   ``I have followed the work of the team which is helping us deal
with some of our problems. We appreciate that good work and feel it
enhances the friendly relations between our people and the people
of the United States.''
   The Sudanese government, which has fought an intermittent war
with Christians and Animists in the south who resisted the
imposition of Islamic law, had resisted delivery of food supplies
into rebel areas.
   Lately, however, the rebel Sudaense People's Liberation Army,
commanded by U.S.-educated Col. John Garang, has fired on relief
planes and convoys, making assistance difficult. The rebels are
backed by the Marxist government in Ethiopia.
   The United States has good relations with Sudan, which received
$100 million in American aid last year. In Africa, only Egypt gets
more U.S. economic assistance.
   Bollinger was quoted in the cable as saying the relief plan
``reflects a joint effort on the part of the United States and The
Sudan to provide essential food and medicines to thousands of
people who face death from hunger and disease.''
   The English-language newspaper Sudan Times reported on Wednesday
that troops and rebels weree fighting house-to-house in the
besieged southern Sudanese town of Torit and that Roman Catholic
Archbishop Paride Taban had sent a plea: ``We implore you to pray
for peace.''
   The army meanwhile confirmed reports by the People's Liberation
Army that the rebels had captured Ikotos, a town near Torit. It
said soldiers made a ``tactical withdrawal'' from the town.
   The army claimed its 108-man garrison had inflicted many
casualties among more than 3,000 rebels attacking from three sides
but gave no figures for casualties. The rebels said Friday that 62
soldiers had died in the three-day battle and that 300 had fled
into Uganda.
   The fall of Ikotos gives the rebels control over three towns
that form a triangle around Torit, capital of East Equatoria
province, 85 miles east of Juba, the largest city in the south.
Liberation Army fighters captured Kialla and Katire weeks ago.
   The Sudan Times said street fighting was reported this week in
Torit and that the archbishop has been sending appeals for food and
other relief supplies for the besieged populace.
   ``This is my last message to you,'' Taban's message read,
according to the newspaper. ``We implore you to pray for peace.''
   He said Catholic agencies in his diocese have nothing else to
offer Torit's thousands of hungry people, but the town has given up
on expecting help from the outside, the newspaper reported.
   Bollinger was quoted in the cable that reached the State
Department today as saying ``critical food shortages brought on by
civil strife in the South, heavy rains and other problems have
driven thousands of people from the countryside into towns were
resources have been streatched beyond limit.''
   He added: ``The U.S. is pleased to be able to join others in the
donor community in assistant the government of Sudan in its efforts
to support the men, women and children who are at risk.''
   The relief operation began with planes carrying food and medical
supplies from storage points in in Kadugli, outside Abyei, to Al
Muglad and Babanusa to the West, the cable from Khartoum said.
   Ambassador Anderson reported that flight operations will begin
to other locations in southern Kordofan, which has been isolated
and where hundreds of thousands of displaced people face possible
starvation.
   In addition to the food supplies, the cable said, the relief
plan also calls for drugs and medical supplies to assist 250,000
people for three months.
   Last week, the State Department and the Agency for International
Development deplored recent attacks on relief efforts by insurgents
in the South.
   AID said nine Kenyan drivers and assistants had been killed or
were missing and several relief trucks had been disabled or
abandoned. The U.S. agency accused the People's Liberation Army of
trying to shoot down a civilian relief aircraft carrying American
supplies to Juba on Sept. 25.
   ``We deplore these outrageous actions which target trucks and
planes that are undertaking humanitarian missions,'' State
Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said. ``We call on all
parties to the conflict in Sudan to avoid interference with the
movement of emergency relief operations so that the hungry might be
fed and the sick attended.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
