<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 1326EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HorsebackDWI     10-13 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Horseback DWI,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Deadlocks on Drunken Riding Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAYNESVILLE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The trial of a man charged with drunken
driving _ on horseback _ has ended in a deadlocked jury.
   ``If they're going to take your license for riding a horse, they
ought to make you have tags and a license for it,'' said defendant
Barry Michael Treadway after the mistrial Wednesday.
   Assistant District Attorney Art Jacobson said he believed some
of the jurors were troubled about applying the drunken driving law
against a horseman. He said he had not decided whether to pursue
the case.
   Treadway, 26, of Canton had been convicted in District Court
last month, and the jury was impaneled to hear his appeal.
   Treadwell was arrested about 2 a.m. July 24 by city police who
found him sitting atop a horse in the parking lot of Homer's Keg
Room.
   Officers testified Monday that Treadway was ``fussin' and
cussin''' and appeared intoxicated when he dismounted.
   Treadway said he was not the man who had been seen riding the
horse around the parking lot.
   The horse's owner, who had been at a horse show nearby, asked
Treadway to hold the horse while he stepped inside to use the
telephone, the defendant said.
   Treadway admitted drinking four to five beers at the horse show
several hours before his arrest, and a Breathalyzer test at the
police station indicated a blood alcohol level of 0.10, the legal
minimum for intoxication.
   Treadway's conviction in District Court netted him a seven-day
jail term, $500 fine and loss of his driver's license for four
years. He risked losing his license for up to five years if
convicted in Superior Court, but said he appealed _ in part _ to
fight a law he considered unfair.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
