<2ND_LINE>PM-Sea Lions,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mystery Malady Hits Sea Lions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAUSALITO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California sea lions are threatened by
a mysterious illness marked by seizures so violent some have bitten
off teeth, according to the California Marine Mammal Center.
   So far, 28 sea lions stricken with the new malady have been
found on beaches and trucked to the center, located at an old Army
fort in Marin County, said center spokeswoman Mary Jane Schramm.
   Twenty of the sick mammals were found on the San Luis Obispo
County coast while others were scattered as far north as Santa Cruz.
   Eight sea lions have died, including one that had a very high
level of lead in its body.
   Schramm said the center is testing for lead poisoning as well as
arsenic, cadmimum, copper, iron and zinc. Other tests are designed
to find natural toxins or other compounds in the food chain.
   The first sick sea lion arrived April 30 at the center, which
was already packed with sea lions suffering from leptospirosis.
Schramm said that 105 sea lions have been diagnosed with that
disease since June 1, and more than half have died.
</TEXT>
