<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador-Massacre,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorney General's Office Implicates Soldiers in Massacre</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Army troops were responsible
for the massacre of 10 peasants last month, the attorney general's
office said today.
   Carlos Lazo, of the Attorney General's Human Rights Department,
told The Associated Press in a telephone interview that his office
requested the arrest of four soldiers implicated in the Sept. 21
slayings.
   The armed forces first said the dead were guerrillas, but then
changed its version to say eight civilians were killed in a
guerrilla ambush and army troops killed two of the ambushers.
   Lazo said the federal judge in San Sebastian, 30 miles east of
San Salvador, was asked to issue warrants for the arrests.
   San Sebastian's jurisdiction covers the village of San
Francisco, where, according to residents, soldiers of the Jiboa
battalion used grenades and rifle fire to kill seven men and three
women suspected of collaboration with leftist guerrillas.
   ``We have asked the judge to order the arrest of four people,
all soldiers in the Jiboa battalion,'' said Lazo. ``Sufficient
evidence exists to justify their detention; the testimony of the
relatives, the neighbors. The local and international press knows
that those who killed them (the victims) were soldiers.''
   Lazo said residents of San Francisco reported up to eight
soldiers were involved in the slayings and that more arrests could
be requested. He said no officer has been implicated.
   The slayings were the first massacre of such magnitude
attributed to government forces in four years.
   A 9-year-old civil war pitting leftist guerrillas against
government forces has killed an estimated 65,000 people, most of
them civilians.
</TEXT>
