<HEAD>Students Hold March To Protest Sexual Attacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>URBANA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of University of Illinois students
held a candlelight march and rally to protest a series of sexual
attacks on campus and the sexism that organizers said lies at the
root of the problem.
   ``Sexism, making women sex objects, is closely tied to the
degradation of women, which ultimately can lead to rape,'' said
Laurel MacLaren, one of the students who put together Wednesday
night's demonstration.
   The rally was called to ``raise the awareness'' of students to a
string of 13 sexual attacks since April by what police have labeled
a serial rapist.
   About 500 students, most holding candles, took part in the march
and the rally at the university's Urbana campus.
   ``I've been raped as many of the women on this campus have,''
student Jenny Keller said at the rally. ``We're not asking for
pity. ... We're demanding respect ... for the strength it takes to
go through this experience.''
   The rally also called attention to an increasing number of
``acquaintance rapes,'' in which the two people know each other,
MacLaren said.
   Another speaker at the rally, Jeff Jochims, president of the
university's Inter-fraternity Council, called on university
officials to solve ``the No. 1'' problem on the campus and ``make
sure this place is safe.''
   Rally organizers also condemned one of the traditional rites of
college life, the panty raid.
   ``We're working to change the image of fraternities,'' Jochims
said.
   Last month, a campus sorority, Gamma Phi Beta, signed a criminal
complaint against the Sigma Alpha Mu fraternity after fraternity
members raided the sorority house and attempted to throw a sorority
member into a shower, Jochims said.
