<HEAD>Drought Drops Tahoe's Level Below Its Rim, Outflow Stops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAHOE CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lake Tahoe has dropped below the level
of its outlet for only the fifth time in 54 years, cutting off its
flow into the Truckee River.
   The Truckee provides water for Reno residents, Pyramid Lake and
Fallon-area farmers. Federal Watermaster Garry Stone said Thursday
that water from Donner Lake and from various creeks and streams
will keep the Truckee flowing downstream from Tahoe.
   Through Reno, 30 miles downstream from Tahoe, the current flow
is a sluggish 10 cubic feet per second.
   Stone said talks are continuing on whether to seek permission to
pump from Tahoe. That last occurred in the Dust Bowl year of 1934.
