<HEAD>Preservationist Vows To Continue Fight After Losing Hotel Battle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One Art Deco hotel is now in ruins, but
the Miami Design Preservation League says that no more Deco
buildings will fall in Miami Beach's South Beach section.
   ``We know that we have had many successes in getting the world's
attention for the Art Deco District,'' Nancy Liebman, the group's
acting director, said shortly after the 39-year-old three-story
Senator Hotel was razed Wednesday to clear the way for a parking
lot.
   ``We are proud that we have changed the laws so that this can
never happen again,'' she said.
   The city of Miami Beach amended its ordinances after the Royale
Group, which owned the Senator, got a permit to destroy it, Liebman
said.
   ``The preservation board now has the authority to deny
demolition of important structures,'' she said.
   The Senator featured etched glass that had appeared in books and
magazines around the world. Royale said it was required to provide
parking as a condition to obtain loans for refurbishing other
properties it owns in the Art Deco district.
