<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Wright-Dukakis     10-13 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wright-Dukakis,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wright to Dukakis: Throw Out TV Ads, Talk to American People</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Debate Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Free advice to Michael Dukakis from House
Speaker Jim Wright: Get rid of your slick commercials, forget your
media advisers and simply talk to the American people.
   ``He's got to seize every opportunity that he has, be on any
talk show he can be on, get rid of these commercials that try to
hawk the candidate and party like toothpaste or soap flakes,''
Wright told reporters in answer to a question Thursday.
   ``People who know Mike Dukakis, they like him, they trust him,
they admire him, they respect him as a person, as a human being, a
warm individual with feelings and convictions,'' the Texas Democrat
said.
   He said Dukakis, trailing George Bush in the polls as Election
Day nears, should go on television and talk directly to the voters,
just as Wright said he did when he faced a critical House race in
Texas.
   ``Get on the tube and look people in the eye and talk with them
earnestly and let them get to know Mike Dukakis,'' Wright said.
``That's what we need to do, and when that happens, we're going to
win.
   ``I think the media advisers are too clever by half, and I've
always believed this,'' Wright said.
   In a personal example, he spoke of a major threat he had in a
campaign once.
   Against the recommendations of his advisers, Wright said, he
bought 30 minutes of television time to speak to voters in his
district.
   ``All the professionals, the cynics, the consultants said, `Oh,
no, you cannot hold them for 30 minutes. God almighty, they'll tune
you out,''' he said. Instead, he said, he program brought 2,000
phone calls offering help.
   ``They can't tell me that people won't listen to something
serious,'' he said. ``You don't have to get into a slogan and make
it into a cheap contest of carnival barkers. This is a serious
business.''
   Taking a shot at George Bush's Republican campaign, he said,
``For any party to try to claim the American flag as its exclusive
property surely is beneath the honor and the dignity of a nation
like this.''
</TEXT>
