<HEAD>Awards Given for Famine Relief Efforts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Americans and three private institutions
were honored Thursday at the State Department for their
contributions to ending world hunger. A sixth American was honored
posthumously.
   The Presidential End Hunger Awards, given annually since 1983,
are designed to increase public understanding of the severity of
world hunger and to promote public interest and involvement in the
search for solutions.
   their categories are:
   Eliza M. Carney, of Phoenix, Ariz., director of the World Hunger
Ecumenical Arizona Task Force (WHEAT), Individual Achievement. Ms.
Carney is credited with establishing, with the The winners and help of
churches, a
network in metropolitan Phoenix to alleviate hunger.
