<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Congress-Drugs 2ndLd-Writethru a0619 10-13 0730</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Congress-Drugs, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0619,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Poised to Begin Considering Drug Bill</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 4 grafs new with Senate commencing debate on bill and
moving to a death penalty amendment; picks up 4th graf pvs,
Democratic and</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate, beginning working on a $2.6
billion drug bill, today debated an effort by liberal senators to
strip a provision providing the death penalty for drug offenders
who kill.
   ``I don't believe our society should ever be one to say, `This
one lives and this one dies,''' said Sen. Mark Hatfield, R-Ore.,
the amendment's sponsor.
   Hatfield's proposal would substitute a mandatory life sentence
without possibility of parole for the death penalty. It would also
require mandatory life imprisonment for many violent drug offenses
for which the bill would impose 20-year sentences.
   Leaders of both parties seemed to have worked out a plan
allowing the chamber to begin shaping the bill into its final form.
Lawmakers held several meetings this morning to work out the final
problems.
   Democratic and Republican leaders reached agreement late
Wednesday on a procedure for winnowing a list of more than 100
amendments _ many of them controversial _ down to about 56. The
Senate was expected to decide whether to accept the plan today and,
if adopted, begin debating the legislation.
   Lawmakers who helped shape the formula warned that if the
procedure was not adopted, Congress might adjourn for the year
without drug legislation to show the voters.
   ``If people want to fight over the margins in the next few days,
we'll probably end up going home with nothing,'' said Sen. Sam
Nunn, D-Ga.
   The bipartisan bill would authorize additional money for
federal, state and local law enforcement agencies and for alcohol
and drug abuse programs. Sixty percent of the money authorized by
the measure would be directed to treatment programs and 40 percent
would be for law enforcement.
   But the legislation lacks a mechanism to pay for the very
programs it would create. Lawmakers expect the government to be
able to scrape together $450 million to finance the measure during
the next year, far short of the $1.4 billion that would be needed
for that period.
   The bill also would allow capital punishment for some drug
offenders who commit murder, lengthen sentences for drug offenders
who commit violent crimes, and crack down on money laundering by
requiring better record-keeping by institutions that sell cashier's
and traveler's checks.
   With all 435 House seats and 33 Senate seats being contested
Nov. 8, legislators have been eager to adjourn for the year and
campaign with a tough drug measure to boast about. Congressional
leaders have been hoping to end the 100th Congress by Friday.
   But those plans _ and ultimate passage of the drug legislation _
have been jeopardized by amendments waiting in the wngs that were
likely to spark volatile debates.
   House leaders already have warned representatives to be prepared
to work next week. Senior members of the Senate told their
colleagues that the drug measure could be completed by Friday if
things go smoothly, or next week if disputes persist.
   ``If that's what senators want, that's all right with me,'' said
Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan. ``I'm not running this
year.''
   Under the agreement to pare down the list of amendments, about
30 of the proposals would be folded into the legislation. Those
would include provisions stiffening penalties for some drug
offenses, giving authorities more weapons for combating child
pornography, and making a newly created federal ``drug czar'' a
member of the White House National Security Council.
   A red-hot dispute over a proposal limiting the rights of
convicted criminals to appeal their sentences on procedural grounds
would be settled by having Congress revisit the issue next year.
   Eight other amendments would be voted on separately, including a
provision that is expected to lose that would eliminate the bill's
death penalty language.
   Eighteen other amendments would be considered if Senate leaders
from both parties agreed to put them to votes.
   The House on Sept. 22 passed a similar bill containing the death
penalty and many provisions eroding the rights of suspects in favor
of law enforcement authorities. President Reagan has said he
prefers the House legislation.
   Before the measure can be sent to the president for his
signature, the two chambers will have to fashion a compromise bill.
</TEXT>
