<HEAD>Royals' Owner Ups Scholarship Offer To Entire Class</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ewing Kauffman, co-owner of the Kansas
City Royals and chairman of a pharmaceutical company, is sweetening
the pot for about 300 high school students he already has agreed to
send to college.
   Michael Herman, president of the Kauffman Foundation, announced
an added incentive for members of a freshman class who are enrolled
in Project Choice. The sweetener will pay each student $50 a
semester for attending classes regularly at Westport High School.
   ``If you're not in school then you can't become an academic
success,'' Herman told several hundred students and their parents
at the school Wednesday night. Many of the families are poor.
   Project Choice, started last spring and administered through the
foundation, guaranteed a college education for members of last
year's eighth-grade class at Westport Middle School who meet
requirements.
   Students must graduate from high school in four years, attend
school regularly and avoid parenthood and drug and alcohol abuse.
Parents must take an active part in their child's education.
   The foundation will pay tuition, fees, books and room and board
for college or vocational school.
   Kauffman, 72, founder and chairman of the board of Marion
Laboratories, recently made Forbes magazine's list of 400 richest
Americans. His net worth was listed at $740 million.
