<HEAD>People In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Helen Hayes, known as the first lady of
American theater, got the gift of a drama scholarship fund in her
name for her 88th birthday.
   Friends of the actress, Col. Barney Oldfield and his wife, Vada,
said the fund, established in his will, will give $1,000 each year
to a student at the University of Nebraska. Miss Hayes' birthday
was Monday.
   Oldfield and Miss Hayes first worked together as judges for the
Great Steamboat Races on the Mississippi River in the early 1980s.
   ``She is the most remarkable woman, and happens to be a great
star, but she also is the kind of person who is an inspiration,''
said Oldfield, who graduated with his wife from the university in
1933.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ann Robinson is delighted the ``War Of The
Worlds'' television series that began this week has remained true
to some of the characters in the movie released 35 years ago.
   Robinson is playing Sylvia Van Buren just as she did in the
movie of the story of a deadly invasion by Martians that terrified
believing radio listeners 50 years ago.
   The makers of the series, a current-day version of the story,
didn't have to ask Robinson twice.
   ``I was thrilled to death,'' Robinson said recently from her
home in Los Angeles. ``When I was 5, my father and I listened to
``War Of The Worlds'' on the radio. In 1953, I got to star in the
movie and in 1988 I'm in the television series.''
   In the movie, Robinson was the love interest of Gene Barry, the
movie's star.
   In the series, her character was committed to a mental hospital
for the past 35 years because no one believed she had witnessed an
alien invasion. She escapes when she hears the aliens are back.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German actress Nastassja Kinski and her
family have been granted permission to live in Fribourg state in
Switzerland, a local official said Thursday. Geneva authorities
denied the request earlier.
   Jean-Pierre Gianini, head of the office for residence permits,
said they decided the actress would contribute to the local economy
and culture.
   Swiss newspapers reported Thursday that Ms. Kinski plans to
start a film production company in Fribourg, and to work on behalf
of the Swiss Red Cross.
   Geneva authorities this summer rejected Ms. Kinski's request,
saying there was no guarantee she would contribute to the local
economy. Swiss states are limited in the number of residence
permits they can grant to foreigners.
   Ms. Kinski is married to producer Ibrahim Moussa and has two
children.
