granddaughter of acclaimed violinist Efrem Zimbalist Sr. and opera
star Alma Gluck, concedes that she's in a bit of a ``trough.''
   ``It's just that I got so burned out on `Remington,''' she said.
``I got a real bad taste for acting and fame, especially. The cost
just seemed too high a price to pay.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country singer Kenny Rogers, who says performing
on stage is addictive, hopes to stay hooked for as long as his
idol, Frank Sinatra.
   But at age 50, Rogers has decided to do it his way, which means
less touring, more time with his family and a new challenge _ a
one-hour talk-and-entertainment show on daytime television.
   ``Part of success for a man is knowing when you've done your
best and it's time to move on,'' Rogers said in an interview in the
November issue of McCall's magazine.
   Concert touring is a habit that's too hard to kick, he said, but
he wants to scale back. He wants more time for other things, but
also fears that fans ``have got to be getting sick of me.''
   For those who aren't, Rogers has a new album coming out in
January. And, he said, he'll keep singing for ``as long as anyone's
listening.''
   When in doubt, Rogers said, ``I've pulled back and said, `What
would Sinatra do?' There aren't many role models for people at my
level, and he's one of mine.''
</TEXT>
