<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Iran-Contra 1stLd-Writethru a0659 10-13 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0659,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hakim Seeks to Bar Testimony of Geneve Lawyer</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds 4 grafs of background on case</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran-Contra defendant Albert Hakim is trying
to invoke attorney-client privilege to bar the testimony of a
Geneva lawyer who helped him set up the secret financial network
used in the arms-for-hostage deals.
   Hakim has filed a motion to obtain details of everything that
Willard I. Zucker told prosecutors about the secret Swiss bank
accounts and off-shore shell companies that were conduits for
millions of dollars generated by the arms deals, according to court
papers.
   Zucker, a U.S. citizen who has lived in Switzerland for 20
years, operates a financial consulting business in Geneva that has
long overseen Hakim's banking interests in that country.
   A former Internal Revenue Service lawyer, Zucker has received
immunity from prosecution for his role in the Iran-Contra affair,
and is listed as a prospective witness by independent counsel
Lawrence E. Walsh.
   Zucker's business, Compagnie de Services Fiduciares, S.A. (CSF),
kept the financial records of the arms deals and set up a series of
dummy corporations and Swiss bank accounts for the arms
transactions.
   Hakim had ``long utilized the services of Mr. Zucker and CSF in
the conduct of his legal and business affairs,'' defense lawyers
said. ``In so doing, he has often entered into confidential
communications with Mr. Zucker for the purpose of securing both
opinions on law and legal services.''
   ``Mr. Zucker is a member of the bar who rendered legal services
to Mr. Hakim, and Mr. Hakim has insisted that all communications
with respect to those services remain confidential,'' defense
lawyers N. Richard Janis and Lawrence H. Wechsler said in a
pleading that was ordered unsealed Wednesday by U.S. District Judge
Gerhard A. Gesell.
   An accounting of the information Zucker provided Walsh ``may
well result in the suppression of any effort by the government to
introduce at any trial either the testimony of Mr. Zucker or any
information derived directly or indirectly from government contacts
with Mr. Zucker'' Hakim's lawyers said.
   Defense lawyers threatened to try to prevent Zucker from
testifying not only against Hakim but his three co-defendants in
the Iran-Contra conspiracy case: former national security adviser
John M. Poindexter, ex-White House aide Oliver L. North and Hakim's
former business partner, retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Richard V.
Secord.
   The four are charged with conspiring to defraud the government
by diverting profits from the U.S.-Iran arms sale to the Nicaraguan
rebels.
   Separate trials have been ordered for each defendant.
   Prosecutors said in a pleading filed Thursday they were ready to
begin North's trial in January. They opposed further delays in
pre-trial proceedings sought by North, contending the defense was
merely trying to delay the trial.
   Zucker's testimony would provide key evidence against all four
defendants about the clandestine network of Swiss bank accounts and
off-shore dummy corporations through which arms-sale profits were
diverted to the Contras.
   His testimony would also support a charge that Hakim and Secord
conspired to pay illegal gratuities to North, including the
creation of a $200,000 investment account at CSF and the
installation of a $13,800 security fence around the former White
House aide's home in Great Falls, Va.
   Zucker, an unindicted co-conspirator in this count of the
indictment, met with North's wife, Elizabeth, in Philadelphia in
March 1986 and later with Washington attorney David Lewis, the
indictment says.
   Lewis told congressional investigators that Zucker wanted him to
pass money to Mrs. North that would be disguised as compensation
for her role in a real estate deal. Lewis, who declined to become
involved, testified that Zucker told him the money was owed North.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
