<DOCNO> AP881013-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 1523EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Shroud Bjt   10-13 0798</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shroud, Bjt,0822</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shroud Debunked as Christ's Burial Cloth, But Mystery Remains</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos ROM2, NY16</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TURIN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Shroud of Turin is only about 700 years
old and cannot be the authentic burial cloth of Jesus Christ as
believed by millions over the centuries, the archbishop of Turin
said Thursday.
   Cardinal Anastasio Ballestrero's announcement that he accepted
the results of dating tests conducted by three laboratories ended a
debate over the origin of the cloth that has raged for hundreds of
years.
   But another mystery remains unsolved: how the shroud came to
bear the image of what scientists have called a real human form of
a whipped and crucified man.
   Rejecting attempts to brand the shroud a fake, Ballestrero
stressed that for the Roman Catholic church, the linen cloth
remains a venerated object and a powerful symbol of faith.
   ``The church believes in the image and not in the history,
because this image of Jesus Christ is very interesting and the
people believe very much in Jesus,'' he said.
   Ballestrero told a news conference at the headquarters of his
archdiocese that carbon-14 tests by labs in the United States,
Britain and Switzerland concluded with 95 percent accuracy that the
shroud cannot be more than 728 years old, dating to between 1260
and 1390.
   ``I see no reason for the church to put these results in
doubt,'' the cardinal said.
   The Vatican's official newspaper L'Osservatore Romano did not
comment on the announcement, but printed the text of the cardinal's
statement on page two.
   Vatican Radio, in reporting the news, said ``The chapter is not
closed,'' noting that the problems of the image on the cloth still
remain.
   Although the church has never claimed it as a holy relic, the
shroud has been revered for centuries by millions who believed it
was the actual cloth that Christ was wrapped in after he died on
the cross. Others called it a clever forgery.
   The sheet _ 14 feet, 3 inches long and 3 feet, 7 inches wide _
bears a faint, yellowish negative image of the front and back of a
man with a thorn mark on the head, lacerations from flogging on the
back, and bruises on the shoulders.
   For years, church officials refused to let scientists study the
cloth.
   U.S. scientists who subjected it to rigorous chemical, computer
and photographic analysis in 1981 concluded that it was ``a real
human form of a whipped and crucified man and not the product of an
artist.''
   Luigi Gonella, scientific adviser to the cardinal, said the
American scientists found the image resulted from chemical changes
in the linen while it was in contact with the body.
   Gonella said the church was particularly angered by claims that
since the shroud dates to medieval times it must be a fake.
   ``A forgery means it was made for the specific purpose of
deceiving people,'' Gonella said. ``This is possible but there is
no proof of that. It could be a medieval icon. We don't even know
how it was made.''
   ``Believers will be hurt much more by the comments about the
results than by the results themselves,'' Gonella added.
   Pope John Paul II finally gave the go-ahead for testing in 1986.
   In April, the shroud was taken from its red silk wrapping inside
a silver chest on an altar in Turin's cathedral. Postage-sized
samples of the cloth were snipped off for the carbon-14 testing.
   Carbon-14 is widely used to date archaeological finds. It is a
radioactive isotope whose half-life _ the time required for
disintegration of half its atoms _ is known. Thus the amount of
carbon-14 present in an object can reveal its approximate age.
   The laboratories that conducted the tests were at the University
of Arizona; the Swiss Federal Institute of Technology at the
University of Zurich; and Oxford University. All dated the shroud
to between 1260 and 1390, Gonella said.
   Ballestrero said church officials in Turin received official
results from the three labs on Sept. 28 and delivered them
personally to the Vatican the next day. Vatican spokesman Joaquin
Navarro flanked the cardinal at the news conference.
   Witnesses from as far back as the 12th century reported seeing
the shroud in the imperial palace at Constantinople. The trail was
then lost until more than a hundred years later in 1354, when the
shroud was traced to Lirey, France.
   The cloth arrived in Turin in 1578, and has remained in its
silver chest here ever since. King Umberto II of Italy bequeathed
it to the pope upon his death in 1983.
   The shroud has occupied public attention so much it was even the
subject of a 1986 Broadway musical. The show, called ``Into the
Light,'' opened to negative reviews and closed after a week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881013-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 1531EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-DebateRdp Bjt   10-13 0781</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Debate Rdp, Bjt,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Hoping to Gain in Debate; Bush Looks to Protect Lead</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Debate begins at 9 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush and Michael Dukakis polished
their lines one final time Thursday in advance of their prime-time
debate, the Republican looking to protect his lead in the polls and
the Democrat hoping for a breakthrough to transform the
presidential race in its final weeks.
   There was no underestimating the stakes as the two would-be
presidents pointed toward their 90-minute, 9 p.m. EDT face-off on
the UCLA campus, their second and final debate of the campaign.
   Pre-debate polls gave Bush a narrow lead among voters nationwide
with a little less than four weeks remaining to the election.
State-by-state breakdowns indicated the vice president's Electoral
College advantage was more formidable, although several large
battleground states _ enough to tip the balance of the election _
appeared unsettled.
   Debate sponsors were looking for a television audience in the
tens of millions for the second and final clash between the
Republican vice president and the Democratic governor of
Massachusetts.
   The audience included vice presidential candidates Lloyd Bentsen
and Dan Quayle, who held their only debate of the campaign eight
days ago in Omaha, Neb.
   The debate scenery, a red-carpeted stage, with a blue backdrop
and oak lecterns, was the same one used in the first Bush-Dukakis
debate in North Carolina last month and again in the vice
presidential debate in Nebraska. This time it was uncrated and
erected in Pauley Pavilion, home of the UCLA basketball team.
   The format for evening was identical to that of the earlier
clashes, with the candidates responding to questions from a panel
of reporters, but having no formal opportunity to question each
other.
   The panelists were moderator Bernard Shaw of Cable News Network,
Andrea Mitchell of NBC, Ann Compton of ABC and Margaret Warner of
Newsweek magazine.
   Neither Bush nor Dukakis campaigned during the day, although
both met with aides and arranged to view the debate set a few hours
before the event began.
   Dukakis took his customary morning ``power walk,'' with hand
weights. Bush planned no pre-debate events outside his hotel other
than his private walkthrough at the debate site.
   Meanwhile, Bentsen spent the morning in Washington, urging his
colleagues in Congress to get behind the national ticket. ``I was
asking for their support and commitment and their leadershiop in
their own states and we had a very enthusiastic meeting,'' he said
after meeting in closed session with Democratic members of the
Senate.
   Quayle, who campaigned in three states, took time out to
telephone Bush with his advice: ``Hit it over centerfield.''
   From both campaigns the word was that the biggest task of the
two presidential candidates in their final debate was to define
where they would lead the country.
   Bush said Wednesday he wanted to help Americans ``understand
what my heartbeat is, what I really care about.''
   Dukakis said, ``One of the nice things about debates is they get
people out from behind the balloons and out of the flag factory and
it gets them to address the issues.''
   House Speaker Jim Wright of Texas offered Dukakis advice from a
distance: Get rid of his slick television commercials and talk
straight to the voters.
   ``He's got to seize every opportunity that he has, be on any
talk show he can be on, get rid of these commercials that try to
hawk the candidate and party like toothpaste and soap flakes,''
said Wright.
   The Commission on Presidential Debates took over sponsorship of
the encounter after the League of Women Voters abruptly backed out
after complaining that the candidates had refused to relinquish
control over such details as the format and membership of the panel
of questioners.
   Repeated national opinion surveys have said a majority of voters
question Quayle's qualifications to succeed to the presidency and
suggest the Indiana senator could cost the Republican ticket votes
on Nov. 8.
   But a Washington Post-ABC state-by-state survey of 10,000 likely
voters, made public on the eve of the debate, said Bush led solidly
in 21 states with a total of 220 electoral votes _ just 50 short of
the total needed to win. Dukakis was firmly ahead in only three
states with 30 electoral votes. The survey was conducted over a
three-week period beginning Sept. 21.
   Debate preparations for Bush and Dukakis followed the same
pattern they used before their first confrontation at Wake Forest
University in Winston-Salem, N.C.
   Dukakis rehearsed with Washington attorney Robert Barnett acting
as a stand-in for Bush.
   Former deputy Treasury Secretary Richard Darman took the role of
Dukakis during the Bush preparations.
</TEXT>
