<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hirohito     10-13 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hirohito,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emperor's Jaundice Worsens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito's jaundice worsened Thursday, and
doctors gave him another blood transfusion to fight his anemia,
court officials said.
   Imperial Household Agency spokesman Kenji Maeda said the
87-year-old emperor discharged more blood. Two court physicians
were spending Thursday night watching over the world's oldest
living monarch.
   Doctors say Hirohito's enlarged pancreas apparently has blocked
his bile duct, sending bile into his bloodstream and causing
jaundice.
   The emperor's kidney and liver functions also appeared to be
worsening, news reports said.
   With the 0.4-pint transfusion Thursday, Hirohito has received
more than 15{ pints of blood since his condition worsened 24 days
ago.
   Court officials have not confirmed or denied reports that he has
cancer in the area of his upper intestine.
   Officials of the governing Liberal Democratic Party said Prime
Minister Noboru Takeshita would resume trips outside of Tokyo to
campaign for a tax reform plan, Kyodo News Service reported.
   Takeshita suspended the trips after Hirohito's condition became
serious, but decided to resume them next week because his condition
apparently stabilized, Kyodo said.
   Concerts, festivals, political meetings, sports meets and other
events have been canceled because of Hirohito's illness. Some
Japanese have criticized the cancellations as an overreaction.
   Some courses at Tohoku University in Sendai in the northwest
were canceled Thursday after about 50 students built barricades and
began a strike. They said Hirohito's illness was being used to
build sympathy for and strengthen the imperial system, Kyodo said.
   Some Japanese fear a strengthened imperial system could bring a
resurgence of the nationalism and militarism that characterized
Japan during World War II.
   The militarists who controlled Japan during the war used
Hirohito's name to rally public support for Japan's invasion of
other Asian countries.
   Japan's postwar constitution defines the emperor as ``the symbol
of the state'' and gives him no real political power.
</TEXT>
