<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     10-13 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aquino Says Government Will File Charges Against Marcos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino said
Thursday the government will charge Ferdinand Marcos with crimes
allegedly committed during his 20 years as president.
   Mrs. Aquino also said Marcos, who fled to exile in Hawaii in
1986, will be allowed to return to the Philippines to answer the
charges. Philippine law prohibits criminal trials in absentia.
   ``Sometime in the future, we will file a criminal case or cases
against Mr. Marcos,'' Mrs. Aquino said. ``At that time, we will
have to allow him to return to face the trial. No definite time
frame can be given as of now for this.''
   She issued the statement one day after a Filipino official
indicated her government may delay filing charges against the
ousted president until U.S. authorities decide whether to prosecute
him.
   The Philippine government claims Marcos and his associates stole
up to $10 billion before his administration was toppled in the 1986
uprising that swept Mrs. Aquino to power.
   The Los Angeles Times reported Tuesday that the U.S. State
Department's legal officer, Abraham Sofaer, recommended that U.S.
authorities allow Marcos to surrender millions of dollars he
allegedly embezzled in return for avoiding prison.
   The plea bargain proposal reportedly involves an investigation
of Marcos by U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani in New York into
alleged illegal money transfers and other activities.
   On Wednesday, Mateo Caparas, chairman of the Philippines'
Presidential Commission on Good Government, said Marcos simply
wants to return to the Philippines to evade prosecution in the
United States.
   Caparas, who said he was speaking for Mrs. Aquino, said the
government would not permit filing of charges here ``to be used as
an excuse by Mr. Marcos to escape his indictment abroad.''
   Caparas' commission is in charge of recovering money allegedly
taken by Marcos.
   In other developments, the military said two Filipino guards at
the U.S.-run Clark Air Base were killed and another wounded in a
shootout with police outside the facility.
   Police said the shooting erupted late Wednesday about 100 yards
from the main gate of Clark Air Base after a city patrolman noticed
three passengers in a jeep who appeared to be carrying concealed
weapons.
   The patrolman reported the sighting to a passing patrol car,
which stopped to search the passengers. The guards, who were in
civilian clothes, drew pistols and shooting broke out, the report
said.
   It was unclear from the report who fired first.
   The dead were identified as Philippine Air Force Sgt. Ramon
Estrada and Sgt. Carlos Bellan, who were assigned to the Clark Air
Base Command, a Filipino unit which provides security at the
installation.
   The wounded sergeant, also assigned to the command, was
identified as Henry Bernal. He was taken to a hospital on the base.
</TEXT>
