<HEAD>Indepedent Committee Set Up To Support Jailed Publisher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Independent Czech journalists have set up
a committee to support a Catholic publisher jailed by authorities
for circulating underground litererature, an emigre source reported
Thursday.
   A group of 88 publishers and journalists signed an appeal for
Ivan Polansky that was published in Prague on Wednesday, according
to the London-based Palach Press, an independent publisher of news
on Czechoslovakia.
   The Supreme Court of the republic of Slovakia on Aug. 30 upheld
a four-year sentence against Polansky, 52, a Catholic activist,
saying he was guilty of ``subversive activity,'' the state news
agency CTK reported.
   ``Independent publishing is a legitimate act of civil defense
against the rulers' total manipulation of society,'' the statement
was quoted as saying.
   ``We cannot and will not be silent over the fact that Ivan
Polansky has, in a way, been sent to prison and serves his sentence
for us all,'' the committee said.
