<1ST_LINE>r w AM-NoriegaAccount 1stLd-Writethru a0677 10-13 0763</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Noriega Account, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0677,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress Told Earlier of Noriega Link With Luxembourg Bank</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 4 grafs with newspaper report on probe before last
graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An international banker arrested by the U.S.
Customs Service last week had told Congress earlier that he managed
a $20 million secret bank account for Panamanaian ruler Manuel
Antonio Noriega, according to Senate testimony made available
Thursday.
   The witness, Amjad Awan, an officer of the Bank of Credit and
Commerce International (BCCI), said the account was used to make
cash payments to Panamanian politicians and to pay travel and creit
card expenses for Noriega and his family.
   Awan said he flew to Panama monthly to report to Noriega on the
status of his account.
   ``I made an effort to cultivate him,'' Awan told investigators
on Sept. 30 at a private session of the Senate Foreign Relations
subcommittee on terrorism and narcotics.
   Senators attending the session were told Awan's testimony would
be closely held because of ``our concern for Mr. Awan's life,''
subcomittee counsel Jack Blum said in the testimony released by the
office of Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass.
   A spokesman for Kerry, the subcommittee chairman, said that
following Awan's arrest the panel voted unanimously to release the
testimony and send a copy of it to the Justice Department.
   Awan was indicted this week on charges of money laundering. His
bank, which is based in Luxembourg, was charged in an indictment
handed down in Tampa, Fla., with laundering $14 million in
narcotics profits for members of Colombia's Medellin drug cartel.
   In his Senate testimony, Awan, 41, a native of Pakistan who
holds British citizenship, denied any knowlege of money laundering
and said his bank made an effort to avoid any contact with illicit
cash. He also said he had no knowlege of whether or not Noriega
received drug payments.
   But he said he made an effort to solicit accounts from Noriega
and in 1982 received from him a deposit of ``several hundred
thousand dollars'' in cash.
   ``He was head of (Panamanian) intelligence at the time and told
me that this was a secret account, a secret service account,'' Awan
said. ``I was told that the account should be kept in a highly
confidential and secret manner.''
   Awan said the balances in Noriega's account went up and down but
at one point reached a high of ``$20 million, maybe $25 million.''
   He said he paid cash out of the account only after receiving a
note signed by Noriega, preceded by a telephone call ``telling me
to expect the person to come in to get these funds.''
   To whom was the money paid? Awan was asked.
   ``Politicians,'' he replied. ``This was during the time of the
elections in Panama.''
   He said the expenses for Noriega's trips abroad also were paid
out of the account, as were personal expenses charged to credit
cards held by Noriega, his wife and their three daughters.
   Awan said that when he reported to Noriega on his account, the
Panamanian was not interested in his balance but wanted to know how
money had been spent.
   ``When I told him that this month we debited $50,000 to your
account, he wanted to know what that $50,000 consisted of. So it
was basically the airline bills, hotel bills, VISA card debits ...
limousines, reservations, theater tickets, schools, hospitals.''
   The St. Petersburg (Fla.) Times on Thursday quoted an
unidentified Justice Department official who worked on both the
Noriega and banker cases as saying: ``We have never been able to
identify a Noriega bank account outside of Panama. We would like to
hope this account would be a breakthrough.''
   He said U.S. investigators hope to obtain detailed records of
the account by the end of the week after the necessary paperwork is
completed.
   Records and sworn testimony presented earlier this year to
Senate investigators have shown that ``there's no doubt that BCCI
definitely handled Noriega money,'' the official told the Times.
   Both Noriega's and BCCI's alleged involvement in laundering drug
proceeds were also described in other Senate subcommittee testimony
by Leigh Ritch and Steven Kalish, two convicted Tampa-based
smugglers who are alleged to have laundered at least $4 million
through Panamanian banks.
   A week after his Senate testimony, Awan and four of other BCCI
officials were arrested in Tampa in a Customs Service sting
operation. They had been drawn to Tampa in response to a faked
wedding invitation sent by an undercover customs agent who had
known them in the two years he posed as a money launderer.
</TEXT>
