<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland     10-13 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland,0540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Gives Opposition Second Chance To Join Gov't</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Mieczyslaw Rakowski on
Thursday gave the opposition a second chance to join his government
and proposed a communist-dominated Cabinet to parliament for
approval.
   Rakowski told the Sejm, Poland's parliament, that he had
reserved four spots for the ``constructive opposition,'' including
a post as deputy premier and the Labor Ministry.
   ``The citizens to whom I proposed these posts refused to accept
them,'' Rakowski said in his first major policy address.
   ``One can look at these refusals according to the saying, `It's
never too late.' Due to all this, I leave all those posts vacant.
The doors remain open,'' he said.
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa said acceptance of government
posts by the opposition depended on whether the government could
bring about change and accept the banned union.
   ``I'm not interested in the government and in power. I'm
interested in structural changes and Soldarity ... If there is
pluralism and Solidarity, those people who refused to accept
government posts will have an open road,'' Walesa said.
   Rakowski bumped several senior members reponsible for the
government's failing economic reform program and proposed a new
generation of younger, little-known party officials to oversee
economic affairs.
   Deputy Prime Minister Czeslaw Sadowski, the government's
economic planning chief, and Deputy Prime Minister Zbignew
Szalajda, who had charge of the industry sector, lost their
portfolios.
   Economist Andrzej Wroblewski, 38, was nominated to head the
important finance ministry. Dominik Jastrzebski, 46, was proposed
as Minister of Foreign Economic Cooperation, essential as Poland
tries to increase its exports.
   Rakowski proposed nine new ministers, five from the governing
Polish United Workers' (Communist) Party, one from the Peasants'
Party, and two from the Democratic Party. Both parties are allies
of the communists.
   Isabella Planeta Malecka, the proposed health minister, was the
only woman and only non-party member nominated.
   Rakowski, however, retained three senior communist officials in
key positions _ Interior Minister Czeslaw Kiszczak, Foreign
Minister Tadeusz Olechowski and Defense Minister Florian Siwicki.
   Parliament will convene Friday to vote on the proposed
candidates.
   Rakowski acknowledged that Poland found itself in a difficult
situation, but held out hope that planned talks between the
government and the opposition could lead to change.
   ``We approach it with the best of will. We are aiming for
reasonable compromise which would ensure the maximum of possible
change,'' Rakowski said.
   Authorities promised the talks following strikes in August,
Poland's worst labor unrest in seven years.
   The talks, scheduled to begin next week, will discuss the
political and economic crisis and consider the future of
Solidarity, which was the Soviet bloc's only recognized trade union
until it was suppressed in 1981.
   When he was named the new prime minister, Rakowski said he hoped
to form a government of people with ``reformist attitudes'' that he
hoped would broaden the communist-dominated government and gain
society's support.
   Parliament approved Rakowski, former party propaganda chief and
Solidarity foe, on Sept. 27.
   Rakowski replaced Zbigniew Messner, whose entire Cabinet
resigned Sept. 19 after fierce criticism for mishandling the
economic reform program.
</TEXT>
