<DOCNO> AP881013-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 1619EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Yugoslavia     10-13 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia,0589</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Montenegro Bans Rallies, Police Chief Steps Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities banned street rallies
Thursday in the southern republic of Montenegro and the police
chief of that area resigned after police used clubs and tear gas to
break up anti-government protests.
   In Belgrade, Communist Party leaders debated the legacy of late
leader Josip Tito, who has been blamed for forming a decentralized
government unable to deal with the country's worst economic crisis
in four decades.
   The weekend protests in Montenegro were the latest in almost
daily rallies driven by hundreds of thousands of Serbs pressing for
more control over Serbia's autonomous province of Kosovo. The
province's Slav minority, which is mainly Christian, allege
harassment by the mainly Moslem ethnic Albanian majority.
   Communists in several regions of Yugoslavia have stepped up
security alerts for the police, army and civilian defense units
following last weekend's events, said sources who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   The ban and the resignation of Montenegro's interior minister,
Lazar Djodjic, were apparently moves to defuse three months of
protests. Demonstrators also are protesting 217 percent inflation,
15 percent unemployment and wages of less than $100 a month.
   The rallies, backed by Serbian Communist Party chief Slobodan
Milosevic, have angered communist leaders in other republics.
Supporters of the ambitious Serbian leader have referred to him as
``the second Tito.''
   At the Belgrade meeting of the ruling party Politburo, Milosevic
and federal party chief Stipe Suvar angrily clashed over a June
statement by 19 intellectuals which blamed Tito's policies for the
country's present troubles.
   Suvar said the document was an ``assault on Tito by Serbian
nationalists'' and said Serbia's communists had failed to criticize
the document, according to the state-run news agency Tanjug.
   Milosevic said Suvar's comments were ``uncalled for'' since the
Serbian party was the first to denounce the intellectuals'
statement.
   Dusan Ckrebic, a prominent member of Serbia's leadership, said
Suvar's remarks were unacceptable because they represent serious
accusations against Serbia's leaders.
   The latest dispute forms the backdrop to a meeting Monday of the
Communist Party's policy-setting Central Committee where several
changes are expected in the leadership.
   Three senior Communists _ Yugoslavia's vice president, the head
of its official trade unions and a deputy premier _ were named
Thursday as leaders likely to lose their seats on the 165-member
Central Committee.
   The three were listed by a senior Communist member of the
Central Committee at a meeting in the northern republic of
Slovenia, according to Belgrade newspapers Thursday. The official
was not identified.
   The three include Stane Dolanc, who was seen as No. 2 to Tito in
the last years of Tito's undisputed 35-year rule. Tito died in 1980.
   Serbian nationalists criticize Dolanc, 62, as not tough enough
toward ethnic Albanian nationalists during 1981 racial riots in
Kosovo. Dolanc was interior minister at the time.
   Serbia, the largest of Yugoslavia's six republics, is now
pushing for more control over Kosovo and Vojvodina provinces.
   The other two men named as likely to lose their seats were
Marjan Orozen, head of the national trade union organization, and
Janez Zemljaric, a deputy premier.
   In Montenegro, where nationalist unrest turned into
anti-government protests by workers and students last weekend, the
republic's Communist Party Politburo announced ``urgent measures''
to stop demonstrations scheduled for this weekend.
   The authorities did not specify what ``urgent measures'' meant.
   Protesters have demanded the resignation of the republic's
leadership.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
