<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Jews     10-13 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Jews,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>East Germany To Announce Payments To Holocaust Victims, Bronfman
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germany is likely to announce
next week it will pay reparations to survivors of the Nazi
Holocaust, the head of the World Jewish Congress said Thursday.
   Edgar M. Bronfman, president of the New York-based Jewish
organization, said he would meet with East German leader Erich
Honecker on Monday in East Berlin to discuss the payments.
   ``In principle, what I'm going to be doing there is hopefully
getting the East German government to agree that East Germany too
has some responsibility for what took place in Germany during the
Second World War, particularly the Holocaust,'' Bro Asked by The Associated
Press if he expected the East Germans
would tell him during his visit that they have decided to make the
reparations payments, Bronfman said: ``Yes, I believe so.''nfman said.
  
   A final decision on the payments to victims of Nazi Germany
would mark a major change in the communist country's policies.
   Since the end of World War II, East Germany has argued it bore
no responsibility for Nazi atrocities because the nation was not
founded until 1949.
   West Germany signed an agreement in 1952 with the World Jewish
Congress to compensate Holocaust victims, and since then has paid
out more than $48 billion to survivors and their families. We East
Germany had been considering paying a up to $100 million to
Holocaust survivors and victims' families.
   ``For them now to take the proper moral position and say `Yes,
we will pay some reparations,' even if it is a token amount, will
be good news for the entire world,'' Bronfman said.
   He said East German reparations to survivors of Nazi atrocities
would be an important step in reminding the world what happened
during the Holocaust.
   ``Our position is it's not a question of just money, but that
the Holocaust has to be taught not just to Germans, but to
everyone,'' Bronfman said.
   Bronfman said he has resisted East German attempts to link
reparations to trade agreements with the United States.
   ``I know they are looking for trade agreements with the United
States, and I have said you cannot tie any payments you're going to
make to the victims of the Holocaust to any boons you might get
from the U.S. government,'' Bronfman said.
   Bronfman was in Bonn for a conference of the East-West Forum,
which he heads. The New York-based group consists of Western
intellectuals and politicians who meet to discuss developments in
East-West relations.
</TEXT>
