<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ArtTheft     10-13 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Art Theft,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dutch Paintings Stolen At Gunpoint</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two paintings by Dutch masters Frans
Hals and Jacob van Ruisdael were stolen at gunpoint from a small
museum early Thursday, police said.
   An armed man seized the caretaker and his wife at about 1:30
a.m. and forced them to let him into Mrs. van Aerden's Hostel
Museum in this central Dutch town, according to police spokeswoman
Ingrid Verbeek.
   She said the thief fled with two paintings _ a canvas by Hals
titled ``The Laughing Boys With The Beer Mug,'' worth at least
$438,000, and a Ruisdael painting, ``Forest Landscape With
Flowering Elder,'' for which no value was given.
   The couple, who lived on the premises, was released unharmed,
she said.
   The Hostel Museum, a privately owned museum built in 1670, is
part of a historic complex that houses nine elderly women and is
named after its founder, Maria van Aerden, Ms. Verbeek said.
   Its collection includes about 25 other paintings and a room with
period furniture, Ms. Verbeek said.
   Frans Hals, thought to have been born between 1580 and 1585, is
regarded as one of the most prominent Dutch landscape and portrait
painters.
   Jacob van Ruisdael, born in 1628, came from a family of painters
and art dealers from the city of Haarlem near Amsterdam.
   The disappearance of the two works comes after the theft in May
of three paintings by Vincent van Gogh, Paul Cezanne and Johan
Jongkind, from Amsterdam's Municipal Museum. Burglars smashed a
ground-floor window to get to the paintings, which were recovered
10 days later by an undercover police agent offering to buy them
for $1.1 million.
   That incident sparked a nationwide debate on the lax security in
the nation's museums. A recent government report severely
criticized security measures at museums that house the nation's
most valuable art works.
</TEXT>
