<DOCNO> AP881013-0187 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 1623EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Soviet-Medicine     10-13 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Soviet-Medicine,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S., Soviets Sign Joint Medical Research Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With a champagne toast, the United States and
the Soviet Union signed a five-year agreement Thursday which calls
for cooperative research programs to combat AIDS, drug abuse,
alcoholism and polio.
   Valentin Pokrovsky, president of the Soviet Academy of Medical
Science and head of a five-member Soviet delegation, expressed hope
that the agreement will mark the ``beginning of a wonderful long
road which we will travel together.''
   Signing for the United States at a brief ceremony at the
National Academy of Sciences was Samuel O. Thier, president of the
U.S. Institute of Medicine. He said the talks leading up to the
agreement were cordial and he predicted an ``extremely pleasant''
experience for both sides if the current atmosphere is maintained.
   The initial plans call for several joint activities in 1989,
including a symposium in the United States on AIDS research and a
meeting in the Soviet Union on the health effects of radiation.
   At a news conference Wednesday night, Pokrovsky said the last
summit meeting between President Reagan and Soviet President
Mikhail Gorbachev and the ``general political atmosphere'' have
contributed to closer cooperation. He wore a lapel pin displaying
the Soviet and American flags.
   Pokrovsky said U.S. experts are eager to draw on Soviet
expertise in the health effects of radiation, based on the
aftermath of the April 1986 accident at the Chernobyl nuclear power
plant.
   At the same time, he said, the program will offer Soviet experts
an opportunity to learn how Americans deal with AIDS, a disease
which has a far higher incidence in the United States than in the
Soviet Union.
   He said there has been only one Soviet fatality since March 1987
as a result of AIDS, but 81 persons who are not yet sick have been
diagnosed as carrying AIDS antibodies. He acknowledged that the
percentage of Soviet citizens who have been tested for AIDS is
relatively small _ 11 million.
   There have been about 300 cases of non-Soviet citizens in the
Soviet Union afflicted with AIDS, primarily students from African
countries where the disease is common.
   The two sides agreed that in the areas of alcoholism and drug
abuse, the focus will be on transmission to offspring,
identification of populations at risk and ways to prevent and treat
these problems.
   As for polio, the research will emphasize the application of
molecular biology to the monitoring and application of the disease.
   The two countries have existing cooperative programs in the
health area and the new agreement is designed to complement them.
   Prior to the signing ceremony, the Soviet delegates visited
research centers in Washington, D.C.; Baltimore; New York;
Hartford, Conn.; Boston; Atlanta; Kansas City, Mo.; St. Louis; and
Oak Ridge, Tenn.
</TEXT>
