<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan     10-13 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troubled Cities Quiet As Government Tightens Gun Laws</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police and army troops patrolled the
streets of two southern cities Thursday after the government
enacted tough new gun laws to combat ethnic violence that left
hundreds dead this month.
   Officials in Karachi, the country's largest city, and Hyderabad,
100 miles to the northeast, reported their districts were returning
to normal following five days of bloody clashes earlier this month
that left about 275 people dead.
   The violence involved ethnic Indians, who comprise more than 40
percent of the southern province of Sind and seek recognition as a
separate nationality, and militant Sindhis seeking independence for
the province.
   In Islamabad, the government Wednesday announced new laws that
provide prison sentences of up to 14 years for possession of
machine guns, other heavy weapons and their ammunition.
   On the night of Sept. 30, Sindhi militants sprayed the streets
of Hyderabad with gunfire, massacring nearly 200 people, mostly
ethnic Indians, authorities said.
   The violence touched off several days of retaliatory rioting in
Karachi, killing 60 more people, mostly Indians.
   Police said many of the deaths were caused by heavy weapons that
have surfaced in Pakistan during the 10-year war in neighboring
Afghanistan.
   The new laws announced by the government provide for special
courts and speedy trials for accused criminals, and authorize
provincial governments to use military force for public security.
   ``It does not mean that martial law been imposed in Sind
province,'' Justice Minister Wasim Sajjad told reporters in
Islamabad.
   ``The measures can be extended to other parts of Pakistan, if
similar incidents take place there,'' he said.
</TEXT>
