<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Iran     10-13 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Iran,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West Germans Say Iran Ready To Improve Relations With West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   High-ranking West German officials say
Iran has indicated a readiness to slowly move toward improving
relations with the United States and other Western nations.
   ``The signals are definately improving,'' said a West German
official, who spoke to The Associated Press on condition he not be
identified.
   ``There are influential people in the Tehran government who
understand that isolation is no longer politically or economically
viable. They know it is in the country's best interests to return
to a broader world community,'' the official said.
   He described the Iranian officials as ``pragmatists who clearly
see the value of rapproachment.''
   West Germany has long enjoyed good relations with Iran and with
Iraq, Tehran's bitter foe in the Persian Gulf war. The two
countries are observing a cease-fire.
   In recent months, Bonn officials have said they wanted to use
those good relations in efforts to improve conditions in the Middle
East and to help broker more ties between Iran and the United
States.
   Unlike the United States and other countries which broke off or
curtailed ties with Iran after Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini came to
power in 1979, West Germany has kept its relations active and has
sought to expand ties during the past year.
   West German officials in Bonn said those efforts paid off in
winning the release in September of West German hostage Rudolf
Cordes, held by pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem kidnappers in Lebanon.
   After Cordes' release, ``intensive talks continued with Iran on
the question of freedom for other hostages in Lebanon,'' the Bonn
source said.
   He added that those West German initiatives ``may have also
played a role'' in the release on Oct. 3 of Mithileshwar Sing, an
Indian professor who holds permanent U.S. residency status.
   Government sources in Bonn said Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich
Genscher was informed by Tehran at least a day in advance of the
release of hostage Singh and immediately told Secretary of State
George Shultz.
   ``The fact that we were informed of this latest release in
advance is also a sign of Tehran's appreciation of West Germany's
efforts in the region,'' one source told the AP.
   Genscher is scheduled to visit Tehran in November, and Bonn
sources said he would use the opportunity to deepen dialogue with
Iran on its relations with the West and to press for more help in
winning the release of the remaining foreign hostages in Lebanon.
   ``We hope that all sides will use this opportunity to improve
relations,'' he said.
</TEXT>
