<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-PressConferences     10-13 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Press Conferences,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fitzwater Defends Reagan's Record on Press Conferences</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater
suggested Thursday that the institution of the presidential press
conference is overrated as a means of communicating with the
American people.
   Defending the infrequency with which President Reagan has held
full-scale, primetime press conferences, Fitzwater said that no
chief executive should be expected to fulfill a quota on such
question-and-answer sessions.
   Fitzwater was responding during his daily news briefing to a
Harvard commission's report that said, among other things, that
White House news conferences have fallen into ``a serious state of
disarray'' under Reagan.
   The spokesman said the report Wednesday by the panel of
journalists and scholars did include several positive
recommendations on how to improve the conduct of these sessions.
The commission said, for instance, that press conferences should be
held mostly in the daytime.
   But it also criticized Reagan for holding too few press
conferences, saying his successor should ``take his lumps on a more
frequent basis.''
   ``The longer presidents go without a press conference, the
greater the suspicion that there is something to hide, and the
greater the pressure becomes for holding press conferences,'' the
16-member Harvard Commission on the Presidential News Conference
said.
   Reagan pledged to hold news conferences once a month, but has
held only 45 in more than 7{ years in office and once let 5{ months
pass without one. The last such session came at the end of the
seven-nation economic summit in Toronto last June.
   The report said that Reagan, ``although successful in the short
run in dodging difficult questions, suffers from the perception
that he is not really in charge of his own White House.''
   It recommended that presidents meet with the media twice a month
during daytime hours and limit televised evening news conferences
to six a year.
   Asked to respond to these and other criticisms, Fitzwater said,
``I don't think any president in good conscience would ever
commit'' to a specific number of formal press conferences.
   ``What I'm trying to say is that ... there is a diversity of
ways to communicate with the general public besides a press
conference,'' he added. ``We've held the press conferences that we
think are appropriate. We've held other kinds of press interviews
that we think are useful, and in the final analysis, you can be the
judge.''
   Asked what criteria are used to decide when the president holds
a news conference, Fitzwater said ``the guiding factor is what's in
the public interest and ways to communicate with the American
public.''
   The spokesman acknowledged that the White House intentionally
kept Reagan at a distance from the media during the height of the
Iran-Contra affair, but he said that was because officials didn't
want to say anything that might prejudice investigations into the
matter.
   ``We had no intention of holding press conferences and having
the president comment on ongoing investigations,'' Fitzwater said.
   He said Reagan will likely have another news conference before
the end of the year, but not before Election Day on Nov. 8.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
