<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Pork-BarrelBill     10-13 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pork-Barrel Bill,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Refuses To Consider Bill GOP Calls Pork-Barrel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Thursday refused to consider an
educational grant bill that Republicans attacked as pork-barrel
legislation because its price tag had grown from $750,000 to $60
million.
   The proposal, making its second trip to the House floor, didn't
even reach the debate stage because lawmakers voted 256-131 to
reject the rule that had to be approved before debate could begin.
   The opposition was led by Rep. Robert Walker, R-Pa., who pointed
out that the measure was far different and much costlier than the
version that had been approved by the House earlier in the session.
   The original bill merely authorized the Department of Education
to provide $750,000 to the Taft Institute, which uses public and
private money to provide summer programs for high school civics
studies teachers.
   By the time the Senate and House-Senate conferees had completed
their work, the package had swollen by nearly $60 million, with
grant authorizations targeted to some 16 schools and educational
programs.
   ``We're famous for having gargantuan side show freaks grow out
of nothing, but this one tops them all,'' said Rep. Jim Kolbe,
R-Ariz.
</TEXT>
