<DOCNO> AP881013-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 1958EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PlannedParenthood     10-13 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Planned Parenthood,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll Finds Support For Government Spending On Birth Control
Research</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LORI DODGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A majority of adults believe schools should
teach sex education and the federal government should put more
money into development of new birth control methods, according to a
poll released Thursday by Planned Parenthood Federation of America.
   The poll said 82 percent of the respondents favor government
spending on research and development of new and improved birth
control methods, while 16 percent of those polled do not.
   In addition, 59 percent of those interviewed said they thought
the European-developed birth control pill RU 486, which can
terminate a pregnancy in its first few weeks, should be made
available in this country. Thirty-three percent disagreed.
   Humphrey Taylor, president of Louis Harris, said the poll also
found that abortion is becoming a less controversial issue.
   In 1979, 38 percent said abortion was a decisive issue in
choosing a candidate for elective office. That number dropped in
1982 to 28 percent and in 1988 to 18 percent. Of the 18 percent, 9
percent said they could not vote for a pro-choice candidate and 9
percent said they could not vote for an anti-abortion candidate.
   ``So one clear finding is that a lot of the heat is going out of
the abortion issue and that political candidates in 1988 need not
worry as much as they have in the past about losing votes on it _
one way or the other,'' Taylor said.
   Results of the poll, conducted by Louis Harris and Associates,
were released at the start of Planned Parenthood's annual meeting
in St. Louis. The findings were based on telephone interviews
conducted in May with 1,250 randomly selected adults nationwide.
The poll's margin of error was 3 percent.
   Anne Saunier, Planned Parenthood's chairwoman, said that of the
6 million pregnancies in the United States each year, half are
unintended. Of the unintended pregnancies, half end in abortion,
she said.
   More than 1 million teen-agers become pregnant each year, and
more than 80 percent of those pregnancies are unintended, she said.
   ``Obviously, something is wrong,'' Saunier said. ``The federal
government spends approximately $9 million on contraceptive
research each year _ less than is spent every 15 minutes for
defense in this country.''
   Saunier said 95 percent of Americans think teen-age pregnancy is
a serious problem, up 11 percent since a 1985 Planned
Parenthood@Harris survey. Sixty-two percent think the problem is
getting worse.
   At the same time, support for sex education in schools has grown
4 percent since 1985. This year's study found that 89 percent of
those polled think sex education should be provided by schools, and
10 percent do not.
   Americans also think school health clinics should be allowed to
refer sexually active students to outside family planning clinics,
Saunier said. According to the poll, 80 percent favor establishing
links between schools and family planning clinics, while 18 percent
oppose the idea, she said.
   The research found that 73 percent of those interviewed
supported making birth control information and contraceptives
available in school health clinics, while 25 percent opposed it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
