<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Welfare-Vega     10-13 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Welfare-Vega,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Welfare Overhaul Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Evelyn Vega, a single mother and former
welfare recipient, considers herself living proof of the gains she
believes other women can make under the welfare bill signed by
President Reagan on Thursday.
   Three years ago, Ms. Vega, 28, of Stamford, Conn., was on
welfare and could not read or write, much less hold a job.
   Now she manages a fast-food store, has her own car and hopes to
send her three daughters to college.
   Other welfare recipients can do the same, she said shortly after
attending the White House Rose Garden ceremony where Reagan signed
the measure that will offer welfare recipients education, training
and work programs.
   ``I'm a happy person now that I'm working and I'm not on
welfare,'' said Ms. Vega. ``Now that the government did all this,
it could be a chance to help a lot of women like me.''
   Ms. Vega, whose parents separated when she was young, said she
largely raised herself after running away from home at age 10. She
and an older sister traveled from Puerto Rico to several U.S.
states, and Ms. Vega became pregnant for the first time at age 15.
   Three years ago, when all of her daughters were old enough to
attend school, Ms. Vega went to her welfare caseworker and said she
wanted to get off public assistance.
   ``I was so lonely. I was so scared,'' she said. ``I didn't want
to sit there with my girls going to school and me doing nothing.''
   Ms. Vega got a tutor, Page Oristano, from the Literacy
Volunteers of America, who began to teach her reading, writing and
basic skills such as how to look up a number in the telephone book.
   Eventually another agency agreed to help her find an entry-level
job in a fast-food store, and the manager there decided to help her
train for a management job.
   She passed the management test a month ago with 98 of 100
possible points. Several months earlier, Ms. Vega received her last
welfare check.
   ``I'm a single woman and I'm just taking care of my girls and
I'm happy,'' Ms. Vega said. ``Sometimes I feel like I'm drowning,
but it's OK.''
   She reads at the third- or fourth-grade level, and is more
proficient with material which is job related. She has a good
chance of finishing high school, Ms. Oristano said.
   Ms. Vega's goal is to send her daughters to college and
eventually attend college herself.
   Ms. Vega said she is convinced other welfare mothers can get off
public assistance.
   ``They've got to say, `I'm going to do it. I'm going to stick
with it and I'm not going to go back,''' she said.
   The Family Support Act signed by Reagan Thursday provides money
to states and requires them to offer education and job training to
women with children age 3 and over, and to put new pressure on
non-custodial parents to pay child support.
   The incentive to get off welfare ``has to come from the person
because the programs are there,'' Ms. Vega said.
   She and Ms. Oristano attended the bill-signing ceremony under
the auspices of the United Way, which supports many of the programs
that aided her.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881013-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 1740EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SudanAid 1stLd-Writethru a0705 10-13 0797</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan Aid, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0705,0819</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<HEAD>U.S.-Funded Airlift Begins Relief Flights in Sudan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout with new material and editing. Changes
byline. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S.-funded airlift started carrying
food and medical supplies on Thursday to thousands of starving
people in war-torn southern Sudan, Sudanese and United Nations
officials said.
   A U.N. official said the airlift aimed to send 12 planes daily
to transport supplies to the towns of Mairam, Kadugli, Muglad and
Abyei. Food was reported to have run out in Abyei last Wednesday.
   Government and U.N. officials implied that southern rebels
promised airlift organizers not to shoot down the planes.
Washington says the guerrillas in the past attacked civilian planes
and truck convoys, and interfered with the International Red Cross
in its effort to work out relief programs.
   The airlift began after Prime Minister Sadek el-Mahdi met in
Khartoum with U.S. Ambassador G. Norman Anderson and Walter
Bollinger, an official of the U.S. Agency for International
Development (AID).
   The agreement broke a deadlock between foreign aid donors and
the government, which had resisted delivery of food supplies into
rebel areas.
   ``The situation in Abyei is very bad. It's now the rainy season,
and the airport is only a strip of sand and stones. We don't give a
time limit, but we would like to carry out the relief operation as
quickly as possible,'' the U.N. official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, told The Associated Press.
   Abyei's normal population of 10,000 shot up to 40,000 as people
in rural areas fled the fierce fighting to the town's relative
safety. Abyei will be virtually isolated for the next two months
because of the rainy season.
   An AP reporter saw a government report covering the last few
months which indicates that dozens of people in Abyei have been
dying each week.
   Ibrahim Mohamed Osman, secretary-general of the Sudanese Red
Crescent, said townspeople and refugees in Abyei ate the last of
their food on Wednesday and that about 700 metric tons of sorghum,
oil and cereal had to be sent there.
   The Red Crescent is Sudan's equivalent of the Red Cross.
   The southern rebellion began five years ago, with the mainly
Christian and animist rebels demanding autonomy and administrative
and economic reforms from the Moslem-dominated government in the
north.
   The official Sudan News Agency said most flights are going to
Abyei, 500 miles southwest of Khartoum, and that supplies destined
for the other towns will be transshipped from there.
   It is the first major foreign civilian relief effort in two
years, since Operation Rainbow, a problem-plagued U.N. program that
finally got off the ground in October 1986.
   A major stumbling block to relief efforts then was a threat from
the rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army to shoot down relief
planes, claiming the government would use them for military
purposes.
   More than 70 people died when rebel gunners shot down two planes
at that time.
   Asked if organizers of the latest airlift had contacted the
Liberation Army about safe conduct for the flights, the U.N.
official said: ``We'd rather not comment on the issue.''
   When reminded of a Liberation Army threat made three weeks ago
to shoot any plane flying in the south, the U.N. official said:
``That was another time. Now it is something else.''
   Osman said planes that took off Thursday carried medicine,
health experts and high-nutrition biscuits to ``people who might
soon starve if food doesn't reach them in the next few days. People
are suffering from hunger and famine is eminent.''
   He said the only hospital in Abyei was deserted last April and
basic medical care was ``nil.''
   Organizers have not disclosed the duration of the operation or
how much food and medication are being flown south, paid for by AID.
   According to a cable from the U.S. ambassador in Khartoum on the
relief plan, however, 90 tons of food will be flown initially into
Abyei, with more to follow. The plan calls for 1,500 metric tons of
food to be trucked from Kadugli west to Muglad and Babanusa. The
Associated Press obtained a copy of the cable.
   The U.N. official said that in addition to the Sudanese
government and the AID organization, the operation involves UNICEF,
the U.N. children's fund; the World Food Program; the U.N.
Development Program; the Red Crescent and private agencies.
   The operation began a week after Sudanese and U.N. officials
toured Abyei. A Sudanese official with the delegation, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said there was a tacit agreement to avoid
publicizing the operation.
   The rebels claim to control 90 percent of the southern
countryside. Fighting has forced more than 820,000 southerners to
flee to army protection in southern towns, northern cities and even
into neighboring Ethiopia.
</TEXT>
