<HEAD>Former Ambassador Calls Soviets `A Failed Society'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former U.S. Ambassador Arthur Hartman on
Thursday called the Soviet Union ``a failed society'' and said it
may grant some independence to its Baltic republics to perk up the
country's economy and to satisfy national aspirations.
   However, Hartman said the steps toward more local control in
Lithuania, Latvia and Esthonia could turn Moscow back on the road
to a more authoritarian regime if the Baltics tried to escape from
the Soviet system.
   ``Eventually, this could be a cataclysmic event,'' he said.
   Hartman, who left his post in Moscow in 1985, was recently in
the Soviet Union. He said it remains ``pretty much a dead-hand
operation'' despite moves by President Mikhail S. Gorbachev to
consolidate his political power.
   ``It is a failed society, and a failed system of central control
and central planning,'' Hartman said at a seminar sponsored by the
Johns Hopkins School of Advanced International Studies.
   He said Gorbachev was determined to improve the economic
situation throughout the country by loosening Moscow's control over
the various republics and their communist parties.
   ``I think there has been a decision that the way to handle the
Baltics, and the way to get the Baltics to be a kind of economic
locomotive for the country, which is what it could be, is to give
them a kind of national freedom,'' the ex-ambassador said.
   Hartman said the people in the three republics could set the
pace for economic reform because they ``have a memory of how to do
things in a way the Russians don't.''
   As a result, he said, the Soviets are proceeding ``in a more or
less autonomous direction'' for the Baltics.
   And yet, Hartman said, Moscow cannot allow the Baltics to get
away from the Soviet system.
   ``I think something can happen which will set the Soviets back
on the road to a much more authoritarian kind of regime,'' he said.
   On human rights, Hartman denounced as ``crazy'' congressional
attempt to withhold economic benefits unless the Soviets improve
their human rights record.
   ``The people who are talking about linkage want to stop any
development in the relationship'' between the superpowers, he said.
``If they tried it in Stalinist times I could understand it.'' But
he said that under Gorbachev the Soviets were stepping up Jewish
emigration because they want a better relationship with the West.
</TEXT>
