<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Anniversary, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0649,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Concert At Masada Ends Celebrations of Israel's 40th Year</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-2 UPDATE with president's remarks. PICKS up 2nd
pvs, The festivities ... Minor editing thereafter to TRIM</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MASADA, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel ended yearlong celebrations of its
40th year Thursday with a dramatic concert at the windswept
foothills of Masada, where Jewish Zealots committed mass suicide
rather than surrender to the Romans.
   ``Their refusal to yield became a symbol and legacy of courage
for the state of Israel in its revival,'' President Chaim Herzog
said in a speech before the concert. ``Our presence here tonight
and the beginning of our fifth decade of our independence is proof
of our promise that Masada will not fall again.''
   The festivities were marred by the 10-month Palestinian uprising
in the occupied lands, which led to a 13 percent drop in tourism.
   ``The damage from the point of view of image has also been
enormous,'' said Micha Gidron, deputy director-general of Israel's
Tourism Ministry.
   He said it was hoped the concert would revitalize tourism and
``return people's confidence in visiting Israel.''
   Yosef Yadin, son of the late archaeologist Yigal Yadin, who
excavated Masada, opened the ceremonies reading from the final
speech of Eleazar Ben Yair, commander of the 1,000 Jewish warriors
and their families who stood off 15,000 Romans for nearly two years.
   Facing certain defeat, Eleazar called on the survivors to commit
mass suicide and destroy the fortress at Masada, except for its
food store.
   ``It will testify when we are dead that we did not perish
through want but because, in keeping with our intitial resolution,
we chose death to slavery,'' Eleazar is said to have told his
followers.
   Zubin Mehta conducted the 120-member Israel Philharmonic
Orchestra and a choir of 170 in peforming Gustav Mahler's Second
Symphony, known as the ``Resurrection.''
   Mehta said the music was chosen to symbolize the suffering and
rebirth of the Jewish people. The first movement begins with a
funeral dirge and moves to a dramatic conclusion symbolizing the
Day of Judgment.
   The men first cut the throats of their wives and children. Then
10 men were chosen by lot to kill the other men. More lots were
drawn, and one man killed his nine companions and then threw
himself on the sword.
   The ancient monument, which overlooks the Dead Sea, is a major
tourist and pilgrimage site, symbolizing Jewish commitment to the
land of Israel. In recent years, Israeli military officers have
been sworn in at ceremonies conducted atop the 1,300-foot-high
monument.
   Israel had hoped the celebrations, which began after the start
of the Jewish new year in September 1987, would bring 1.6 million
tourists. Earnings were projected at $350 million more than in
1987, when 1.5 million tourists brought in $1.5 billion.
   Instead, Gidron said, only about 1.3 million tourists are
expected by year's end.
   About 4,000 Israelis, including Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir
and his political rival, Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, attended
the concert in the Judean Desert hills, 95 miles southeast of
Jerusalem.
   The price of tickets ranged from $150 to $960.
   Security was tight, with cars banned from the site and shuttle
buses taking people to the staging area.
   The celebration included a sound and light show, fireworks
synchronized to music and a procession of 400 torch-carrying
Israeli youths who climbed to the top of the monument.
   French entertainer Yves Montand and American actor Gregory Peck
were hosts for the program, which included a reading of Roman
historian Josephus Flavius' account of the fall of Masada in 73
A.D. to Roman legionnaires.
</TEXT>
