<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Navy-UrinalysisCase     10-13 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Navy-Urinalysis Case,330</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy admiral has ordered a court martial for
a female lieutenant who has refused to provide a urine sample for a
drug test ``under the direct observation'' of another woman.
   Rear Adm. James D. Cossey, the chief of naval technical
training, ordered the special court martial on Thursday for Lt.
Elizabeth Susan Unger, accusing her of one count of willfully
disobeying a lawful order, said Lt. Brian Cullin. a Navy spokesman.
   ``The court martial is to be conducted at the Great Lakes Naval
Training Center, Ill., where Lt. Unger is assigned, on a date not
determined as yet,'' added Cullin.
   ``The maximum punishment, if convicted, is six months
confinement and forfeiture of two-thirds pay for six months.''
   A special court martial differs from a general court martial in
that the presiding officer cannot order a bad conduct discharge. A
conviction at special court martial, however, would still likely
lead to a general or administrative discharge for a Navy officer.
   Unger has told Navy officials she supports drug testing and is
willing to submit a urine sample, but refuses to do so if she must
be observed in the process.
   ``I told my commanding officer that I can't be observed,'' she
told The Washington Post in an interview last month.
   ``I think it's demeaning and degrading. I said I think it's
wrong. He said that we make certain sacrifices, we give up certain
privileges in the Navy.''
   A civilian attorney retained by Unger, Gary R. Myers, has argued
the Navy's urinalysis policy should be changed because ``a woman
officer has to disrobe; a male officer does not.''
   ``A woman officer has to face that observer eyeball to eyeball;
a man does not.''
   Myers also argues that forcing officers to disrobe in front of
enlisted personnel flies in the face of the military's strict
policies against fraternization between the two.
</TEXT>
