<HEAD>Poll Finds Voters Unenthused By Either Presidential Ticket</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis holds a
49 percent to 40 percent lead over Vice President George Bush,
according to a telephone survey conducted by the Buffalo News.
   The sampling by Political-Media Research Inc. of Washington,
D.C., consisted of telephone interviews Monday and Tuesday with 850
registered voters across the state. It has a margin of error of
plus or minus four points.
   Vice President Bush led in every upstate area, including the
heavily Democratic Buffalo area, which has not voted for a
Republican presidential candidate since 1972.
   The poll showed Bush leading 48 percent to 41 percent in Buffalo
and 50 percent to 38 percent in Albany, another traditional
Democratic stronghold.
   Dukakis carried a commanding 62 percent to 28 percent lead in
the populous and overwhelmingly Democratic New York City region,
however.
