<HEAD>Sri Lanka Closes Schools To Halt Student Violence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government closed 9,800 schools
across the country Thursday in an effort to halt increasing student
violence against security forces.
   A government announcement said the schools would stay closed
until Oct. 24. Colombo University also was closed for a month.
   Thousands of students took to the streets Wednesday and set fire
to 49 state-owned buses in protests over the death of a student who
was shot by police and over the arrest of 113 students, police said.
   Officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
protesters either were members or sympathizers of the People's
Liberation Front, a body of radical Sinhalese.
   The group opposes government efforts to reach a settlement with
Tamil militants fighting for an independent homeland in this island
nation. The Front has been blamed for more than 450 deaths since
India and Sri Lanka signed a July 1987 accord to end the Tamil
strife.
   Tamils, who make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's population of 16
million, claim the Sinhalese majority discriminates against them in
employment and in the military.
   Tamil rebels killed six Indian soldiers in northern Sri Lanka on
Wednesday by detonating buried explosives, military officials said
Thursday. India maintains an estimated 47,000 troops in Sri Lanka
to disarm those Tamil militants who refused to surrender their
weapons and abide by the July accord.
</TEXT>
