<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Indians-Hostages 1stLd-Writethru a0727 10-13 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Indians-Hostages, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0727,0591</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Final Arguments in Newspaper Hostage Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE that case goes to jury,
deliberations resume Friday, CORRECTS quote in 9th grav pvs, `Can
you...' Picks up 10th graf pvs, `Kunstler could...' INSERTS one
graf after 12th graf pvs, `Hatcher's voice...' with prosecutor's
comment. Picks up 13th graf pvs, `Pitts said...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors argued Thursday that a county's
problems do not excuse two people from taking hostages at a
newspaper, but the defense said Eddie Hatcher and Timothy Jacobs
saw no alternative.
   ``Conceding an argument that there are serious problems in
Robeson County that need to be addressed, that does not excuse the
action taken here,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney John Bruce.
   ``We're not saying that because there were problems in the past
(in Robeson County) that this was a violent protest,'' countered
defense lawyer Lewis Pitts, one of Jacobs' attorneys. ``That's what
the government would like you to think, but it ignores the real and
immediate threat to Timothy Jacobs and Eddie Hatcher.''
   The arguments were held before a federal jury began its
deliberations in the case at 3:50 p.m. after more than an hour of
instructions from U.S. District Judge Terrence Boyle.
   After about 45 minutes of deliberations, jurors asked for and
received definitions for ``knowingly,'' ``willfully'' and
``maliciously.'' They deliberated until 5 p.m. and were to resume
Friday.
   Hatcher, 30, and Jacobs, 20, both Tuscarora Indians from
Pembroke, face charges of making and possessing illegal firearms,
conspiring to make those weapons and making a bomb threat. A
federal charge of hostage-taking was dismissed earlier this week
against Jacobs but remains against Hatcher.
   The defendants have argued that their lives were in jeopardy
because of information they had linking law enforcement officers to
drug trafficking in Robeson County. They claimed they had to take
hostages at The Robesonian newspaper in Lumberton to publicize
their case and save their lives.
   The two held as many as 20 people during their 10-hour siege on
Feb. 1. No one was injured.
   The judge rejected a request by defense attorneys Wednesday to
discuss self-defense in his instructions to the jury, which will
follow closing arguments.
   ``Can you imagine 60,000 frightened, abandoned people crying
out?'' Hatcher appealed to the jury in a closing statement partly
written by his attorney, William Kunstler. ``From 150 miles away,
they're crying out. Some are faint, they're tired, they're wore
out. Please don't abandon me and Timmy.''
   Kunstler could not appear at the trial because he is tied up in
a New York case.
   ``Mr. Bruce talked about the Constitution this morning and how
it allows peaceful protest,'' Hatcher said. ``When those sworn to
uphold the Constitution won't, what do you do?''
   Hatcher's voice cracked and began to quaver, bringing sobs from
his supporters in the courtroom and tears to Jacobs and his defense
attorneys, who were seated opposite the jury.
   But Bruce said, ``If everything in this whole scenario they have
spun out is true, it still does not justify their putting innocent
people in terror of their lives.''
   Pitts said taking hostages was ``a drastic action'' he was not
trying to minimize, but that the intentions of Hatcher and Jacobs
were critical to the case.
   ``If you put aside the fear and impact on the individuals (at
the newspaper), what it comes down to is if they had a guilty mind
or evil intent,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
