<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Senators-ChemicalWeapons     10-13 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Senators-Chemical Weapons,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senators Urge U.N. Action On Chemical Weapons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bipartisan group of nearly 60 senators urged
U.N. Secretary General Javier Perez de Cuellar on Thursday to
launch an international crusade to prevent the use and spread of
outlawed chemical weapons.
   In a meeting in New York with Sen. Nancy Kassebaum, R-Kan., the
secretary general was given a letter signed by 59 senators urging a
``coordinated response by the international community'' against
chemical weaponry.
   ``Over the past decade, we have seen both the spread and use of
chemical weapons gain increasing momentum,'' stated the letter, a
copy of which was released by Kassebaum's office in Washington.
   ``This is a problem of international dimension. It is critical
that we move as a body of nations to rebuild the barrier to
chemical weapons use and reassert the principle that chemical
warfare is unacceptable,'' the senators said.
   A copy of the letter, which was written by Kassebaum and Sens.
William Cohen, R-Maine; Bill Bradley, D-N.J.; and Joseph Biden,
D-Del., also was sent to President Reagan.
   The lawmakers endorsed Reagan's recent call for an international
conference to determine how to enforce a 1925 protocol that bans
chemical weapons in international conflicts. Reagan, in his
farewell speech to the U.N. General Assembly last month, condemned
the use of chemical weapons in the Iran-Iraq war.
   In addition, the senators suggested a broadening of controls on
exports of materials and technologies that can be used in the
manufacture of chemical weapons. A number of Western nations have
an informal set of export controls, but the lawmakers said those
can only be effective if the Soviet Union, Eastern Bloc nations and
emerging industrialized countries join in the effort to prevent the
spread of chemical weapons.
   Finally, the senators recommended the United Nations adopt a
policy of international sanctions against any country that uses the
banned weapons and called for a system that makes it easier for
U.N. teams to investigate cases of suspected use.
   ``We strongly believe that unless the international community
moves swiftly, perhaps the most serious threat we face is that the
main lesson from the Iran-Iraq war ... will be that chemical
weapons do work and states that use them can get away with it,''
the senators wrote.
</TEXT>
