<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-13 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sunny Skies After Some Early Morning Chills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Sunny skies extended over much of the nation Thursday, although
it rained along the lower Great Lakes and the northern and central
Pacific Coast.
   Early morning temperatures were unseasonably cold over the
eastern portion of the nation and freezing temperatures reached
across the southern Appalachians.
   Sunny skies helped noon temperatures reach the 40s in Ohio and
Indiana and the 50s across Tennessee.
   Temperatures were much higher in the upper Midwest. Noon
temperatures were in the 50s and 60s over the upper Mississippi
Valley, in the 60s and 70s through the Dakotas, Delaware, eastern
Maryland, eastern interior Virginia, northeast Georgia and the
inland portion of the Carolinas.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 32
degrees at Montpelier, Vt., to 92 degrees at Gila Bend, Ariz. The
low temperature for the nation Thursday morning was 18 degrees at
Elkins, W.Va.; Lone Rock, Wis.; and Marquette, Mich.
   The forecast for Friday called for continued showers in northern
New England, scattered rain along the northern Pacific Coast, and
cloudy skies across the Great Basin of Nevada and western Utah and
the southern coast of California. Sunny skies were expected across
much of the remainder of the nation.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 40s over northern New
England into northeast New York state, in the 50s and 60s in
central New England, Georgia, the Great Lakes and the upper Ohio
Valley. Highs were expected in the 60s from the northern two thirds
of the Pacific Coast across the Great Basin, the region west of the
central Rockies and the northern Rockies. Temperatures in the 80s
were expected for southern Florida and the southern and central
Plains. Highs across the desert Southwest were forecast for the 80s
to low 90s. Highs over the remainder of the nation were expected to
be in the 70s.
</TEXT>
