<2ND_LINE>AM-Anti-Quayle Ad,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Ad Focuses On Quayle Questions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three residents of the San Francisco Bay
area have taken out a full-page ad in the New York Times urging the
media to pressure Republican vice presidential candidate Dan Quayle
into disclosing his records from college and law school.
   ``Release Dan Quayle's College Records Now,'' read the banner of
the full-page, $16,000 advertisment in Thursday's editions of the
Times.
   The ad said it was sponsored by the ``Independent Committee on
Presidential Qualifications.'' It was signed by author Orville
Schell, entrepreneur Paul Hawken, and actor Peter Coyote.
   A total of about $65,000, raised from personal and donated
funds, will have been spent before the election, Coyote said. The
group is planning a second ad in the Times and an ad in USA Today,
Coyote said.
   The ad was topped by coupons that readers were asked to fill in
and mail to the committee, a radio network and a newspaper.
   Quayle has refused to make his grades public. He acknowledges he
was a less than stellar student but says he doesn't want reporters
scrutinizing his academic records. Quayle also insisted he got into
law school ``fair and square'' after a newspaper reported that he
entered by way of a program intended to help minority and other
disadvantaged students.
