<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 2109EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     10-13 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czechoslovakia,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Premier Wants Economy Restructured Under Central Control</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One day after taking office,
Premier Ladislav Adamec on Thursday demanded economic reform under
a strong central government and warned his ministers their jobs
depended on concrete results.
   President Gustav Husak swore in Adamec and his Cabinet Wednesday
evening in a reshuffle that added 10 new faces to the 20-member
government.
   It was the biggest shake-up in 20 years and saw the departure of
Lubomir Strougal, who led the government for more than 18 years,
and Foreign Minister Bohuslav Chnoupek.
   Adamec told his Cabinet at its first meeting that the Central
Committee, which sets policy for the ruling Communist Party,
strongly criticized Strougal's government for the present state of
the economy.
   It ``sharply criticized a number of branches (of the economy)
for which we bear responsibility,'' Adamec said, according to the
official news agency CTK.
   ``A number of suggestions were made on how to improve the
activity of the governments and ministries.''
   He indicated the government was under pressure from the party to
achieve concrete results that would be felt by a population
accustomed to adequate supplies of consumer goods and services.
   Czechoslovakia has not faced the economic stagnation and
declining living standards that plague communist neighbors Poland
and Hungary, but economic growth has slowed and much of its
production processes are outdated.
   ``It is our duty to respond to all suggestions and demands as
soon as possible ... by energetic efforts to provide a remedy for
the shortcomings in the criticized branches,'' CTK quoted Adamec as
saying.
   He emphasized the role of the government as ``the state economic
center.''
   Adamec cautioned that changes would not come overnight. He also
said the government would be judged ``not ... by the extent of
personnel changes but by the results achieved.''
   He warned against ignoring ``growing discontent'' among the
population and said the government could not be indifferent to poor
quality production or short supplies of goods and medicines.
   His emphasis on the need to keep consumers well supplied
indicated that the Prague leadership hopes to achieve economic
reform without making political concessions, as the leaderships in
Warsaw and Budapest have done.
</TEXT>
