<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 2112EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PearyHoax     10-13 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peary Hoax,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Researcher Says He Deciphered Peary's Own Notes Showing False
Claim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANE E. ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Baltimore astronomer and historian says he's
found long-suppressed evidence that shows explorer Robert E. Peary
was not the first man to reach the North Pole, but had stopped 121
miles short of his goal.
   Dennis Rawlins, a 51-year-old researcher fascinated by the Peary
expedition, said Thursday he had deciphered Peary's detailed
navigational notes from a document that indicates he and his
dogsled were off course.
   Rawlins believes Peary felt pressured to declare his 1909 polar
expedition a success, but privately instructed his wife to ``treat
this (the document) as your most precious possession and never let
it out of your hands,'' except to silence an archrival who had
falsely claimed to have beaten Peary to the North Pole.
   ``He had the task of hoaxing the world while under the harshest
spotlight, all the while accusing his archrival (explorer Frederick
A. Cook) of faking the very same attainment. The amazing thing is
he had the guts and the intelligence to pull it off,'' Rawlins said.
   ``There had to have been a core of integrity to him or he
wouldn't have kept this record,'' he said.
   Officials of the National Geographic Society, which backed
Peary's expedition, said they would examine the document. But the
society said in a statement, ``We believe Mr. Rawlins has been too
quick to cry fake.''
   Last month, National Geographic Magazine published an article by
another writer acknowledging Peary might have been 30 to 60
nautical miles from his destination.
   Rawlins claimed Isaiah Bowman, the director of the New
York-based American Geographical Society, the professional society
of geographers, had seen Peary's secret papers in 1935 at the Peary
family home in Eagle Island, Maine, after Peary's daughter became
concerned about published attacks on her father's trip.
   Rawlins, who is publishing his findings in his own journal, Dio,
said he stumbled upon the evidence on Sept. 3, 1987, while
reviewing the papers of Bowman, a Peary admirer and the former
president of Johns Hopkins University from 1935 to his death in
1950.
   After having them verified by an astronomer, Bowman suppressed
the papers as well, telling eminent geographers of the day the
papers backed Peary's claim to have reached the pole, Rawlins said.
   Despite the alleged coverup, Rawlins said Peary remains the
greatest U.S. explorer, having discovered the northernmost point of
land in the world, Cape Jesup in northern Greenland, after
surviving an obstacle-laden route.
   Rawlins said Peary's secret document reveals ``he was somewhat
short and a good distance to the right,'' of the North Pole.
   In 1973, Rawlins published a book, ``Peary at the North Pole:
Fact or Fiction?,'' providing evidence against Peary's claim.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
