<DOCNO> AP881013-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 2006EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Congress-Drugs 1stLd-Writethru a0734 10-13 0856</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-Drugs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0734,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Approves Death Penalty as Drug Bill Debate Begins</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS new 3rd graf, ``The lawmakers ...'' with additional
votes; INSERTS new 20th graf, ``Lawmakers and ...'' with
possibility of future spending bill; Senate has recessed for night.
Story should stand for AMs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate on Thursday voted to allow capital
punishment for drug-related killings, as lawmakers lurched past
procedural snarls and finally began debating a $2.6 billion drug
bill.
   The capital punishment language, retained in the legislation on
a 64-25 vote, was just one of many provisions in the 600-page,
campaign-season measure that would strengthen the government's
arsenal against drug offenders.
   The lawmakers easily defeated two other efforts to weaken the
death penalty language, and then adopted by an 88-0 vote a
provision that would allow fines of up to $10,000 against people
who possess even small amounts of illegal drugs.
   The failed effort by liberals to strip the death penalty
language from the bill was a major step toward extending federal
capital punishment statutes because there is similar language in
the harsher, House-passed version of the legislation. Congressional
leaders want to send the drug legislation to President Reagan
before adjourning for the year in the next few days.
   ``The death penalty is necessary and long overdue as a weapon in
the incredible butchery that is taking place on America's
streets,'' said Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y.
   Liberals from both parties, however, derided capital punishment
as an ineffective vestige of less enlightened times.
   ``The desire for vengeance, for eye-for-an-eye justice, is a
principle and a mentality unworthy of civilized government and of
this body,'' said Sen. Mark Hatfield, R-Ore.
   The bill would allow capital punishment for drug traffickers who
kill civilians or law enforcement officers. Hatfield's amendment,
which was defeated 64-25, would have removed the death penalty from
the bill and replaced it with mandatory life imprisonment without
possibility of parole.
   Consideration of the legislation was delayed for days while
lawmakers squabbled over more than 100 amendments they wanted to
attach. Added pressure was being placed on legislators by the
calendar, since 33 Senate seats and all 435 House seats are being
contested in the Nov. 8 elections and lawmakers are eager to
campaign full-time at home.
   By Thursday afternoon, legislative leaders seemed to have pared
the list of amendments down to around 60 and were ready to fold
some of them into the bill and debate others separately.
   Two of the most contentious proposals, advanced by
conservatives, seemed to have been resolved in closed-door
negotiations.
   An effort to restrict the right of convicted criminals to appeal
their sentences on procedural grounds was toned down with an
agreement that Congress would reconsider the question next year,
after a Supreme Court-appointed commission issues a report.
   Another provision was altered that would have allowed courts to
use evidence seized by police with no warrants. Instead, the
amendment would codify a 1984 Supreme Court ruling that evidence
seized in ``good faith'' by officers could be used even if their
warrant was defective.
   Many other amendments awaited action, including language
strengthening federal laws against child pornography, requiring
warning labels on alcoholic beverage containers, mandating random
drug testing for first-time drivers' license applicants and
allowing the loss of many federal benefits for repeat drug
offenders.
   Overall, the legislation would devote 60 percent of its
resources toward treatment and prevention programs, and 40 percent
toward law enforcement efforts.
   It would provide $676 million for federal agencies to hire 3,287
new law enforcement officers, purchase new equipment and build
additional prisons. Another $275 million would be made available to
state and local authorities.
   An additional $1 billion would be provided for treatment and
prevention, allowing programs to handle an additional 600,000 drug
abusers annually over five years. Money would be distributed
locally to train health professionals, to improve existing or build
new treatment centers, and to train teachers involved in drug-abuse
education.
   Federal penalties for repeat drug offenders and for narcotics
crimes involving children or firearms would be increased. A
Cabinet-level federal ``drug czar'' would be created, federal
contracts would be prohibited with businesses that could not
maintain a drug-free workplace, and public housing projects would
be permitted to evict tenants who are drug offenders.
   But there was a question where the money would come from.
Lawmakers said $1.4 billion of the measure's money would be spent
over the next 12 months. Without a new source of revenue _ which
they so far have refused to provide _ they said they only knew
where about $450 million of that amount would come from.
   Lawmakers and aides, however, said Thursday that there was a
chance legislators would pass a supplemental spending bill
providing extra money _ and adding to the deficit _ next week or
when the 101st Congress commences in January.
   Reagan favors the tougher House bill, which was passed Sept. 22.
It contains some provisions imposing tough penalties that are
missing in the Senate bill.
   House-Senate negotiators will have to agree to a compromise bill
before it can be sent to the White House for Reagan's signature.
</TEXT>
