<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel     10-13 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops Kill Palestinian In Arab Village</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops on Thursday shot and killed one
Palestinian after being pelted by cement blocks and stones when
they entered an Arab village in the occupied West Bank, the army
command said.
   A military spokeswoman said troops opened fire in Judeida, north
of Nablus, after one soldier was wounded by the protesters. Four
Palestinians were wounded in the clash.
   ``Because it was a life-threatening situation, the troops opened
fire,'' the spokeswoman said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
``One of the attackers was killed.''
   The army identified the Palestinian as Mahmoud Ahmed Abu Khatir,
18. His death raised the Arab death toll to 296 since the
Palestinian uprising broke out 10 months ago in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip. Six Israelis have died in the unrest during the same
period.
   Three Palestinians were wounded in the Gaza Strip, including a
10-year-old boy shot in the chest, Israel radio and Arab hospital
officials said. The army said two Palestinians were wounded.
   In Jerusalem, a bus driver was slightly injured when his bus was
stoned as it drove along the main street of Arab east Jerusalem,
police spokesman Rafi Levy said.
   Meanwhile, doctors and nurses immunized 20,000 students against
polio in the first day of a campaign to vaccinate all 650,000
Palestinian inhabitants of the Gaza Strip. The government launched
the campaign following a polio outbreak inside Israel. At least 12
polio cases have been confirmed.
   In politics, Foreign Minister Shimon Peres of the left-leaning
Labor Party and Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir of the right-wing
Likud bloc agreed to an Oct. 23 television debate before the Nov. 1
national elections. The top campaign issue is the Palestinian
uprising.
   U.S.-born Rabbi Meir Kahane, an anti-Arab member of parliament
who was barred last week from running in the elections because of
his racist views, appealed to the Supreme Court to overturn the
parliament decision disqualifying him.
   He said his policy favoring the expulsion of all Arabs from
Israel is rooted in Orthodox Jewish law, not racism.
   ``I am not a Nazi. I am not a racist. I am an Orthodox Jew,''
Kahane said.
   Meanwhile in Abu Dhabi, a PLO official said in an interview
published Thursday that the Palestine National Council will meet
Oct. 31 to discuss measures to declare an independent Palestinian
state.
   Yassir Abd-Rabbo, head of the PLO's information department, told
the United Arab Emirates newspaper Al-Ittihad the PLO leadership
would discuss the future of the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip, where 1.5 million Palestinians live.
</TEXT>
