<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 2107EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Spycatcher 1stLd-Writethru a0652 10-13 0919</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spycatcher, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0652,0947</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Loses Lengthy Court Battle Over Spycatcher Memoirs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout UPDATING with Wright saying portion of his
book `unreliable'; publishers backtracking on plans to print books,
editing to conform and TRIM.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Thursday lost its long and costly
battle to block British newspapers from publishing extracts from
``Spycatcher,'' the memoirs of former intelligence agent Peter
Wright.
   Hours later, British Broadcasting Corp. TV altered its schedule
to air an April interview with Wright in which he said part of his
book was ``unreliable.''
   He was refering to a passage dealing with an alleged plot inside
Britain's MI5 counter-intelligence agency to force the resignation
of Labor Party Prime Minister Harold Wilson in the 1970s.
   Conservative Party spokesman Michael Mates said Wright's comment
made ``nonsense'' of media claims of the public's right to know.
   ``The public doesn't have a right or need to know about fanciful
ideas which somebody ... chooses to put in a book and call it
revelations of wrongdoing.''
   Newspapers saw the ruling by the Law Lords, Britain's highest
court, as a triumph for press freedom, while the government claimed
a moral victory because the five judges unanimously accused Wright
of violating the oath of secrecy he took as an intelligence officer.
   He was ``guilty of treachery as heinous as that of the spies he
excoriates in his book,'' said Lord Keith, one of the judges.
   But the judges said any possible damage to Britain's national
security had already been caused by the book's publication
elsewhere, and they lifted temporary injunctions against The
Guardian, The Observer and The Sunday Times of London.
   ``It is absolutely terrific,'' Peter Preston, editor of The
Guardian, said after the ruling. ``This has gone on for 2{ years
and been heard by 23 judges. It is smashing to win hands down at
the end.''
   Andrew Neil, editor of The Sunday Times, said: ``We won, but
it's a battle we should never have had to fight.''
   The book has sold 1.4 million copies overseas after being
published in 40 countries, including the United States.
   ``Spycatcher'' alleges that MI5 eavesdropped on foreign
embassies, bungled operations, stole documents, plotted to
assassinate Egyptian President Gamal Abdel Nasser and plotted to
destabilize the Labor Party government in the 1970s.
   Wright also claims the late MI5 chief Sir Roger Hollis was a
Soviet agent _ a claim the government says has never been
substantiated by investigators.
   On the BBC broadcast Thursday night, Wright indicated the
alleged Wilson plot was not as advanced as the book suggested and
that the manner of forcing the resignation was not exactly as
published.
   Asked if that part of the book was ``perhaps an exaggeration of
what you recall now,'' Wright answered: ``I would say it was
unreliable.''
   Asked if it would be ``fair to conclude from that, that the plot
_ if that's what it was _ was not as advanced as the book
suggests,'' Wright responded: ``I think that is true.''
   He indicated his ghostwriter, Paul Greengrass, might have
misunderstood him, but when the BBC showed him proofs he had edited
without changing the statements in question he said:
   ``I think basically I never thought there would be a fuss about
it. I didn't see why there would be a fuss about it because it had
been stopped.''
   The BBC said Wright, who was 72 at the time of the interview and
had suffered a stroke, appeared a bit confused over details.
   After the ruling, publishers William Heinemann said they would
give the government two weeks' notice that they plan to print
200,000 paperback copies in Britain.
   But early editions of Friday's Daily Telegraph quoted Heinemann
spokeswoman Helen Fraser as saying that after studying the decision
with company lawyers, ``we do not think this would be possible.''
   Home Secretary Douglas Hurd said the ruling vindicated the
government's three-year international battle to block
``Spycatcher,'' and uphold the duty of confidentiality which bars
intelligence agents from writing books and memoirs about their work.
   Wright, 73, retired to Australia in 1976 to raise thoroughbred
horses following a 20-year career with MI5.
   Lord Brightman said Wright had ``flagrantly'' breached his
secrecy oath and Lord Jauncey said ``his action reeked of
turpitude.''
   Wright could not be reached for comment Thursday. His lawyer
Malcolm Turnbull welcomed the decision, but said the judges'
comments about Wright's conduct ``lacked objectivity and were
inappropriate.''
   Wright has said nothing in his book could jeopardize national
security, but Lord Griffiths said it wasn't for Wright to decide.
   ``What may appear to the writer to be trivial may in fact be the
one missing piece in the jigsaw sought by some hostile intelligence
agency,'' he wrote.
   Donald Trelford, editor of The Observer, estimated the
government would have to pay $3.5 million in legal fees. The
government puts the bill at $1 million.
   The government first moved against the book in September 1985
when it obtained a temporary injunction preventing publication in
Australia.
   That case was resolved only in June when Australia's highest
court unanimously ruled against Britain. While accepting that
Wright was bound by secrecy, the judges said Australian courts had
no jurisdiction to enforce British security regulations.
   The Hong Kong Court of Appeal upheld the British government's
case, but the New Zealand High Court rejected it.
   Last year the government said individuals could bring copies of
``Spycatcher'' into Britain, and Heinemann estimates 50,000
hardbacks and 70,000 paperbacks arrived that way, mostly from the
United States and Ireland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
