<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Amnesty-Algeria     10-13 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amnesty-Algeria,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amnesty Group Calls For Probe Of Algeria Killings</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Algeria</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amnesty International on Thursday urged President
Chadli Bendjedid of Algeria to begin an inquiry into the fatal
shootings of unarmed civilian demonstrators.
   The London-based human rights organization said the number of
people killed during the clashes was much higher than the 176
officially listed.
   In Paris, exiled Algerian opposition leader Ahmed Ben Bella
estimated 1,000 people died. Ben Bella, first president of
independent Algeria, was ousted in a 1965 coup.
   The uprising began Oct. 4 when youthful rioters burned cars,
smashed shops and attacked government buildings to protest the
rising cost of living, government austerity measures and consumer
goods shortages.
   The number of protesters swelled and Bendjedid declared a state
of emergency to bring the streets under virtual martial law. He
withdrew most of the troops Thursday, bringing temporary calm to
the capital, and promised a referendum on political reform to give
Algeria's parliament greater power.
   Amnesty said it received reports that hundreds of suspected
critics or opponents of the government had been detained as a
result of the protests.
   Miloud Brahimi, president of Algeria's Human Rights League, has
put the figure at 3,000.
   An undetermined number have been tortured, Amnesty said, and
others summarily tried without legal counsel and sentenced to
prison terms.
   Reports reaching Amnesty said screams could be heard coming from
the national police academy in Al-Biar where many detainees are
believed held.
</TEXT>
