<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 2149EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Debate-Color 3rdLd-Writethru a0757 10-13 0748</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Debate-Color, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0757,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Candidates Set Out To Project Personable Image</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 14 grafs new to UPDATE with debate under way; Picks up
12th graf pvs, bgng: ``Bush said ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two smiling and ostensibly upbeat candidates,
George Bush and Michael Dukakis, shook hands amiably Thursday night
to begin their second and final debate of the presidential campaign.
   Both men had been coached by advisers to project a personable
and humane image, and acknowledged with a wave and a pointed finger
the audience as applause greeted their arrival at UCLA's Pauley
Pavilion.
   But their expressions quickly turned serious at the first
question to Dukakis, about whether he would favor the death penalty
for the killer if his wife, Kitty, were raped and murdered.
   Both men punctuated their answers with expansive gestures,
Dukakis seeming to use less of the familiar closed-fist,
thumb-jabbing movement that has become his trademark.
   Dukakis looked directly into the camera, but Bush _ contrary to
advice given him by former Sen. John Tower of Texas to do the same
in order to establish a connection with the TV viewing audience _
instead faced mostly the panelists or his opponent while answering.
   Dukakis appeared eager to counter his image as a somber,
non-humorous candidate, smiling as he said, ``I think the
presidency of the United States is a very serious office'' but
adding that he wants to be liked and would handle the job ``with as
much good humor as I can.''
   Bush also smiled often and looked bemused when asked a question
about the possibility of his running-mate, Dan Quayle, becoming
president should Bush be elected and die before Inauguration Day.
But Bush then gave a serious answer, reiterating his confidence in
the Indiana senator.
   The debate stage, telegenic blue backdrop, red carpeting and oak
lecterns installed in the pavilion were the ones the two candidates
used at their first debate in Winston-Salem, N.C., last month.
   The props were trucked to Los Angeles from Omaha, Neb., where
they also had been put to use for last week's debate between vice
presidential rivals Dan Quayle and Lloyd Bentsen.
   The lectern Bush stood behind was set at 48 inches, while the
one for the half-foot shorter Dukakis was at 45 inches.
   In the carpeting around Dukakis' lectern was a circular cut from
where it was altered to insert a subtle three-inch riser the
Massachusetts governor used in Winston-Salem.
   Dukakis wore a dark grey suit with a red tie and Bush wore a
dark blue suit with a red, white and blue striped tie.
   The audience was restrained, having been lectured severely
against outbursts and applause, but did reward each candidate with
those responses on occasion.
   The well-dressed audience was dotted with California elected
officials and some members of the Hollywood community, including
actress Sally Field.
   Bush said Wednesday he wanted to show voters ``what my heartbeat
is, what I really care about.''
   It took work at UCLA to create a setting that might foster those
kinds of personal self revelations.
   The venue at UCLA was vastly different from the cozy Wake Forest
University chapel where they met in North Carolina.
   The chapel could accommodate fewer than 1,500 spectators once a
balcony was outfitted for TV crews and reporters. Pauley Pavilion
seats 13,000 and had to be revamped for a more intimate audience of
2,000.
   The stage and seats were set up on the basketball floor, which
was partitioned off from the bleachers.
   The audience was divided between Dukakis and Bush supporters and
guests invited by the sponsoring Commission on Presidential Debates.
   Of the 2,000 tickets for the debate, only about 100 were
distributed through the university, said Alan Charles, vice
chancellor for UCLA.
   Those tickets came from the one-third allotted to the debate
commission. The campaigns also got one-third each.
   Pauley Pavilion, home of the UCLA Bruins basketball team, is in
a central location on the sprawling campus where 34,000
undergraduate and graduate students attend classes.
   At lunchtime Thursday, a punk rock band named Thelonius Monster
entertained a few hundred students who gathered in the busy plaza
between the student union building and arena.
   With Dukakis-Bentsen placards on the stage, the band leader
repeatedly derided Bush. The students laughed but seemed more
enthusiastic about the band's hard-driving music than the political
commentary.
   UCLA audio engineer Fred Stites said the concert was part of the
campus' noon music series and not sponsored by the Dukakis campaign.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
