<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Kurds     10-13 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kurds,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Turkey Confers With Iranians About Kuridsh Refugees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Turkish and Iranian authorities discussed
on Thursday the plight of Kurdish refugees who fled to Turkey
claiming Iraqi forces dropped chemical bombs on their settlements,
a government official reported..
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, told The
Associated Press the talks took place in the southeastern border
village of Esendere.
   The independent Hurriyet News Agency meanwhile reported that
Iran closed its border with Turkey to prevent any crossings by
Kurdish refugees.
   About 60,000 Kurds sought refuge in Turkey in August, and Iran
offered to accept any of the refugees.
   Nearly 19,000 refugees from Iraq voluntarily went from Turkey to
Iran in recent weeks. But Iran reportedly ran into problems finding
them shelter.
   ``Iran still had the same problem and negotiations centered on
such issues,'' the official said, refusing to go into detail.
   During the Persian Gulf war, Iran supported Kurdish guerrillas
fighting for autonomy in northern Iraq.
   Iraq started an offensive against Kurds soon after Iran agreed
to a cease-fire in the 8-year-old war in August.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   A Kurdish guerrilla official, a spokesman for the Kurdistan
Democratic Party, or KDP, charged Thursday that Turkey has
``discreetly'' forced as many as 30,000 Kurdish refugees into Iran
in recent days.
   The spokesman, who is known to The Associated Press in Nicosia,
Cyprus, spoke to the AP there by telephone from a West European
city. He spoke on the condition his name and exact location not be
used for ``security reasons.''
   The official called Turkey's treatment of the Kurdish refugees
``despicable'' and appealed for international help.
   ``We are deeply perturbed at Turkey's forcible transportation of
refugees ... without giving the Iranian authorities any prior
notice and without making sure that any arrangements have been made
for them in Iran,'' he said.
   The refugees now were crammed into an overcrowded camp at Zieva
in Iran's northwestern Urumiyeh province, he claimed.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic New Agency, monitored in
Nicosia, said 32,000 Kurdish refugees from Turkey have sought
sanctuary in northwest Iran, including nearly 8,000 in the last few
days, because of Ankara's ``reluctance to host them.''
   The KDP official said: ``Although we are grateful to Turkey for
its initial response in providing refuge for many thousands of
Kurdish civilians fleeing Iraqi onslaughts with chemical weapons,
the Turkish government's behavior in recent weeks has been
despicable.''
   About 20 million Kurds live in the mountainous region where the
borders of Turkey, Iran and Iraq converge. They have been fighting
for independence in all three countries intermittently throughout
this century.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881013-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 2220EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p BC-DebateText 4thadd   10-13 0901</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Debate Text, 4th add,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LOS ANGELES: oppose that.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Moderator: I'm going to say this, and I'm going to say it once
to every person in this auditorium. What these candidates are about
is of utmost seriousness to the American voters. They should be
heard, and you should be quiet. If you are not quiet, I'm going to
implore the candidates to do something about prodding -- or
quieting their own partisans. But we cannot get through this
program with these outbursts. Margaret Warner, for Governor Dukakis.
   Q: Good evening, Governor, Mr. Vice President. Governor, you won
the first debate on intellect, and yet you lost it on heart.
   Bush:: Just a minute.
   Dukakis: I don't know about the vice --
   Q: You'll get your turn. The American public --
   Dukakis: I don't know whether the vice president agrees with
that.
   Q: The American public admired your performance, but didn't seem
to like you much. Now Ronald Reagan has found his personal warmth
to be a tremendous political asset. Do you think that a president
has to be likable to be an effective leader?
   Dukakis: Margaret, may I go back and just say to the vice
president that I didn't raid the pension fund in Massachusetts.
You're dead wrong, George. We didn't do that. As a matter of fact,
I'm the first governor in the history of my state to fund that
pension system, and I'm very proud of that. And you just had your
   Bush: (Inaudible.)
   Dukakis: -- You just have your information -- no, we did not.
No, we did not. I've been in politics for 25 years, Margaret. I've
won a lot of elections; I've lost a few, as you know, and learned
from those losses. I won the Democratic nomination in 51 separate
contests. I think I'm a reasonably likeable guy. I'm serious,
though I think I'm a little more lovable these days than I used to
be back in my youth when I began in my state legislature. But, I'm
also a serious guy. I think the presidency of the United States is
a very serious office. And I think we have to address these issues
in a very serious way.
   So, I hope and expect that I'll be liked by the people of this
country as president of the United States. I certainly hope I'll be
liked by them on the 8th of November. But, I also think it's
important to be somebody who's willing to make those tough choices.
Now, we've just heard two or three times from the vice president
that he's not going to raise taxes. I repeat, within days after you
made that pledge, you broke it. You said, ``Well, maybe as a last
resort, we'll do it,'' and you supported legislation this year
that's involved tax increases not once, but twice.
   So, that pledge isn't realistic, and I think the vice president
knows it. I think the people of this country know it. The fact of
the matter is that the next president of the United States is going
to have to go to the White House seriously, he's going to have to
work with the Congress seriously. He can't turn to the Congress and
blame them for the fact that we don't have a balanced budget and
that we have billions and billions of dollars in red ink.
   And I'm going to be a president who is serious, I hope and
expect will be liked by the American people. But more than that,
will do the kind of job that I'm elected to do, will do it with as
much good humor as I can, but at the same time, will do it in a way
which will achieve the goals we want for ourselves and our people.
And I think we know what they are --
   Moderator: Governor --
   Dukakis: -- a good strong future, a future in which there --
   Moderator: You're time has run out, sir.
   Dukakis: -- is opportunity for all of our citizens.
   Moderator: One minute from the vice president.
   Bush: I don't think it's a question of whether people like you
or not to make you an effective leader. I think it's whether you
share the broad dreams of the American people, whether you have
confidence in the people's ability to get things done, or whether
you think it all should be turned over, as many of the liberals do,
to Washington, D.C. You see, I think it's a question of values, not
likeability or lovability.
   It's a question in foreign affairs of experience, knowing world
leaders, knowing how to build on a superb record of this
administration in arms control because you'd know exactly how to
begin. You have to learn from experience that making unilateral
cuts in the defense system is not the way that you enhance the
peace.
   You've got to understand that it is only the United States that
can stand for freedom and democracy around the world, and we can't
turn it over to the United Nations or other multilateral
organizations. It is, though, trying to understand the heartbeat of
the country. And I know these campaigns get knocked a lot, but I
think I'd be a better president now --
   Moderator: Mr. Vice President --
   Bush: -- for having had to travel to these communities and
understand the family values and the importance of neighborhood.
</TEXT>
