<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Nicaragua     10-13 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Nicaragua,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaragua Looks To Next Administration To Repair Relations</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-UN-Central America</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The foreign minister of Nicaragua said
Thursday that he hoped the next U.S. president would help repair
relations with his leftist government.
   Foreign Minister Miguel D'Escoto Brockmann told delegates to the
43rd General Assembly that ``the problem in Central America has a
first and last name. It is called U.S. intervention.
   ``When the United States stops making war on Nicaragua and stops
involving its lackeys in this war, then the international situation
will be immensely eased in Central America,'' D'Escoto said.
   The minister claimed the reputation of the United States had
sunk to an all-time low internationally, and ``all agree that the
dirty, immoral and illegal policy against Nicaragua is the basic
reason for this discredit.''
   ``Secretary of State (George) Shultz and a couple of his Latin
American friends may think differently, but that's another kettle
of fish,'' D'Escoto said.
   ``We were not intimidated in the military struggle against the
U.S. mercenary forces. We have defeated them,'' he said, referring
to the U.S.-supported rebels, known as Contras. The United States
has supported the Contra since 1981, two years after the Sandinista
government came to power.
   Leftist rebels fighting El Salvador's U.S.-backed government and
the U.S.-backed Contras battling the Sandinistas both launch raids
from Honduran territory.
   ``We believe that it is possible to arrive at an understanding
with the United States and normalize our bilateral relations with
that country,'' D'Escoto added. ``With the next U.S. administration
we hope that might be possible.''
   The U.S. presidential elections between Democrat Michael
Dukakis, the governor of Massachusetts, and Vice President George
Bush, a Republican, is Nov. 8, with the winner taking office in
January.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
