<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CableFee     10-13 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cable Fee,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Throws Out Local Franchise Fee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has declared
unconstitutional a franchise fee charged by the city of Palo Alto
to a local cable television company, a ruling described by a
company lawyer as the first of its kind.
   The ruling, if it stands, would save the cable company, Century
Federal, $900,000 a year, attorney Harold Farrow said Thursday. But
he said the potential impact of the issue is much greater because
more than 40 million homes in the nation have cable and at least 90
percent are with companies that pay franchise fees.
   ``I believe this is the first case in the whole country where
they held a franchise fee to be straightforwardly and without any
question unconstitutional,'' Farrow said, noting that a federal
appeals court in Philadelphia had ruled to the contrary.
   He called the ruling a victory for freedom of the press.
   Jerome Falk, a lawyer for Palo Alto and several neighboring
communities that joined in assessing the franchise fee, declined
comment.
   The decision by U.S. District Judge Eugene Lynch, issued
Wednesday, declared that the franchise fee discriminated against
cable operators, in violation of constitutional freedom of
expression.
   Palo Alto said the fee, which is 5 percent of a company's gross
revenue, was justified as rent for use of the city's right-of-way
to place cables.
   Lynch said the fee was discriminatory because Pacific Bell,
which uses the same right-of-way for its telephone lines, is not
charged any fee as its access is guaranteed by state law. Also,
Pacific Gas & Electric Co. is charged only a 2 percent fee for use
of a public right-of-way by the neighboring city of Atherton, a
defendant in the cable case.
   The 5 percent fee ``is aimed exclusively at cable television
operators engaged in speech protected by the First Amendment,''
Lynch said.
   He also said the city's goal of raising money could have been
met by a non-discriminatory fee.
   Farrow, who represents several cable companies that have fought
local restrictions, said Century Federal had signed up 50,000
subscribers in the Palo Alto area, paying an average of $30 a month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
