<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MarcosPapers     10-13 0578</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marcos Papers,0600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Secret Marcos Papers Show Plans To Become Dictator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ferdinand Marcos fostered unrest against his
own government to justify dictatorial powers, according to a
journal handwritten by the ousted Philippine president, the Los
Angeles Times reported Thursday.
   ``I have that feeling of certainty that I will end up with
dictatorial powers if the situation continues _ and the situation
will continue,'' Marcos wrote in 1970.
   The papers indicate that Marcos deceived U.S. officials who have
long sought good relations with the Philippines because of the
country's strategic location and vast U.S. military installations.
   For example, Marcos told Ambassador Henry A. Byroade that he
suspected China of supplying arms to Maoist revolutionaries just a
few months after Marcos wrote in the papers that it appeared no
foreign powers were providing the revolutionaries with arms, the
Times said.
   The papers are reportedly part of a larger manuscript discovered
in the presidential palace after Marcos fled Manila in the
bloodless revolution that brought Corazon Aquino to power in
February 1986.
   Marcos lives in exile in Hawaii. His spokesman, Gemmo Trinidad,
blasted the papers' release as ``an invasion of privacy'' and said
Marcos may go to court over it.
   The papers also show that Marcos expected Maoist rebels would
try to spark a revolution, but he acknowledged that they and other
groups were weak.
   ``We should allow them to gather strength, but not such strength
that we cannot overcome them,'' a Feb. 17, 1970, entry says.
   Marcos worked his plan for absolute power cautiously, the papers
say.
   ``I must continue to restrain myself lest we lose the support of
the people by a stance of tyranny,'' another entry says.
   By March 1970, however, Marcos was losing patience as nonviolent
demonstrations were not disruptive enough for him, the papers say.
   ``The disorders must now be induced into a crisis so stricter
measures can be taken,'' a March 3, 1970, entry says.
   Another entry says: ``A little more destruction and vandalism,
and I can do anything.''
   James Miller, an independent handwriting analyst hired by the
newspaper, checked them against formal degrees written by Marcos
and found ``virtually everything was consistent.''
   The entries start on New Year's Eve of 1970, just after Marcos
was re-elected to his second term as president in an election
marked by allegations of vote fraud.
   One month later he started outlining his ``total solution,'' an
elaborate scheme to ``liquidate'' Communists and silence opposition
political leaders and media critics through mass arrests.
   The plan started taking shape 32 months before he declared
martial law and while he presented himself as a champion of
democracy, the papers show.
   Meanwhile, in Honolulu, more than a dozen relatives and
supporters of Marcos have been subpoenaed to appear before a
federal grand jury that apparently is investigating an alleged 1987
plot to return Marcos to power.
   Trinidad said those subpoenaed include Marcos' daugther, Irene,
and her husband, Gregorio Araneta.
   Marcos denounced the subpoenas as ``pure and simple harassment.''
   The U.S. Justice Department, through the FBI, has been
investigating possible violations by Marcos supporters in Hawaii
and California of the Neutrality Act with regard to the Philippines.
   Supporters of Marcos allegedly provided a private Boeing 707
that flew into Honolulu last year but departed without Marcos after
federal agents threatened to restrain him if he tried to leave.
   U.S. officials are convinced that Marcos continues to try to
destabilize the government of President Corazon Aquino. Marcos
denies such efforts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881013-0259 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 2304EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua-Radio     10-13 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Radio,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Shuts Down Radio Newscast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Sandinista government on Thursday
ordered off the air a private radio newscast for broadcasting an
interview in which the president and interior minister were called
``monsters.''
   An Interior Ministry communique said the news program El
Nicaraguense had been indefinitely suspended for ``its defamatory
campaign against the government.'' The program is run by the
opposition Superior Council of Private Enterprise and broadcast by
the private Radio Mundial station.
   The statement said an interview with Nicaraguan rebel leader
William Montalvan, which was aired Wednesday, ``slandered the
government ... and its leaders.''
   The communique quoted Montalvan, who is based in Costa Rica, as
saying in the interview that ``(Interior Minister Tomas) Borge and
(President Daniel) Ortega are monsters.
   ``Here in exile, there isn't a day that goes by without my
hearing of another Nicaraguan being jailed. There isn't a day that
goes by without the economic situation of our people getting worse
because of the totalitarian policy of the Sandinista regime,''
Montalvan was quoted as saying.
   The communique said El Nicaraguense was taken off the air under
provisions of a media law that calls for permanent closure of
repeat violators of the law.
   In May, the government prohibited Radio Mundial from
broadcasting its regular news programs for eight days. The official
Sandinista newspaper Barricada said the station was accused of
``spreading false information'' about a workers' hunger strike and
of violating laws preserving public order.
   The U.S.-backed rebels, known as Contras, have opposed the
Sandinistas since the leftist government came to power in 1979.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881013-0260 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 2308EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p BC-DebateText 14thadd   10-13 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Debate Text, 14th add,515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LOS ANGELES: Trust Fund.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Moderator: Ann Compton for the vice president.
   Q: Mr. Vice President, there are three justices of the Supreme
Court who are in their eighties, and it's very likely the next
president will get a chance to put a lasting mark on the Supreme
Court. For the record, would your nominees to the Supreme Court
have to pass something that has been called a kind of conservative
ideological litmus test, and would you give us an idea of perhaps
who two or three people on your short list are for the court?
   Bush: Well one, I don't have a list yet. I feel pretty confident
tonight, but not that confident. And secondly -- secondly, I don't
have any litmus test. But, what I would do is appoint people to the
federal bench that will not legislate from the bench, who will
interpret the Constitution. I do not want to see us go to again _
and I'm using this word advisedly _ a liberal majority that is
going to legislate from the bench.
   They (Dukakis supporters) don't like the use of the word, but
may I remind his strong supporters that only last year in the
primary to capture that Democratic nomination, he said, ``I am a
progressive liberal Democratic.'' I won't support judges like that.
   There is no litmus test on any issue. But, I will go out there
and find men and women to interpret. And I don't have a list, but I
think the appointments that the president has made to the bench
have been outstanding, outstanding appointments _
   Ms. Compton: Including Bork, including Bork?
   Bush: Yeah.
   Moderator: Governor --
   Bush: _ I supported him.
   Moderator: _ you have a one-minute reponse time.
   DUKAKIS: If the Vice President of the United States thinks that
Robert Bork was an outstanding appointment, that is a very good
reason for voting for Mike Dukakis and Lloyd Bentsen on the 8th of
November. And I think Mr. Bush supported the Bork nomination.
   You know Mr. Bush has never appointed a judge. I've appointed
over 130, so I have a record _ and I'm very proud of it. I don't
ask people whether they're Republicans or Democrats. I've appointed
prosecutors, I've appointed defenders. I don't appoint people I
think are liberal, or people who I think are conservative; I
appoint people of independence and integrity and intelligence,
people who will be a credit to the bench. And those are the
standards that I will use in nominating people to the Supreme Court
of the United States.
   These appointments are for life -- these appointments are for
life, and when the vice president talks about liberals on the
bench, I wonder who he's talking about? Is he talking about a
former governor of the state of California, who was a former
prosecutor _
   Moderator: Governor _
   Dukakis: _ a Republican, named Earl Warren? Because I think
Chief Justice Warren was an outstanding chief justice, and I think
most Americans do too.
</TEXT>
