<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Dance     10-13 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dance,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Martha Graham Premieres her 178th Dance</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the 1930s, before she turned to large
theatrical dances, choreographer Martha Graham rooted her work in
Indian material from the U.S. Southwest.
   At 94, she has returned to American Indians for her 178th dance
creation.
   ``Night Chant'' had its premiere Thursday night by the Martha
Graham Dance Company at the City Center.
   The music was traditional Navajo forms, arranged by R. Carlos
Nakai. Melodies, carried by what sounded like wooden flutes and
reed instruments, were beautiful and not melancholy even when the
dance led one to expect that.
   The dance is in ritual form and sustains a viewer's interest.
When a line of men or a line of women dance across the stage, they
repeat the same pattern of steps. The next time they use a
different pattern but also repeat it all the way across.
   Denise Vale was the central figure, standing at first in front
of a tall structure which looked like a metal cactus without
spikes, designed by Isamu Noguchi. She lifted a tambourine, which
she hit a few times then hung on a hook on the cactus.
   From time to time, she bowed to it as though it were the moon.
Side lighting by David Finley makes it look like moonlight. Though
none of the dancers looked Indian, the dance strongly evoked an
outdoor, nighttime American Indian scene.
   One section has four men with long poles flexing them over the
head of a fifth man. He dances and falls, injured, finally is
``killed,'' then carried out. This isn't what the entire dance
leads up to, as in ``The Rite of Spring.''
   Three couples who have danced together before dance together
again after that scene. Miss Vale is partnered briefly by Peter
London. The 20-minute dance ends with Miss Vale pounding the
tambourine with her hand.
   The evening also included Miss Graham's ``Diversion of Angels,''
``Errand into the Maze'' and ``Appalachian Spring.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881013-0267 </DOCNO>
