<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 2156EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv14   10-13 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 14,0519</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Friday, Oct. 14</NOTE>
<HEAD>No Tax Increases?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While Americans may never underestimate the
verbal ingenuity of politicians, they had better be prepared for
the acrobatics of taxes that aren't taxes.
   ``Tax'' is a bad word. Not only does it cost votes, but it leads
directly to other uunpleasant images, including overspending,
bureaucracy, waste, pork barrel and favoritism.
   But it is a very necessary word too, since the very candidates
for office who rail against taxes would hardly know what to do
without them, since most of their proposals involve expenditures of
some sort.
   Be prepared, therefore, for more user fees, revenue enhancers,
mandated benefits, earmarking and other techniques for squeezing
more out of the private sector without recourse to the nasty T word.
   It already is happening. Those frenzied debates over postal
rates, for instance, have been cooled by turning over the increases
to a semi-private entity, where actions are much better shielded
from public attention.
   Earmarking, or special levies on special groups for special
purposes, is likely to become common. In fact, John Hanly Adams of
the Tax Foundation suggests it will become a highly practiced art
if voters don't cry out.
   Such tax boosts often can be hidden behind the name of a
program, he says. ``Thus a tax increase on parents to finance child
care should be called an `education premium,''' he says. And
national health insurance, seriously discussed lately, could be
financed with premiums similar to those on Medicare.
   The technique of mandated benefits would shift from government
onto employers certain new services that once might have required a
tax increase. Health insurance for part-time workers and
dependents, for example.
   Revenue enhancers, already being employed, take various forms:
User fees, such as charges paid by users of Coast Guard services,
is one example.
   Another is to charge for forms used in meeting federal
regulations. The Internal Revenue Service, for instance, charges
fees for private rulings on tax questions, including computations
for individuals' retirement annuities.
   Adams cites this revenue enhancer: By tightening its procedures,
hiring more auditors, carrying more disputes to the courts, the IRS
can squeeze more dollars out of taxpayers whether tax rates go up
or not.
   The search for nontax taxes is intense and pervasive. Adams
makes this classic observation:
   ``Many tax initiatives are conceived in secrecy, drafted into
legislation without public hearings, passed with little or no
debate, and then buried in lengthy, complex legislation on other
topics such as trade rules and massive appropriations bills.''
   What do you think of this nontax tax idea now floating around
Congress: Index federal excise taxes on gasoline and other products
so they could rise automatically and without publicity.
   One of the goals of such ideas, of course, is to give the
appearance of stable taxes while simultaneously raising them. It is
a politically ingenious idea, since it gets everyone off the hook _
except the taxpayer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Friday, Oct 14.</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881013-0279 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 0534EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a AM-AmericanCampaigners-Venezuela Adv17   10-13 0766</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-American Campaigners-Venezuela, Adv 17,0791</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, Oct. 17, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-American Campaigners, b0440</HEAD>
<HEAD>U.S. Political Advisers Spread `Campaign Magic' to Latin America</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARRIE FIGDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As more Latin American nations shake
off military rule and turn to democratic government, foreign
campaign consultants, nearly all of them from the United States,
increasingly become a fixture in elections.
   Latin politicians say the advisers are most valuable for
bringing an outsider's perspective on the candidate and on what
voters want. They also provide techniques to link the candidate to
the voters' desires.
   U.S. consultant David Garth came to Venezuela in 1978 to help
presidential candidate Luis Herrera Campins. His first suggestion
was that the famously fat politician lose weight.
   Herrera, a Social Christian who felt his girth was an integral
part of his popular image, rejected Garth's advice.
   ``When you're campaigning, Venezuelans will always offer you
food and drink,'' the still-corpulent Herrera recalled recently.
``The only way you can refuse without losing a vote is to say,
somewhat mysteriously, that you're taking pills, and they'll think
you have a venereal disease or something.''
   Garth lost the battle to slim down his candidate. He chose
instead to capitalize on Herrera's communications skills in eight
memorable commercials, filmed outdoors, featuring the candidate
speaking with disgruntled citizens.
   The spots galvanized the campaign and helped Herrera defeat the
Social Democratic Party in a race that was crucial in forging
Venezuela's democracy into a two-party system.
   U.S. pollsters, media specialists and general advisers have also
helped the winning presidential campaigns of Carlos Andres Perez
and Jaime Lusinchi in Venezuela; Oscar Arias Sanchez in Costa Rica;
Nicolas Ardito Barletta in Panama; Alan Garcia in Peru and others.
   Besides Garth, these high-powered campaign consultants have
included Joseph Napolitan, David Sawyer, Matthew Reese, Robert
Squier and Sergio Bendixen.
   Sometimes, candidates ignore the advice of their hired guns from
the north at their own peril.
   In the 1987 presidential nomination race in Venezuela, Social
Democratic hopeful Octavio Lepage ignored his consultant's advice
to stay in his key government post, rather than quit to campaign in
the streets.
   Lepage, a dry party-line politician with no popular appeal, lost
the nomination to Carlos Andres Perez, a charismatic former
president who has no trouble gathering large and noisy crowds.
   But the U.S. consultants must also adapt. In Latin America, as
in Europe, political parties are much stronger than they are in the
United States, and party loyalty is the norm.
   U.S. consultants' advice can get lost in the shuffle as party
leaders struggle for influence in the campaign, which is seen as
collective rather than an individual bid.
   Latin American candidates, who are almost always men, prefer a
political message that emphasizes strength and machismo.
   While television is growing in importance as a political tool in
Latin America, the old-fashioned campaign rally, which has fallen
from favor in the United States, is still a powerful technique.
   Latin Americans have resisted using direct mail or telephone
campaign operations, mainly because these public services are
typically inefficient.
   Even so, campaigns have increasingly resembled U.S. contests,
with a variety of imported techniques.
   Mapping out a strategy, choosing one or two short messages that
are repeated as long as they are effective, polling to obtain
reliable information and relying more heavily on television are
among the principles that have filtered south.
   Now the region is developing its own advisers who are pioneering
their own techniques.
   Argentina's Felipe Noguera, for instance, an Oxford-educated
mathematician, is analyzing at what point a voter chooses a
candidate.
   Substituting Latin consultants for U.S. ones appeals to Latin
pride and saves money at the same time.
   The North Americans tend to charge Latin American clients the
same rates as U.S. candidates: perhaps $100,000 per campaign for a
general consultant, plus additional fees for specialists.
   In Venezuela's 1978 presidential election, estimates of the
candidates' spending ranged up to $120 million in all.
   In Latin America, there are no limits on campaign spending, as
there are in the United States.
   As the region has become poorer, candidates are less willing to
spend that amount for a touch of foreign ``magic,'' especially if
they can hire quality talent locally.
   But if they can afford to hire U.S. consultants, they generally
do.
   ``We began the campaign without foreign advisers and we ended it
using foreign advisers,'' said Rafael Montes de Oca, Herrera's
former campaign manager. ``They were indispensible because of their
knowledge of the media and of the techniques to find out what
people think.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, Oct. 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881013-0280 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 2157EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a AM-EnglishingScotland ADV18   10-13 0758</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Englishing Scotland, ADV 18,0780</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tue AMs, Oct. 18, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Scots Agonize Over `Englishing of Scotland'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDINBURGH, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scotland has suffered another blow to
its sense of separate identity: The English have overrun its
cultural establishment.
   Ever since 1707, when Scotland and England were united under one
crown and parliament, Scots have worried about being swamped by
their English neighbors, who outnumber them 11-1.
   Comes now ``The Englishing of Scotland,'' broadcast Aug. 29 on
the independent Scottish television channel, which shows the
command posts of Scottish culture firmly in the hands of Sassenachs
from south of the border.
   Not the artists, mind. Native Scottish creativity has never
looked healthier. What worries guardians of Scottish identity is
the preponderance of Englishmen in a cultural bureaucracy supposed
to be separate.
   ``The Englishing of Scottish life is a process that has gone on
for many years, but many Scots ... feel it is beginning to
undermine the very notion of Scotland,'' George Rosie, the writer
and host, said in introducing the program.
   Rosie presented impressive of evidence of ``non-Scot''
infiltration, the non-Scots being almost invariably from England.
   Non-Scots run most of Scotland's major state-subsidized arts
institutions: the National Museums, National Galleries, National
Library, Arts Council, Scottish Opera, Scottish Ballet, its three
major international arts festivals and the Scottish National Trust
for heritage parks and buildings.
   They run five of the eight universities, 10 of the 15
government-funded colleges and three of the six leading theaters.
   ``We are assimilating ourselves toward an English ideal and
gradually I think we will assimilate ourselves out of existence,''
Billy Kay, a playwright, historian and Scottish nationalist, said
on the program.
   Paul Scott, a retired diplomat, said: ``I think we're at very
grave risk of ceasing to exist as a recognizable nation, as a
recognizable culture and identity. The species is under threat.''
   While everyone saw a problem, there was little agreement on the
cause.
   Newspaper columnist Neal Ascherson said most of the institutions
mentioned were recent creations copied from England.
   ``The idea of cultural bureaucracies is entirely alien to
Scotland,'' he said. ``This is not a country which has
traditionally been kind to the arts.''
   Some said Scots were reluctant to protest ``Englishing'' for
fear of sounding racist. Alan Lawson, editor of the left-wing
journal ``Radical Scotland,'' said this fear had deprived Scots of
``the confidence to stand up and argue that there is a problem.''
   Allan Massie, a conservative writer, offered simple arithmetic:
``Because of the population ratio, if you have a job that is
publicly advertised and you have 10 applicants, you're quite likely
to find that seven of them come from outside Scotland.''
   Timothy Clifford, an Englishman who heads the National Gallery
of Scotland, called the program ``absolute arrant nonsense.''
   He said just as many Scots run English institutions, but Rosie
reported no Scots among 34 university heads in England and Wales,
and said only two of the 21 state-funded museums, art galleries and
libraries south of the border were run by Scots.
   Clifford argued that ``An Englishman sometimes understands more
and can better identify the Scottishness of something than a Scot
can.'' The program, too, paid tribute to the many non-Scots who
have fostered Scottish art forms the Scots themselves had neglected.
   Overall, however, Rosie's presentation painted a gloomy portrait
of a culture hijacked by outsiders. It inspired a deluge of
commentary and letters that complained of ``Englishing'' in
everything from soccer through architecture to the Englishisms
creeping into everyday speech in Scotland.
   The Advisory Council for the Arts in Scotland weighed in with
worry about ``the survival of Scotland as anything more than a
geographical expression.''
   Rosie said the letters ran 8-2 in support of his conclusions,
which are that ``certain jobs should be reserved for people who are
educated and brought up in Scotland and understand the nuances of
Scottish culture.''
   He acknowledges the impossibility of barring Englishmen from
jobs in Scotland since both are part of Britain, but added in an
interview: ``It's similarly daft that so many such jobs are being
taken by non-Scots. That's the ambivalence of our whole
constitutional situation.''
   The broadcast coincides with a broadly based campaign for
limited independence that is gathering support in Scotland.
   ``There does seem to be a fairly stronger feeling of nationalism
again,'' Rosie said. ``I think Scots have a pendulum consciousness
that swings from feeling British to feeling Scottish, and in my
opinion it's swinging toward Scottishness now.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tue AMs, Oct. 18</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881013-0281 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 1417EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-IsraelElection Adv23   10-13 1063</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Israel Election, Adv 23,1094</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 23, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Israeli Election: A Showdown On Future Of The Occupied Territories</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's election is focused on whether to keep
the West Bank and Gaza Strip as a buffer to hostile Arab states or
trade away the land to preserve the Jewish character of Israel.
   Israelis seem almost evenly split on the issue, and the Nov. 1
vote may be less a watershed than another shotgun wedding between
the rightist Likud bloc of Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir and the
left-leaning Labor Party of Foreign Minister Shimon Peres.
   Shamir and Peres have been reluctantly sharing power since the
1984 elections resulted in a stalemate. The unlikely coalition has
hung together despite basic policy differences.
   Interest is high in this year's election and about 80 percent of
the 2.4 million eligible voters are expected to cast ballots.
   Israel's belated debate on the future of the West Bank and Gaza,
captured by Israel in the 1967 Middle East war, was largely sparked
by the 10-month-old Palestinian uprising in which more than 290
Palestinians and six Israelis have been killed.
   The two large parties have summoned generals out of retirement
to appear in TV ads and bolster their arguments over whether Israel
can risk yielding the territory to Arab control.
   ``The distance from Jordan to Jerusalem is about 12 miles,''
warns Likud's Yehoshua Saguy, a former head of military
intelligence.
   Standing on heights overlooking Jerusalem, Saguy points down a
road once used by Iraqi tanks. ``The message is simple: We cannot
leave these hills. This is the security of the coastal plain''
where two-thirds of Israel's 4.2 million people live.
   Maj. Gen. Ori Orr, ex-West Bank commander, is shown driving
through Nablus, the largest city in the West Bank and a focus of
the Palestinian rebellion. He suggests that controlling a hostile
population is unworkable and rejects Likud's argument that more
force is the answer.
   ``Whoever promises to end the intefadeh (Arabic for uprising)
with military means is mistaken. The solution to this problem is
political,'' he says.
   Peres supports Arab calls for an international conference on
Middle East peace, and Labor leaders have suggested they would be
willing to talk with the Palestine Liberation Organization, viewed
by Israel as a terrorist group, if the PLO abandons armed attacks
and recognizes Israel's right to exist.
   Peres argues that if Israel annexes the 2,266 square miles of
land occupied in 1967, as some right-wing politicians have
demanded, an Arab majority will emerge and destroy the Jewish
character of the country.
   Shamir's peace program rules out territorial concessions to the
Arabs, talks with the PLO or an international conference. He
advocates negotiations on the basis of the Camp David autonomy plan
embodied in Israel's peace treaty with Egypt.
   Yaakov Ezrachi of the Labor-aligned Decima Poll said voters
appear prepared to give up territory but want guarantees that it
would work.
   ``The voter is confused. He wants peace. But he doesn't believe
the Arabs,'' Ezrachi told reporters.
   Bethanie Horowitz, also of Decima, said initial reaction to the
intefadeh was a sharp swing to the right. But she predicted a
``surprise Labor victory'' because a majority has emerged which
wants to get rid of the burden of occupation.
   Mina Zemach of the Likud-hired Dahaf Poll said Likud was
expected to do well among first-time voters aged 18 to 22, about 10
percent of total voters. She said they were ``more hawkish,''
partly because of their experience as soldiers dealing with rioters.
   The polls have shown a neck-and-neck race with each party able
to win about 42 seats in the 120-seat Parliament. In 1984, Labor
won 44 and Likud won 41 seats. Twenty-eight parties are fielding
candidates and about half are likely to win a place in the
parliament.
   Likud appears to have the advantage in forming a coalition _ the
form of government that had run Israel since its founding _ because
Likud has a better rapport with the small religious parties which
are expected to get 11 or 12 seats.
   Polls are not entirely reliable because Arabs, ultra-Orthodox
Jews, kibbutz communal farmers and soldiers currently serving in
the army are not surveyed, said Rachel Yisraeli of the independent
Modiin Ezrachi poll. She said slum areas also are under-represented.
   Shamir says his party has broader appeal and a more modern
approach to the economy. He portrays Labor as speaking for European
Jews and the outmoded ideas of Israel's socialist founders.
   ``Labor represents a certain class. We care about all groups,''
he said in an interview during a campaign stop in Kfar Sava, near
Tel Aviv. ``The concept of Labor belongs to the past. It belongs to
East Europe at the beginning of the century.''
   Labor efforts appear centered on Sephardim, or Jews whose
families originated from North Africa and the Middle East. They
make up about 55 percent of Israel's 2.1 million voters and their
surge to the Likud in 1977 ended 29 years of Labor government.
   Labor strategists have defined the undecided or ``floating
voter'' as being aged 30 to 50, of Sephardic origin, with a
high-school education and above-average income.
   David Elazar, a political analyst for the Jerusalem Center for
Public Affairs, told reporters that Likud got about 70 percent of
the Sephardic vote in 1984 but would get less this time.
   Labor has been trying hard to change its image as an
establishment party dominated by Ashkenazi Jews of European origin.
   Party officials note that for the first time there is a large
Sephardic representation on the party's list of candidates with 16
Sephardim having a chance at getting into parliament.
   One Labor TV ad featured Ely Dayan, the Moroccan-born mayor of
Ashkelon who complained that roads in the Negev Desert went
unrepaired while Likud governments squandered money on developing
the West Bank.
   Peres has concentrated his personal campaign in low-income
districts with heavy concentrations of Sephardic Jews. But the
reception has often been hostile.
   On a recent walking tour of the open-air market of Ramle, 12
miles east of Tel Aviv, scores of young Sephardic Jews jostled and
booed Peres, taunting him with chants of ``go home,'' ``traitor''
and ``PLO.'' The next day Peres was sprayed with water in Beit
Shemesh, also a predominantly Sephardic area.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 23</NOTE>
