<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   10-13 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0499</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Real estate mogul Donald Trump has agreed to buy
Eastern Airlines' profitable Northeast shuttle for $365 million in
cash and will rename it after himself, but if Eastern's unions get
their way the deal will collapse.
   Trump and Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern's parent Texas Air
Corp., announced the sale Wednesday.
   Unionists vowed a fight, saying the shuttle is Eastern's most
valuable operation and the sale would kill the entire airline.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Analysts say Eastern Airlines' decision to sell the
shuttle to developer Donald Trump raises more questions about the
future of the loss-ridden carrier, but Eastern management contends
the sale will strengthen it.
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said after the deal was announced
Wednesday that the Miami-based airline would gain badly needed cash
to pay bills while maintaining marketing relationships and route
tie-ins. Also, the shuttle would not go to an existing competitor,
he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The next president could be forced to preside
over a sharp decline in U.S. living standards unless he acts
quickly to deal with pressing international economic problems, two
staff members of the private Council on Foreign Relations say.
   The president's ability to deal with economic problems has been
fundamentally altered because financial markets have coalesced into
a single worldwide market, the specialists wrote in a new book,
``After Reagan: Confronting the Changed World Economy,'' unveiled
Wednesday in Washington.
   Authors C. Michael Aho and Marc Levinson pointed to the
worldwide collapse of stock markets last Oct. 19 as a warning of
what can happen if investors lose confidence in the ability of
governments to manage their international affairs.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shamrock Holdings Inc. has intensified
the pressure in its battle to acquire Polaroid Corp., charging in
newspaper ads that the instant camera giant is fanning ``fear and
concern'' among its employees.
   Full-page advertisments in two Boston papers Wednesday followed
a sharply worded exchange between the presidents of the two
companies over Polaroid's rejection of Shamrock's request to meet
with stockholders about its $2.6 billion, $42-a-share tender offer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Personal computer industry pioneer Steve
Jobs finally has shown the world his Next computer workstation,
calling it a ``university on a desktop'' during a glitzy premier
demonstration.
   ``This will serve not only as the latest state-of-the-art
technological took, but as a partner in thought,'' Jobs told 3,000
guests Wednesday at San Francisco's posh Louise M. Davies Symphony
Hall.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Haft family, a takeover clan already bidding
for one of the largest supermarket chains, apparently also is
gunning for the nation's biggest drugstore chain.
   Executives of drug giant Walgreen Co. disclosed Wednesday that
the Hafts are interested in acquiring a substantial stake of their
company. The Hafts, well-known for takeover forays, have been
seeking grocery giant Kroger Co.
</TEXT>
