<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   10-13 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0555</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Rules Committee has killed a bill
that would have pumped $5 billion into the fund that insures
deposits in the nation's 3,000 savings institutions.
   The committee decided Wednesday to indefinitely postpone floor
debate on the measure by the full House after members argued that
any attempt to bring more money into the ailing insurance fund
should wait until early next year when a study of the industry is
completed.
   With only about a week before Congress adjourns for the fall
election campaign, the action effectively blocks the bill until
next year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sundstrand Corp. has agreed to plead guilty to
federal fraud charges and pay a $115 million settlement for
overbilling the Pentagon for airplane parts over five years,
federal prosecutors said.
   U.S. Attorney Anton Valukas said Wednesday the settlement
includes ``tens of millions of dollars'' in penalties against the
aerospace contractor.
   A further investigation of individuals at Sundstrand will be
completed in two or three months, Valukas said, noting the plea
agreement calls for the company to cooperate in that probe.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has issued an order temporarily
blocking Britain's Grand Metropolitan PLC from acquiring an
interest in Pillsbury Co. and blocking Pillsbury from making any
moves to thwart Grand Met's $5.2 billion takeover bid.
   The temporary restraining order issued Wednesday by District
Court Judge Thomas Carey lasts until Oct. 27, when the judge will
hear further arguments in Pillsbury's lawsuit seeking to block the
unsolicited $60-a-share tender offer by the hotel and liquor
conglomerate.
   Pillsbury sued to block the offer on grounds it violates state
tied-house statutes that prevent liquor distillers from selling
liquor in retail outlets.

</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kroger Co. employees are concerned that
another takeover attempt might be looming, even though a big
investment firm has withdrawn its $5.03 billion buyout bid and the
giant supermarket chain has undertaken a major defensive
restructuring.
   Employees at Kroger headquarters say they are relieved Kohlberg
Kravis Roberts & Co., which specializes in corporate takeovers,
withdrew its $64-a-share buyout offer on Tuesday.
   But concern about Kroger and their jobs remains, especially
because rival suitor Dart Group Corp. has not apparently withdrawn
its bid yet.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This year's drought-reduced corn crop is
expected to yield 4.55 billion bushels, an increase of 2 percent
from last month's estimate, the Agriculture Department reports.
   The figure disclosed Wednesday was still 36 percent below last
year's harvest, reflecting the heat and lack of rain that cut
sharply into this summer's production and still represented a
five-year low.
   Soybean production was forecast at 1.5 billion bushels, up 2
percent from September's estimate, but still 22 percent below 1987.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices took their sharpest drop in nearly two months
Wednesday as traders awaited the latest monthly report on U.S.
trade. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 30.23 points to
2,126.24.
   The dollar fell to its lowest point since the early summer. Gold
prices mostly were higher.
   Government bond prices declined.
   Energy futures rallied sharply; livestock and meat gained;
grains and soybeans were mixed; and stock-index futures retreated.
</TEXT>
