<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 0129EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Eastern-Trump Bjt   10-13 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Eastern-Trump, Bjt,0615</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trump's Purchase of Eastern Shuttle Faces Union, Government
Hurdles</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY97 of Oct. 12</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald Trump's deal to buy Eastern Airlines'
profitable Northeast air shuttle for $365 million in cash still
faces the hurdles of government scrutiny and a legal attack by
Eastern's unions.
   The real estate developer announced the purchase at a joint news
conference Wednesday with Texas Air Corp. Chairman Frank Lorenzo,
who had agreed earlier to sell the three-city shuttle to Trump. The
ailing Eastern, based in Miami, is a major subsidiary of Texas Air.
   Lorenzo said the deal, under which the service between New York,
Boston and Washington would become the ``Trump Shuttle,'' is
expected to be completed by Dec. 15. He said he did not foresee any
significant legal or regulatory barriers to the sale.
   But Eastern's militant union leaders said the sale would be the
death of the airline and vowed a fight to overturn it.
   ``Our attorneys and financial consultants will be taking a very
close look at this one,'' said Jack Bavis, chairman of the pilots
union at Eastern. ``And it wouldn't surprise me if some interested
members of Congress got involved, given Lorenzo's past history of
wheeling and dealing.''
   The Eastern machinists union indicated it would to seek a
federal court order against the shuttle sale.
   In Washington, attorney Joseph Guerrieri, representing the
machinists, said he planned to file later this week a request for
the U.S. District Court in Washington to grant an injunction
against the sale.
   Earlier this year, the Eastern unions successfully blocked in
the courts Lorenzo's attempt to transfer the shuttle operation from
Eastern to a new Texas Air subsidiary for $225 million.
   Besides the new court challenge threatened by the unions, the
sale to Trump also must be approved by the Department of
Transportation, which could take from 60 to 90 days.
   The department is not expected to have any concerns about the
sale on antitrust grounds, according to a DOT official in
Washington who asked not to be identified by name.
   Trump now operates a helicopter service, Trump Air, between New
York and Atlantic City, N.J., where he owns three hotel-casinos.
The operation is too small to raise antitrust concerns if combined
with the shuttle, the official said in an interview.
   Trump still must get a new operating certificate for the shuttle
from the Federal Aviation Administration, because some of the
shuttle's personnel may be changed and the new employees may have
different training backgrounds, the DOT official said.
   The DOT also judge the new owner's fitness to operate the
shuttle, examining the managerial and technical ability of Trump
and his senior managers, Trump's financial posture and the
likelihood he will comply with safety regulations and other rules.
   But Trump ``doesn't all of a sudden have to become an airline
expert,'' said Robert Joedicke, an industry analyst for the
investment firm Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Trump said Wednesday he had named Bruce R. Nobles, who formerly
ran Pan Am Corp.'s rival shuttle service, as president of the Trump
Shuttle. Nobles has been working at Continental Airlines, the other
big Texas Air subsidiary.
   Trump and Lorenzo said the shuttle would maintain fares
competitive with the Pan Am service and would not lay off any
employees. The $365 million price tag includes landing rights at
airports in the three shuttle cities plus 17 Boeing 727s.
   The blue-silver Eastern aircraft will be redecorated and
emblazoned with red, black and gold stripes, and will carry the
word ``Trump'' on their tails.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
