<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 0130EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Eastern-Casinos Bjt   10-13 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Eastern-Casinos, Bjt,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gambling Resort Hopes Trump Brings His New Jets To His Casinos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald Trump's purchase of the
Eastern Airlines shuttle is prompting speculation and hope among
local officials that this seaside resort _ where Trump owns three
casinos _ might be a big beneficiary of the deal.
   Trump would not say he definitely plans to use the shuttle to
bring gamblers to Atlantic City, but said Wednesday that ``it's
something that we're looking at.''
   Right now, Atlantic City gets most of its 30 million annual
visitors by car and bus, from cities several hours away.
   ``We have an airport capable of handling the Concorde,'' Gerald
Greenberg, president of the Atlantic City Hotel-Motel Association,
said Wednesday, ``and it certainly has the potential to handle
Trump's shuttle.''
   ``We need more air service to Atlantic City, more people coming
from distant markets,'' Greenberg said.
   Trump announced Wednesday he would pay $365 million in cash to
buy the shuttle from Eastern, a major subsidiary of Texas Air Corp.
   The shuttle, which will be refurbished and renamed ``The Trump
Shuttle,'' is a profitable carrier serving Boston, New York and
Washington.
   Trump said the possibility of using the fleet's 17 Boeing 727s
for shuttle service during the week and for Atlantic City junkets
on weekends was ``an interesting concept.''
   Marvin B. Roffman, an analyst with the Philadelphia investment
firm Janney Montgomery Scott Inc. said the deal ``does not revolve
around Atlantic City. He's buying the shuttle because it makes good
business sense.''
   ``But it fits into Atlantic City definitely in the next couple
of years,'' Roffman said. ``Right now there are a limited number of
hotel rooms in Atlantic City. But after Trump gets the Taj Mahal
(casino hotel) built, then he'll have 2,250 rooms in his three
hotels.
   ``So I'm sure he'd like to fly in at least 15,000 to 20,000
people a month.''
   Atlantic City Airport, located about 10 miles outside of the
city, is underused by most standards. A long-standing political
dispute among Atlantic County and community officials over control
of the airport has delayed plans for a $50 million expansion.
   In May, some progress was made when USAir began offering
regularly scheduled jet service from its Pittsburgh hub to the
airport, which has been used primarily by chartered and commuter
flights. The airline declined to give statistics on its passenger
traffic into Atlantic City.
   But before USAir, charter and commuter flights delivered just
324,000 of the city's 30 million annual visitors. By comparison,
5.8 million of the 15.2 million visitors who travel to Las Vegas,
Nev., annually arrive by plane.
   Studies indicate that if jet service had been available in
Atlantic City in 1986, 300,000 more visitors would have flown to
the resort.
   Atlantic County spokesman Michael Crowley said Wednesday that
the county would welcome seeing Trump or any other airline bring in
more flights.
   ``And our interest is not exclusively for the casino industry,''
he said. ``We're also thinking in terms of the people who live
right here, so they would be able to get air service from their
hometown airport instead of having to drive to Newark or
Philadelphia.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
