<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 0131EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Next-SteveJobs Bjt   10-13 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Next-Steve Jobs, Bjt,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Computer `Whiz Kid' Out to Prove He's Matured</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steve Jobs helped pioneer the personal
computer and then turned the industry on its head with a whole new
version of it, but the guru of new technology still must prove
himself.
   The big question Wednesday as the 33-year-old ``father'' of the
Apple II and the Macintosh unveiled his new Next computer
workstation was whether Jobs, ousted three years ago from Apple
Computer Inc., remains an enfant terrible who stumbled on fame and
fortune.
   Was he what author Lee Butcher called an ``accidental
millionaire,'' a megalomaniac who ruthlessly capitalized on others'
achievements?
   Or does he have the entrepreneurial genius capable of creating
what he calls ``insanely great'' new computer products?
   ``The whole story of his computer debut is not so much a story
in a business sense of its possible success or failure, but a part
of the whole myth-building process. The media is trying to tell the
story of what's happening to Steve Jobs,'' said Steve Wozniak, who
co-founded Apple Computer with Jobs in 1976.
   ``I hope the media can judge him for qualities other than his
folk-hero image,'' Wozniak said. ``He deserves a chance to be let
off the hook, if that's necessary.''
   Separating the myth from the fact of Jobs may be impossible.
   Jobs himself refuses to discuss the character questions that
have followed him since his much-publicized dethroning at Apple,
and says only that he is interested in the future, not the past.
   Some praise of Jobs for the Next already is coming in from those
convinced that his attempts to make developing technology available
to the widest number of consumers reflects the spirit necessary to
drive the American computer industry into the 21st century.
   ``I think the Next clearly shows that what Steve did in the past
at Apple was no fluke,'' said Jonathan Seybold, a leading Los
Angeles-based trade publisher.
   ``He is the kind of leader who gets people to achieve what they
felt they couldn't achieve,'' Seybold said.
   Jobs is touting the Next as a super personal computer that gives
ordinary people the kind of technology previously available only to
engineers.
   But because he has allowed only limited trial use of the
machine, neither the industry nor the marketplace has decided with
any finality whether his claim is hype or reality.
   Unless he proves the Next offers another revolutionary step in
computers, Jobs could join the ranks of other industry pioneers
whose latest endeavors have failed to have much impact.
   Public perceptions of Jobs may have changed since he was at
Apple. In his book, ``Accidental Millionaire,'' Butcher has
described him as a moody, tyrannical, abrasive and arrogant boss,
contrary to the widespread public perception of him as an amiable,
somewhat eccentric, collegial researcher.
   John Sculley, the former president of the Pepsi-Cola division of
PepsiCo, came to Apple in 1983 as its chief executive officer and
gave Jobs ``greater power than he ever had and I had created a
monster,'' he wrote in last year's best-selling ``Odyssey: Pepsi to
Apple...''
   Both Butcher and Sculley have contended that Jobs, during his
tenure as head of Apple's Macintosh division, almost destroyed
Apple by ignoring the opinions of others, berating employees and
insinuating himself into every decision.
   Both describe him as charismatic, but claim he was lucky, not
talented, when it came to his past business successes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
