<DOCNO> AP881013-0289 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 0221EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Pillsbury Bjt   10-13 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pillsbury, Bjt,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Jousting Continues Between Pillsbury, Grand Metropolitan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court order temporarily blocking Grand
Metropolitan PLC from acquiring any interest in Pillsbury Co. also
blocks Pillsbury from making moves that could thwart Grand Met's
$5.2 billion takeover bid.
   The temporary restraining order issued Wednesday by Hennepin
County District Court Judge Thomas Carey lasts until Oct. 27, when
the judge will hear further arguments in Pillsbury's lawsuit
seeking to block the unsolicited $60-a-share tender offer by the
British liquor and hotel conglomerate.
   The order temporarily enjoins Grand Metropolitan from acquiring
any interest in Pillsbury, while barring Pillsbury from taking any
action to alter the status quo before the Oct. 27 hearing.
   The judge also scheduled a hearing today to finalize terms of
the order.
   Pillsbury sued to block the tender offer on grounds it violates
state tied-house statutes that prevent liquor distillers from
selling liquor in retail outlets. Pillsbury's retail liquor outlets
include the full-service restaurant chains of Steak & Ale and
Bennigans.
   Pillsbury closed up 12{ cents at $56.87{ a share Wednesday on
the New York Stock Exchange.
   The Minneapolis-based food and restaurant company is fighting
the takeover attempt but has not officially responded to the bid.
Pillsbury must reject or accept the offer by Oct. 19 to conform to
federal securities laws, said Johnny Thompson, vice president of
public relations for Pillsbury.
   Thompson said the order, among other things, would temporarily
prevent Pillsbury from such actions as making major acquisitions.
   Allen Finkelson, chief counsel for Grand Metropolitan, said
Carey's ruling was important because it blocks Pillsbury from
taking action that could thwart the deal.
   But he also said the order could slow the pace at which market
professionals buy Pillsbury stock for the purposes of tendering it
to Grand Met, which would lower the stock price and decrease the
momentum of the takeover bid.
   ``People will become less sure that the offer will become
sucessful so they don't buy the stock,'' Finkelson, said.
   He added that the full impact of the judge's ruling would not be
known until it is finalized.
   Finkelson said Grand Metropolitan already is prohibited by
federal securities law buying Pillsbury shares until its tender
offer expires on Nov. 1. The offer could be extended.
   Larry Haeg, a Pillsbury spokesman, said Carey's ruling
temporarily maintains the status quo in the relationship between
Pillsbury and Grand Metropolitan as litigation in 13 other states
related to the tied-house statutes continues. Grand Metropolitan is
seeking waivers from the laws, saying it will immediately sell
Pillsbury's liquor retail outlets if the takeover succeeds.
   Pillsbury had obtained restraining orders in eight states
blocking Grand Metropolitan from acquiring Pillsbury stock, but the
restraining orders have dissolved in four of those states,
spokesmen for the two companies said.
   Separately, Grand Metropolitan issued a news release late
Wednesday, saying Minnesota Commerce Commissioner Michael Hatch has
ruled that the tender offer meets disclosure requirements under the
state's anti-takeover law.
   Under the law, Hatch has the power to suspend tender offers if
he determines Minnesota shareholders are not provided with enough
information about the deal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
