<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 0222EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-HollyFarms-Tyson Bjt   10-13 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Holly Farms-Tyson, Bjt,0616</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tyson Must Sweeten Pot To Buy Holly Farms, Analysts Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tyson Foods Inc. may have to sweeten its
$891 million buyout offer before Memphis-based Holly Farms Corp.
gives in to the bid from its rival poultry processor.
   Holly Farms officials on Wednesday would say only that they were
considering Tyson's offer of $45 cash and a quarter share of its
Class A common stock for each of Holly Farms' 18.1 million
outstanding shares.
   Tyson, of Springdale, Ark., is the nation's largest poultry
processor. A Holly Farms buyout would increase Tyson's market share
from 18 percent to 28 percent, analysts said.
   ``I think Holly Farms will sell to Tyson only as a last
resort,'' said John M. McMillin, an analyst with Prudential-Bache
Securities in New York.
   McMillin said he valued Holly Farms at $55 a share or more. He
said the Tyson offer amounts to about $49.25 a share.
   ``If Tyson wants to buy the company he's going to have to pay
$55,'' McMillin said.
   Holly Farms stock rose sharply in heavy trading, jumping $6.62{
a share to $49.62{ in composite New York Stock Exchange trading.
Tyson fell 62{ cents a share to $17 in over-the-counter trading.
   Based on Wednesday's closing price, Tyson's offer would be worth
$49.25 a share, or about $891.4 million.
   Holly Farms officials could not be reached for comment Wednesday
night.
   McMillin also speculated Holly Farms alternatively would pursue
a leveraged buyout by managers who will seek to take the company
private.
   ``There's a couple of options,'' McMillin said. ``One is to look
for a white knight, which could potentially be a Phillip Morris or
a Sara Lee...look for a company to basically choose who they want
to get married to.
   ``The other is to pursue a management-led leveraged buyout, take
the company private. I think that's what they're pursuing right
now,'' McMillin said.
   John Lawrence, an associate analyst for Morgan Keegan in
Memphis, said he believes Holly Farms could be bought out by Tyson
at a price in the range of $50 to $55 a share.
   Hours before Tyson announced its offer late Tuesday, Holly Farms
announced it had been approached by an unidentified company
regarding a possible business combination. Holly Farms said no
specific proposal had been received and the company did not intend
to seek one.
   The company also said it had activated a shareholder rights
plan, commonly known as a ``poison pill'' takeover defense, aimed
at making a hostile takeover prohibitively expensive.
   ``We haven't heard a word. We are just waiting on whatever
decision they are making over there. We are standing by,'' Bob
Justice of Tyson Foods said Wednesday. ``We do have a timetable of
Oct. 19. That's our deadline. Hopefully, they can make a decision
prior to that. And we feel optimistic about a response before
that.''
   Officials of the two companies met four weeks ago in Memphis.
Tyson asked for access to nonpublic corporate information from
Holly Farms to help determine whether a higher offer was warranted.
   Tyson, which posted sales of about $1.8 billion last year,
produces 14 million pounds of chicken meat each week from an
operation that includes hatcheries, feed mills, processing plants
and a sophisticated marketing arm. The company sells both whole
chickens and ``value enhanced products'' to supermarkets, fast food
chains and institutional customers.
   Holly Farms is a diversified foods company, with about 50
percent of its sales concentrated in chicken. The company, which
also mills flour and provides other meats for the food service
industry, had sales of about $1.6 billion last year.
</TEXT>
