<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Walgreen Bjt   10-13 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Walgreen, Bjt,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Walgreen Reveals Haft Interest in Stock, Reports Successful Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walgreen Co. ``will not be distracted'' from its
aggressive growth plans by the Haft family's bid to acquire a stake
in the nation's largest drugstore chain, says Chairman Charles R
Walgreen III.
   The Hafts, who already are bidding on the food retailer Kroger
Co., have applied for federal clearance to buy at least $15 million
of the drug retailer's stock, Walgreen said.
   The disclosure came Wednesday as Walgreen reported a 22 percent
increase in its fourth-quarter net income and a 25 percent profit
gain during the company's 1988 fiscal year.
   Walgreen stock rose $1.25 to $35.25 a share in New York Stock
Exchange composite trading Wednesday.
   Based on that closing price and Walgreen's roughly 61.5 million
outstanding shares, a $15 million investment would give the Hafts a
stake of about six-tenths of 1 percent in Walgreen.
   The Hafts, who control Dart Group Corp., have a reputation as
corporate raiders who buy large amounts of stock in companies they
have ostensibly targeted for takeover and later sell their shares
back to those companies or other suitors at a hefty profit.
   Neither the Hafts nor Landover, Md.-based Dart would comment on
their plans regarding Walgreen, which operates more than 1,400
stores in 29 states.
   Walgreen, the company's chairman, said the Deerfield, Ill.-based
chain would ``take all actions necessary to protect the company and
its shareholders.''
   ``Walgreen Co. intends to continue the course on which its
success has been built _ concentrating on our core business,
growing that business carefully through a program of planned
expansion and providing our customers with high quality products
and service,'' the chairman said in a statement.
   ``We will not be distracted from that course.''
   The Walgreen chain has grown by 562 stores in the past five
years. The company said it plans to open another 100 stores in
fiscal 1989.
   The Hafts sold their 77-store Dart discount drugstore chain in
1984 for $160 million and have said they intend to acquire another
retailing company.
   Despite apparent attempts to acquire such chains as Federated
Department Stores Inc., May Department Stores Co., Supermarkets
General Corp., Dayton Hudson Corp., the Hafts have yet to complete
a takeover.
   The Hafts have also indicated interest recently in F.W.
Woolworth Co. and Zayre Corp., but have not made bids for those
retailers.
   Last month, Dart chairman Herbert Haft and his son, company
president Robert Haft, offered to buy Kroger for about $4.32
billion. The status of the bid was in doubt after the New York
investment firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts Inc. withdrew a $5.03
billion offer for Kroger.
   The Hafts offered last week to help Kroger fight the Kohlberg
bid by proposing to provide additional equity for Kroger's
previously-announced restructuring.
   Robert Haft reiterated that offer Tuesday, but declined to
comment on whether the Dart offer for Kroger has been withdrawn.
   Walgreen reported net income of $31.9 million, or 52 cents a
share, on sales of $1.2 billion for the three months ended Aug. 31.
   For the year ended Aug. 31, Walgreen reported net income of
$129.1 million, or $2.10 a share, on sales of $4.9 billion.
</TEXT>
