<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     10-13 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Drops For Third Straight Day, Stocks Also Lower</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar dropped today for the third straight
trading day because of what dealers said was uncertainty over the
U.S economy. Stocks were also lower.
   After opening at 127.90 yen, down from Wednesday's close of
129.65, the dollar moved between 127.75 yen and 128.35 yen. It
closed at 127.98 yen, down 1.67 yen. It fell a total of 3.85 yen
Tuesday and Wednesday.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, the Tokyo Stock
Exchange's main index, lost 136.07 points, or 0.50 percent, closing
at 27,273.30.
   Dealers said the markets declined because dealers believed the
U.S. economy is slowing and were wary of U.S. trade figures
scheduled for release today in Washington. They also said the
sudden decline of the dollar in Tokyo reflected its overnight fall
in London and New York.
   ``The market appears to be overreacting a bit, but there were
various elements since last week that could push the dollar down,''
said Toshikazu Kotoge, a dealer at Yasuda Trust Bank.
   He cited the lower-than-expected U.S. employment rate of 5.4
percent released last week and a growing feeling the U.S. trade
deficit is worsening.
   ``My impression is that (the yen's) appreciation was somewhat
too steep,'' Japan's Kyodo News Service quoted Finance Minister
Kiichi Miyazawa as saying. ``If the fluctuation is too wide for one
day, it better be tamed down.''
   But dealers said it was unlikely the dollar would dip below the
125-yen level as traders were likely to start buying at that rate.
   The dollar's closing today was the lowest since June 22, when it
closed at 127.60 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, dealers said uncertainty in the
foreign exchange market made investors already nervous over the
upcoming U.S. trade figures even more wary.
   ``Most export-oriented shares are down, reflecting the yen's
sudden appreciation,'' said Ichitaro Watanabe of Nikko Securities
Co. ``Only very few shares ... are gaining. But the market as a
whole was very quiet as expected ahead of the release of U.S. trade
figures.''
   The volume traded on the first section of the exchange, where
most major shares are listed, was a light 400 million shares.
   Also, dealers attributed the market slump to Emperor Hirohito's
poor health. Since he became bedridden Sept. 19, the Nikkei has
lost 456.99 points, or 1.6 percent.
   ``There is no clear logic to the relation between the emperor's
illness and the market,'' said Jeff Bahrenburg, an economist at
Merrill Lynch. ``But at least I can say a situation like this
creates uncertainties, and that one of the things market doesn't
like most.''
</TEXT>
