<1ST_LINE>r f BC-ChipProduction     10-13 0113</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Chip Production,0119</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chip Industry Indicator Slumps</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CUPERTINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The semiconductor industry's most
closely watched indicator fell to its lowest point in 22 months in
September, according to the Semiconductor Industry Association.
   The book-to-bill ratio stood at 0.97, meaning that for every
$100 worth of products shipped manufacturers obtained $97 in new
orders.
   The last time new orders fell below shipments was in November
1986 when the industry was pulling out of a slump.
   Mel Phelps, an analyst with Hambrecht & Quist, said customers
are using up inventories rather than buying new chips.
   ``I think that what we are experiencing is a rather rapid
dissipation of inventory,'' he said Wednesday.
</TEXT>
