<HEAD>Dollar Falls on U.S. Trade Report</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: updates with dollar falling sharply on U.S. trade report.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar sank today in Europe after the
U.S. government reported a larger-than-expected widening in the
U.S. trade deficit.
   Gold prices were mixed.
   The dollar, which had dropped during the morning, fell further
after the Commerce Department reported the U.S. merchandise trade
deficit swelled to $12.18 billion in August from $9.47 billion in
July.
   Traders had expected the deficit to widen to between $11 billion
and $12 billion.
   In addition to concern over the trade report, the upcoming U.S.
presidential election also was creating uncertainty in the market,
traders said earlier.
   ``We don't know whether the new president will talk the dollar
up or down,'' said a dealer at a European bank in Frankfurt.
   In London, the dollar plummeted a cent against the British pound
after the report was issued. It cost $1.7465 to buy one pound after
the report, compared with $1.7305 late Wednesday.
   Other dollar rates after the report was released, compared with
late Wednesday's prices, included: 1.8175 West German marks, down
from 1.8340; 1.5350 Swiss francs, down from 1.5587; 6.2150 French
francs, down from 6.2770; 2.0515 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0760;
1,356.60 Italian lire, down from 1,379.00; and 1.2093 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.2118.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar plunged for the third straight trading day because of
what dealers said was uncertainty about the U.S. economy. The
dollar closed at 127.98 yen, down 1.67 yen. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 127.00 yen after the trade report.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $409 an ounce, down from
$409.25 bid late Wednesday. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $408.60.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $408.60, up from $408.10 bid late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.69 to close at a bid $411.22.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.32 an ounce,
down from Wednesday's $6.35.
</TEXT>
