<HEAD>United Plans Large Purchase Of Boeing Jets, Paper Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Airlines is prepared to place an order for
Boeing 757 and 737 jets with a potential value of $6.15 billion, a
newspaper reported today.
   United spokesman Chuck Novak would neither confirm nor deny the
story in today's editions of the Wall Street Journal.
   ``That's a rumor and as a matter of company policy we do not
comment on rumors,'' he said.
   United, the nation's largest airline, plans to turn 30 previous
options for Boeing 757-200 jets into firm orders and take new
options for 40 more of the aircraft, the Journal reported, citing
unnamed industry sources.
   At about $45 million per aircraft, that part of the deal would
have a potential value of $3.15 billion, the newspaper said.
   In addition, the Journal said, Chicago-based United is ready to
place orders for 35 Boeing 737s and options for 65 more. Based on a
unit price of about $30 million, the 737s would have a potential
worth of $3 billion, according to the report.
   Boeing Co. would not comment on the story.
   ``We just don't discuss anything we are doing with any of our
customers without their permission,'' said Boeing spokeswoman
Elizabeth Reese in Seattle.
