<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 1133EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-TradeDeficit 4thLd-Writethru f0055 10-13 0783</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trade Deficit, 4th Ld-Writethru, f0055,0803</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Gap Widens by $2.7 Billion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 8 grafs for grafs 3-11 pvs with further market reaction
and background; picks up 12th graf pvs, Vice President.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. merchandise trade deficit swelled to
$12.18 billion in August as a record level of American exports was
swamped by an all-time high in imports, the government reported
today.
   The Commerce Department said that the imbalance between what the
United States imports and what it sells abroad climbed by $2.7
billion over a July deficit of $9.47 billion.
   The July figure, which followed a $13.22 billion June imbalance,
had been the smallest monthly deficit in more than three years.
Economists had expected an increase for August, but the actual
result was worse than the $11.3 billion many forecasters had
predicted.
   Financial markets had been tensed waiting for the trade report,
remembering that a worse-than-expected August deficit a year ago
had prompted a 95-point drop in the Dow Jones industrial average
just a few days before the Black Monday stock crash of Oct. 19.
   Today, however, the markets appeared to be riding out the bad
news.
   The dollar tumbled briefly in foreign exchange markets but soon
rebounded. The Dow Jones average climbed through the morning with
analysts saying the market appeared to have taken the news largely
into account with its decline on Wednesday.
   The Reagan administration moved quickly to put the best face on
the new trade figures, insisting that the August increase was only
a brief interruption to the downward trend in the deficit figures
evident for most of this year.
   Commerce Secretary C. William Verity said that if the wide
swings in July and August were averaged, the result would be a
monthly deficit of $10.8 billion for the two months, down from an
average of $11.8 billion in the first six months of the year.
   ``I have been saying for some time that we can hope for an
improvement of about $30 billion in our trade deficit this year.
The figures for the first eight months show that we are on target
at an annual rate of $139 billion,'' Verity said in a statement.
   Despite the administration's assurances, the widening deficit
was certain to provide ammunition for Michael Dukakis, who has
charged that the soaring trade deficits of the 1980s have cost
America millions of lost jobs and represent one of the greatest
failures of the Reagan administration.
   Vice President George Bush has sought to minimize month-to-month
variations in the deficit, pointing instead to the fact that the
deficit for the entire year is headed lower.
   For the first eight months of the year, the trade deficit is
running at an annual rate of $138.2 billion, a substantial
improvement from the record deficit of $170.3 billion suffered in
1987.
   Indeed, the shrinking of the deficit has been the principal
reason for the better-than-expected economic growth so far this
year. Economists attribute about half of overall growth to the
improving trade deficit.
   U.S. exports rose to a record level of $27.55 billion in August,
an increase of $1.03 billion over the July level.
   After suffering hard times from mid-1984 through 1986, American
industry has been enjoying a boom as the lower value of the dollar
has made U.S. goods competitive once again on overseas markets.
   But, unfortunately, the weaker dollar has not had much impact in
slowing Americans' appetite for imported goods, even though they
now cost more.
   Imports jumped to an all-time high of $39.72 billion in August,
an increase of $3.73 billion from the July level.
   Analysts have said that the country has seen about as much of an
improvement as can be expected from higher exports and a further
shrinking in overall deficit will not occur until imports begin to
fall.
   The rise in imports in August reflected identical increases of
$1.1 billion for business capital goods and consumer goods. Imports
of foreign cars were up $700 million while oil imports rose by $300
million to $3.7 billion.
   The higher foreign oil bill reflected an increase in volume as
the average price per barrel fell by 62 cents to $15.15 per barrel.
   The higher export sales reflected an increase of $800 million in
sales of American autos and a smaller rise of $200 million in the
category that includes farm products.
   By country, the largest deficit, as usual, was with Japan, an
imbalance of $4.8 billion, up from a July deficit of $4.4 billion.
The deficit rose to $1.7 billion with Taiwan, compared to $1.2
billion in July, while the deficit with Western Europe shrank to
$1.4 billion, down from $2.3 billion in July.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881013-0309 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 1144EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   10-13 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Slightly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened moderately
higher today on the Chicago Board of Trade in anticipation of
increased export sales due to poor crops elsewhere and the dollar's
weakness against other major currencies.
   The higher opening surprised analysts who had expected a drop in
prices based on Wednesday's crop production estimates from the
Agriculture Department, which projected slightly larger corn and
soybean crops than it had previously estimated.
   But the agency also reduced its estimates for end-of-the year
stockpiles of corn and wheat, reflecting expectations of greater
foreign demand for those grains.
   ``You've also got to realize the fact that the dollar was
sharply lower this morning and yesterday, and that should keep our
grains competitive on the world market,'' said Joel Karlin,
research analyst with Research Department Inc. in Chicago.
   Further support came from hopes of a new U.S.-Soviet long-term
grain purchase agreement, he said. Negotiators for the two
countries were scheduled to meet this afternoon in London.
   In early trading, wheat was 2\ cents to 3} cents higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.38 a bushel; corn was 1}
cents to 2\ cents higher with December at $2.98} a bushel; oats
were 1{ cents to 1} cents higher with December at $2.58{ a bushel;
soybeans were 2{ cents to 6} cents higher with November at $7.97 a
bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were slightly
higher in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .15 cent lower to .22 cent higher with October
at 72.82 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent lower to .25
cent higher with October at 82 cents a pound; live hogs were .10
cent to .40 cent higher with October at 40.70 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .87 cent to 1.08 cents higher with February at
49.05 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly higher on Wednesday.
