<1ST_LINE>r f BC-TW-Coniston     10-13 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-TW-Coniston,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coniston Reviews Options After TW Rejects Merger Proposal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coniston Partners said Thursday it is mulling
its options after food services giant TW Services Inc. rejected its
$1.4 billion merger proposal.
   In a statement issued late Wednesday, TW said its board turned
down the proposal after its financial advisers determined that the
$28 a share Coniston offered to pay was inadequate.
   The board reaffirmed TW's ``belief that its shareholders will be
served best by the company remaining independent,'' the statement
said.
   Augustus Oliver, a Coniston principal, said the partnership is
reviewing its alternatives, which include launching a hostile
tender offer. While Coniston is under no time constraints on making
a decision, Oliver reiterated the firm's interest in owning TW,
which runs the Denny's restaurant chain.
   New York-based Coniston already owns about 19 percent of TW's
48.5 million outstanding shares. The partnership outlined its
proposal for a friendly merger in a letter to the TW board earlier
this month.
   ``We're obviously disappointed at their response,'' Oliver said,
adding that ``it's worth noting that they never made any attempt to
contact us about the offer ... (or) to discuss their views on the
price.''
   In its letter to TW, Coniston said that while $28 a share was an
``extremely favorable price,'' it might be willing to offer more if
TW could ``demonstrate sufficient business prospects to justify
doing so.''
   Oliver said that Coniston still thinks the price is ``extremely
high, and we haven't heard anyone out there in the financial
community taking great issue with that.''
   On the New York Stock Exchange, TW was trading at $26.50 share
at midday, unchanged from Wednesday.
   TW Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Frank Salizzoni noted
that the company's earnings have grown at a rate in excess of 20
percent over the past two years and predicted the trend to continue
``for the foreseeable future.''
   ``We believe that our shareholders will benefit more from TW's
continued growth and performance than from the Coniston'' proposal.
   Oliver countered, however, that the board is protecting
shareholders and said, rhetorically, ``Why don't they simply let
the stockholders decide rather than make the decision for them?''
   In addition to Denny's, TW is a franchisee of the Hardee's
restaurant chain. The New York-based company also runs Canteen
Corp., a food services concern, and a small nursing home chain.
   TW reported net income of $47.2 million on sales of $2.5 billion
in 1987.
</TEXT>
