<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Bayer-Cooper     10-13 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Bayer-Cooper,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bayer USA Buys Cooper Technicon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Cooper Companies Inc. have reached
a definitive agreement to sell its Technicon unit to a subsidiary
of Bayer USA Inc., in a deal estimated at $500 million, the
companies announced Thursday.
   Miles Inc., a healthcare company headquartered in Elkhart, Ind.,
will buy all of the capital stock of Cooper Technicon Inc. for $212
million in cash. In addition, Cooper Technicon's outstanding debt,
estimated at $288 million, will be eliminated, the companies said.
   The proposed transaction is expected to be completed by the end
of the year, according to a Cooper statement.
   Cooper Technicon, based in Tarrytown, N.Y., had 1987 sales of
about $470 million. It develops, manufactures and markets automated
medical diagnostic systems for hospitals and large commercial
clinical laboratories.
   The sale does not include the company's worldwide contact lens
or plastic and reconstructive surgical products business.
   Cooper co-chairman Gary Singer said the deal means the company
is moving ``to complete our asset divestiture program and embark on
a restructuring and revitalization of the company.''
   The agreement is subject to the approval of Cooper shareholders
and regulatory agencies.
   ``The acquisition of Technicon achieves our strategic objectives
for the diagnostics business worldwide by strengthening the
company's representation in the hospital and commercial clinical
laboratory market segments,'' said Dr. Klaus H. Risse, president
and chief executive of Miles, which manufactures medical diagnostic
systems under the Miles and Ames names.
   Risse said Technicon will become part of Miles' Diagnostics
Business Group.
   Earlier this month, Cooper announced it had signed a letter of
intent to sell Cooper Surgical, its ophthalmic surgical products
business, to Alcon Laboratories for about $325 million.
   It sold its U.S. contact lens care solutions business to
Wesley-Jessen for $40 million.
</TEXT>
