<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0326</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market gained ground today, riding out
the news of a wider-than-expected U.S. trade deficit in August.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 10.14 to 2,136.38
by noontime on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 4 to 3 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 682 up, 514 down and
536 unchanged.
   Before the market opened the Commerce Department reported that
the trade deficit expanded to $12.18 billion in August from $9.47
billion the month before.
   The latest figure slightly exceeded advance estimates on Wall
Street, and send the dollar briefly tumbling in foreign exchange.
But the dollar soon steadied.
   Analysts said the stock market appeared to have taken the news
largely into account with its decline on Wednesday, when the Dow
Jones industrial average fell 30.23 points.
   Today's activity came as a sharp contrast to the release of the
August trade report a year ago, which prompted a 95-point drop in
the Dow just a few days before Black Monday on Oct. 19.
   Among actively traded blue chips, International Business
Machines rose 2[ to 119|; Sears Roebuck gained 1 to 41\, and
American Telephone & Telegraph was unchanged at 26{.
   Federal National Mortgage climbed 2] to 51{. On Wednesday the
company reported sharply higher earnings for the third quarter.
   Avon Products dropped 1\ to 24]. The company said it would post
losses for the third quarter and the year as a result of a $425
million charge to be taken on some discontinued operations.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.72 to 155.49. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .14 at 302.05.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 79 million shares at noontime,
up from 78.04 million at the same point Wednesday.
