<HEAD>VW Announces Executive Changes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TROY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president and chief executive officer of
Volkswagen of America Inc., has been named to the same position at
a Ford-Volkswagen joint venture in South America, the West
Germany-based automaker said Thursday.
   Noel Phillips will become president and chief executive officer
of Autolatina on July 1, 1989. The company was formed in 1987 when
Volkswagen and Ford Motor Co. merged their operations in Brazil and
Argentina.
   Hans-Jorg Hungerland, 47, will replace Phillips on March 1,
1989, the company said. Hungerland is export sales manager for
Volkswagen AG in Wolfsburg, West Germany, the parent corporation
for the American company.
   Hungerland joined Volkswagen in 1958 and was general manager of
the corporate service division of Volkswagen of America from 1980
to 1983.
   Phillips, 54, joined Volkswagen in South Africa in 1960 and
became executive vice president for sales and marketing for
Volkswagen of America in 1978. In 1981, he went back to South
Africa for two years as managing director of a holding company, and
returned to the United States at the end of 1982 as president and
chief executive officer of Volkswagen of America.
