<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BritishStocks 1stLd-Writethru   10-13 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Up 16.4 Points</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with closing prices</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the London Stock Exchange rose
strongly Thursday, as dealers breathed a sigh of relief that the
U.S. trade report for August did not confirm the market's worst
fears.
   World financial markets had suffered a bout of jitters before
the release of the report, with rumors circulating that there would
be a pronounced widening in the trade gap.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed up
16.4 points, or 0.9 percent higher, at 1,830.7, near the
mid-afternoon best level for the day of 1,831.1.
   Volume was modest, with 464.2 million shares changing hands,
compared with the 476.5 million shares traded Wednesday.
   The U.S. Commerce Department announced that the merchandise
trade gap for August widened to $12.18 billion from a revised $9.47
billion in July.
   Several market observers had predicted a shortfall between $11.3
billion and $12.5 billion, but rumors abounded that the trade gap
might balloon to as much as $15 billion.
   ``The market had braced for a number far worse,'' said Kevin
Gardiner, an economist at Warburg Securities in London.
   Gardiner suggested that the market had been looking back
nervously to a year ago, when the July trade figure of $17.08
billion unhinged world financial markets preceding the October
stock market crash.
   ``There was concern that history might repeat itself,'' Gardiner
said.
   But on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was 10.31
points higher at 2,136.56 as London trading ended Thursday, having
opened about 4 points lower.
</TEXT>
