<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 1317EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Tyson-Profile Bjt   10-13 0785</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tyson-Profile, Bjt,0811</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Khaki-Clad Poultry Millionaire Don Tyson: `We're Chicken Folks'</HEAD>
<HEAD>REPEAT for all needing</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LR3 of Oct. 12</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT CHARTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Don Tyson arrives at his sprawling Ozarks
corporate complex each workday attired in company-issue tan slacks
and shirt, just like most of his 17,000 employees in Arkansas.
   He even has his first name in red script on the chest, right
next to a red and orange Tyson Foods logo.
   The 58-year-old chairman of the nation's largest poultry
processing company says dressing fancy might keep him from visiting
its scores of growing houses and processing plants, which yield 14
million pounds of chicken a week.
   Besides, Tyson says he doesn't have to worry about whether his
tie complements his shirt.
   This is no country bumpkin. A Rolex peeks from beneath his khaki
shirt cuff, and a black Lincoln Continental is parked outside. This
week, Forbes magazine listed Tyson as the 245th wealthiest U.S.
resident, with an estimated net worth of $330 million.
   That means a lot of drumsticks have been sold since his father,
the late John Tyson, started the Springdale-based chicken company
``with half a load of hay and 5 cents in 1930.''
   That's how his son, who was unavailable Wednesday, described the
origin of the firm in a 1985 interview with The Associated Press.
   ``We're chicken folks. We're just nothing else. We don't shoot a
shotgun at the consumer. We shoot a rifle and its got chicken in it
every time we shoot,'' Tyson said.
   Tyson Foods' 1987 annual report listed gross annual sales of
$1.8 billion, with net income of $67 million.
   The report also offered the chairman's philosophy about
acquiring other companies, wrapped in the gleeful language Tyson
applies to his frequent Caribbean fishing trips: ``We'd buy this
afternoon if the right opportunity came along. Acquisitions are
like fishing _ you never know when you're going to snag one. Our
hooks are in the water all the time.''
   Tyson cast his hook eastward Tuesday to Memphis, Tenn.,
headquarters of Holly Farms, the nation's No. 3 poultry company.
   Tyson offered $45 cash and a quarter share of Tyson Foods' Class
A common stock for each of Holly Farms' 18.1 million outstanding
shares.
   The deal would be worth nearly $900 million based on Tuesday's
closing prices _ Holly Farms closed at $43 a share, up $2.37{ in
New York Stock Exchange trading, while Tyson rose 62.5 cents a
share to $17.62{ in national over-the-counter trading.
   From the booming northwestern corner of Arkansas, Tyson's
influence is felt across the Ozarks into the southern flatlands. A
Tyson mill at Pine Bluff, in the southeast, turns out processed
poultry. Buildings in Nashville, to the southwest, produce millions
of birds.
   The company has the biggest payroll in Arkansas farming, says
Clifton Meador, director of agriculture for the Arkansas Industrial
Development Commission. ``Tyson's means an awful lot to the economy
of Arkansas, that's all there is to it,'' he says.
   Don Allen, executive director of the Arkansas Poultry
Federation, estimates Tyson Foods controls about half of the
state's $1.53 billion broiler business, with the remainder split
among seven other companies.
   ``We're just trying to be good neighbors,'' says Tyson spokesman
Bob Justice.
   Tyson rarely grants formal interviews. But he was at stage
center last month as the Arkansas Business Council, comprised of 19
of the state's wealthiest businessmen, released a sweeping yearlong
study of education.
   The bearded, balding chicken chairman isn't all business. ``He
has a darn good sense of humor and he doesn't take himself too
seriously. He is very down to earth. He can tell a joke and he can
take one,'' Allen says.
   Tyson's headquarters are decorated with western sculpture. Two
colorful paintings of fighting cocks on his office wall were gifts
from actor Jack Lord. Carved eggs are worked with whimsy into the
room's wood trim, and it has a white domed ceiling, ``just like the
Oval Office,'' Tyson says.
   He was a major backer of Jimmy Carter's presidential campaigns
and chips in to Democratic treasuries. Country star Willie Nelson
has flown into the Ozarks to entertain for Tyson's birthday in a
hotel ballroom. Senators and governors have been special guests at
the parties.
   A major Tyson diversion is University of Arkansas sports.
Athletic Director Frank Broyles, who has known Tyson 30 years,
calls him ``a brilliant person and close personal friend.'' Tyson
pays $10,000 a year for Razorback Stadium's largest posh skybox,
where he entertains pals at Fayetteville football games.
   ``Don is dedicated to growth and prosperity, not just for our
program, but for the whole state,'' Broyles says, ``and he's got
one of the quickest minds of any person I've ever known.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881013-0318 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 1334EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-IndustryAutomation Bjt   10-13 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Industry Automation, Bjt,0675</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Manufacturers Slow In Adopting Computerized Machinery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American manufacturers need to install
more automated machinery or lose jobs and sales to efficient
foreign competitors that share technology with their peers,
according to a Harvard University study released Thursday.
   The survey of more than 1,300 U.S. metalworking plants concluded
that American industry is clinging to an outdated notion that big
firms should not share technological advances with potential
competitors.
   ``Relations between large and small firms is not part of the
business culture in the United States,'' said Maryellen R. Kelley,
an assistant management professor at Carnegie Mellon University in
Pittsburgh and one of the study's authors.
   ``That kind of boost to small manufacturers that encourages them
to automate is absent,'' she said.
   The study found that more than half of U.S. metalworking plants
have not installed any computer-controlled machinery and just one
in 10 plants planned to invest in computerization in 1988-89.
   ``In the long run, if small manufacturers in particular don't
modernize, they will no longer be able to compete ... with more
sophisticated foreign suppliers,'' Kelley said. ``That could
ultimately lead to a loss of jobs.''
   The study found that just 11 percent of machine tools used in
the American metalworking industry are computer-controlled. Kelley
said a similar 1985 study of Japanese firms found that 30 percent
of the total stock was computer-run.
   ``The model of the self-interested, do-it-alone small business
driven by a gear of cut-throat competition ... seems to be a
peculiarly American phenomenon,'' the report issued by the Center
for Business and Government at the John F. Kennedy School of
Government said.
   The authors said America's competitive culture ``must change if
U.S. industry is to continue to be an industrial power in the world
economy.'' In countries such as Japan and Italy potential
competitors as well as buyers and suppliers routinely share
information, they said.
   The survey of metalworking and machinery manufacturers in 21
durable goods industries, including hardware, plumbing and forging,
was based on a national mail questionnaire and interviews with more
than 1,300 firms nationwide. An equal distribution of companies
with workforces ranging from under 20 to more than 250 was used.
   The study, ``The State of Computerized Automation in U.S.
Manufacturing,'' was conducted from September 1986 to April 1987.
It was funded by the National Science Foundation and the U.S.
Congress' Office of Technology Assessment.
   According to the survey, 53 percent of U.S. plants use
conventional machinery while 47 percent have some type of
computer-operated machines.
   ``Surprisingly we found that there has not been much adoption of
competitive technology _ and this is after five years of economic
recovery,'' Kelley, a Kennedy School research associate, said in an
interview.
   Small manufacturers have resisted the adoption of
computer-controlled technology partly out of a fear of job losses
through automation and partly because high expenses would require
product diversification, Kelley said.
   ``It certainly seems that this technology is more efficient and
seems to be more flexible,'' she said. ``But that means a shift in
business strategy is required.''
   The 22 percent of plants that said they have not adopted
computer-controlled technology and have no plans to do so accounted
for 1 million jobs in 1986 _ jobs Kelley said are threatened by
foreign competition.
   The industries surveyed make tools used in machinery for
production of a variety of durable goods, from furniture to
clothing. Kelley said three types of machines dominate the field:
numerically controlled, computer numerically controlled and
flexible manufacturing systems.
   Numerically controlled machinery is usully manually operated.
Computer numerically controlled machinery allows machines to be
programmed to automatically execute a set of metal-cutting
operations, which reduces the cost of set-up and permits repeat
runs of a product.
   Flexible manufacturing systems, used by just 1.5 percent of the
firms surveyed, are computer numerically controlled machines linked
by automatic material-handling equipment such as robots or
conveyors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881013-0319 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 2157EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f AM-ApparelSales Adv17   10-13 0828</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Apparel Sales, Adv 17,0856</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release AMs Monday Oct. 17 and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Apparel Sales Showing First Signs of Recovery</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Earlier this month, when the nation's largest
retailers announced their results for September, people with an eye
on apparel sales breathed just the barest sighs of relief.
   The numbers brought the first signals that a year-long drought
in clothing sales might be approaching an end. But, industry
watchers stress, the key word is ``might.''
   ``All of the major retailers are showing some fashion strength,
but it has to be taken in some context,'' said Walter Loeb, a
retail industry analyst with the investment firm Morgan Stanley &
Co.
   Donald I. Trott, who tracks specialty retailers for Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc., called September apparel sales ``very good,'' but
said he was not fully convinced they marked the beginning of a
trend.
   The nation's largest specialty apparel retailer, Limited Inc.,
reported that sales at its stores open for at least a year _ known
in the business as same-store sales _ rose 7 percent last month
from September 1987.
   The company's overall sales picked up 11 percent in September,
but analysts believe same-store sales more accurately reflect a
retailer's performance than figures that include the results of
newer stores.
   Fred Wintzer, an analyst with Alex. Brown & Sons Inc. in
Baltimore, was optimistic because Limited's sales have gradually
improved in recent months, especially at its Limited Express stores
that cater to teens and young women.
   Wintzer estimated Limited Express' same-store sales soared 30
percent in September, and said he expected Limited Inc. to be the
pacesetter for other apparel retailers.
   ``This is the company that will lead the pack,'' he said. ``The
rest of the industry will pick up on it after it's definitely
working at the Limited _ this is the way it always goes.''
   Limited and other retailers are trying to recover from the
problems they encountered in the fall of 1987: Fashion lines
fizzled as women shied away from shorter skirt lengths and decided
they had had enough of baggy, oversized casual wear.
   Clothing sales nosedived, and retailers, forced to take heavy
markdowns to clear merchandise, saw their profits slide as well.
And, because the stores had already ordered the same styles for
spring 1988, their slump persisted through this summer.
   For fall, retailers have experimented with more tailored and
dressy fashions and they reinstated longer skirts.
   Bloomingdale's, known for its trendy apparel, brought back a
large selection of ``career'' clothes not seen at the store for
several years.
   Limited stores _ the flagship division of Limited Inc. _ has
featured suits, and Limited Express, which sells mostly casual
clothes, has hints of the tailored look with pleated pants and
cable-knit cardigan sweaters.
   But while sales have improved, no one can point to a specific
fashion item or style that is extraordinarily successful.
   Gap Inc., which has continued to stress the casual look, says
its sales have come on a broad selection of merchandise.
   ``I can't put my finger on any individual items that have been
blowing out of the stores,'' said Warren Hashagen, Gap's vice
president and treasurer.
   ``We've got more fashion merchandise and a steady flow of new
items in new colors coming in,'' he said. ``That flow of
merchandise has caused customers to come back.''
   Gap does not report its sales monthly. However, Trott, of Dean
Witter, estimated Gap's same-store sales rose during September by a
percentage ``in the low to mid teens.''
   A year ago, Gap was the most prominent victim of the fashion
slump. After a disastrous August 1987, the company announced a
sharp downward revision in its expected profit for that quarter.
   Investors responded by dumping Gap and other retail stocks.
Gap's shares, which had traded at nearly $78 in August, plunged to
just under $37 a month later. In two days alone, the stock fell
nearly $19.
   Having watched the industry stumble its way through the ensuing
year, analysts say they have reasons to be cautious.
   For one thing, the September increases were what the analysts
call ``easy comparisons,'' because they were made against the
depressed results of a year earlier. The industry watchers say
sales must improve by double-digit percentages to be meaningful.
   Trott said several questions remain to be answered, such as how
much of the sales increase is due to price inflation.
   ``I'm not sure what that means in terms of numbers of garments
sold,'' he said of the September results.
   William Smith, an analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.,
said ``It's a bit early to generalize,'' and predicted October
sales would give a better idea of how healthy clothing sales are.
   And Wintzer, the Alex. Brown analyst, although upbeat about
Limited, said, ``For the rest of the industry to get in the swing
of this, the earliest it will happen is next spring.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv AMs Oct. 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
