<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     10-13 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Plummets on Trade News, Gold Prices Also Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar plummeted against major foreign
currencies in heavy selling Thursday after the American government
reported a sharp widening of the U.S. merchandise trade deficit in
August.
   However, the U.S. currency later managed to bounce back up above
its worst levels of the day.
   Gold prices also fell, but not as dramatically.
   The August deficit of $12.18 billion compared with a revised
shortfall of $9.47 billion in July, was near the top end of market
expectations, and prompted a bout of heavy selling that pushed the
dollar to a session low of around 1.8110 West German marks.
   ``The figure was as bad as expected, or maybe a bit worse,'' one
dealer at a U.S. bank in Frankfurt said. ``The dollar is now
battered.''
   Dealers said technical support at the 1.8100-mark level and
rumors that the U.S. Federal Reserve was checking dollar-yen rates
helped to push the dollar back to its closing levels.
   But market players added that sentiment remained bearish, and
most said they expected the dollar to continue its downward move.
   Any decline, however, would be limited by fear of central bank
effort to prop the dollar up.
   The Frankfurt dealer said: ``The central banks will make sure
that the dollar moves down only gradually. They don't want to risk
a crash, and just one year after the crash, this psychology is
strong in the market.''
   Some analysts say the October 1987 stock market crash was
triggered partly by worse-than-expected trade figures, which had
sent the dollar into a tailspin.
   is no way the central banks will let the dollar fall too far
ahead of the (U.S. presidential) elections in November,'' a London
dealer said.
   In London, the dollar sank against the British pound. It cost
$1.7470 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.7305 Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late
Wednesday's rates, included: 1.8193 West German marks, down from
1.8340; 1.5390 Swiss francs, down from 1.5587; 6.1995 French
francs, down from 6.2770; 2.0475 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0760;
1,354.00 Italian lire, down from 1,379.00; and 1.2084 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.2118.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar closed at 127.98 yen, down 1.67 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 127.95 yen.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $406.70 a troy ounce,
compared with $409.25 bid late Wednesday.
   In Zurich, gold was lower, closing at a bid $406.50 compared
with $408.10 bid late Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.69 to close at a bid $411.22.
   Silver bullion prices fell on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $6.29 a troy ounce, compared
with Wednesday's $6.35.
</TEXT>
