<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Prime-GE     10-13 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prime-GE,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Computer Buying GE's Calma Unit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Computer Inc. said Thursday it will acquire
General Electric Co.'s Calma business, which makes computer-aided
design and manufacturing systems, for an undisclosed price.
   The move will increase Prime's share of the computer-aided
design and manufacturing market while getting GE out of a
money-losing business which it entered with fanfare in 1981.
   With its $435 million takeover of Computervision Inc. in
February, Prime already is the second leading supplier behind
International Business Machines Corp. in the field of
computer-aided design and manufacturing systems.
   Calma, based in Milpitas, Calif., has 650 employees. GE, which
bought Calma for $170 million in 1981, said it has failed to earn a
profit in recent years, but the company declined to release figures
on either its sales or losses.
   Salomon Brothers Inc., a New York investment banking house,
estimated Calma's sales at $200 million in 1985 and $210 million in
1986.
   One of Calma's biggest customers has been Fairfield, Conn.-based
GE, which said it will give Prime ``preferred vendor'' status and
access to GE's corporate research in the field after the sale is
completed in approximately 90 days.
   Analysts said the acquisition appears to complement Prime's
current businesses, but could prove difficult for the Natick-based
computer maker to absorb.
   ``I think it's a good strategic move in the same sense and
direction that buying Computervision was. It could solidify the
company's position in the CAD-CAM market,'' said Carol E. Muratore,
an analyst with Morgan Stanley & Co.
   ``But strategy is only one part of the puzzle,'' she added.
``Execution is the other, and that remains to be seen. They're
still very early in the process of assimilating Computervision, and
there are no clear signs yet that they have done that well.''
   The companies said some reductions in Calma's workforce are
likely before the end of the year. But they said the numbers have
not been determined.
   Prime reported earnings of $21.7 million on revenues of $772.1
million for the first six months of this year. Those earnings were
down from $27.6 million in the same period of 1987, despite an
increase in revenues from $457.8 million. Most of the rise in
revenues was due to the Computervision takeover.
   Last week, former GE executive Anthony L. Craig was named to
succeed Prime President Joe M. Henson in a few months. Both
companies said the move was unrelated to the Calma sale.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881013-0323 </DOCNO>
