<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Raytheon     10-13 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Raytheon,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Raytheon Third-Quarter Earnings Rise 10.5 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Raytheon Co. said Thursday its
third-quarter earnings rose 10.5 percent over the same period last
year with the help of a 7.4 percent increase in sales.
   Raytheon said other factors contributing to the earnings jump
were its improved operating performance and lower taxes.
   Earnings rose to $126.6 million, or $1.91 per share, on sales of
$1.99 billion, compared with 1987's third quarter earnings of
$114.6 million, or $1.57 per share, on sales of $1.86 billion.
   ``The third quarter was another strong one for Raytheon,''
Chairman Thomas L. Phillips said in a prepared statement. ``We ...
received important government awards during the quarter for
submarine combat control systems, missile programs and FAA
technical support services.''
   The electronics and defense equipment manufacturer said sales in
major appliances continued to outpace those of last year, but
profits were lower due to higher material costs and stiff price
competition.
   Provisions for federal and foreign income taxes were $54.7
million in the quarter, compared with $61.6 million last year.
   For the first nine months of the year, Raytheon earned $362.3
million, or $5.43 per share, up 10.7 percent from $327.2 million,
or $4.44 a share, in the same period of 1987.
   Sales for the first nine months totaled $5.98 billion, up from
$5.52 billion.
</TEXT>
