<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Allied-Signal-Ozone     10-13 0111</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Allied-Signal-Ozone,0117</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Allied-Signal Gets Patent On CFC Substitute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allied-Signal Inc. said Thursday it has received
a patent for a new lubricating system that will permit the use of
substitutes for an ozone-depleting material in car air conditioners.
   The lubricating system is not suited for other kinds of air
conditioners or refrigerators, said Allied-Signal, of Morristown,
N.J., which has a big auto parts business.
   The system was developed at Allied-Signal's laboratory in
Buffalo, N.Y.
   It permits the use in car air conditioners of a substance called
HFC 134a that is a substitute for CFC-12, a chlorofluorocarbon that
contributes to the depletion of the Earth's protective ozone layer.
</TEXT>
