<1ST_LINE>u f PM-CreditCards 1stLd-Writethru f0034 10-13 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Credit Cards, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0034,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Considering Bill To Force More Credit-Card Disclosure</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Top 4 grafs new to update; picks up 3rd graf pvs, ``Under
present...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House today put off until Tuesday a vote
on Senate-approved legilsation to require issuers of credit and
charge cards to disclose information about interest rates, fees and
other details before consumers apply for the cards.
   The House leadership had promised members who wanted to leave
the nation's capital for the weekend that there would be no
roll-call votes after 1 p.m. today. The bill, although debated,
came up for a vote shortly before 2 p.m.
   Rep. Fernand J. St Germain, D-R.I., chairman of the House
Banking Committee, called the measure ``one of the most important
and strongest credit disclosure acts that we have been able to move
through the Congress since the first truth-in-lending statute was
passed 20 years ago.''
   He said the measure ``ends the hide-and-seek approach to
disclosures on credit card terms. It prevents sneak attacks on
unsuspecting consumers who often learn of charges and fees long
after the fact _ too late to reject the card and seek
alternatives.''
   Under present law, terms of credit and charge card accounts do
not have to be disclosed until after a card is issued. More than
105.5 million Americans hold 800 million of the cards.
   Sen. Christopher J. Dodd, D-Conn., consumer affairs subcommittee
chairman who sponsored the bill approved by the Senate on a voice
vote Tuesday night, said full, advance disclosure of card fees and
terms would enable consumers to weigh the costs and benefits of
signing up for particular credit or charge cards.
   Now, he said, the cost information is given to consumers too
late to make a difference.
   ``The information is often confusing and difficult to read, and
arrives at a time when the consumer cannot very well shop around
for a better rate,'' said Dodd. ``This late disclosure of
information is in sharp contrast to the way card issuers solicit
consumers. We all know how that is done. All you have to do is read
your mail to know that lenders rely heavily on mail solicitations.''
   The legislation would require all direct mail applications and
solicitations to contain clear information on the annual interest
rate, any minimum finance charge, any transaction fee, the grace
period and the method of calculation used in computing the balance
for interest purposes. Issuers also must clearly state any cash
advance fees, late fees and over-the-limit fees.
   The measure still falls short of the disclosure requirements
sought by some members of Congress and consumer groups.
   Rep. Frank Annunzio, D-Ill., chairman of the House Banking
consumer affairs subcommittee, said, ``This bill does not help the
consumer.''
   Leslie Gainer, an official of the Ralph Nader-organized U.S.
Public Interest Research Group, said the legislation fails to go
far enough with the new disclosure rules and pre-empts states from
passing stronger laws.
   The Consumer Bankers Association, which represents approximately
800 federally insured banks, savings and loans and credit unions,
endorsed the legislation.
   Joe Belew, the association president, said the measure
``provides for simple, meaningful disclosures which ensure that
consumers can compare terms on credit cards. Its enactment will
show that consumer and industry representatives can work together
to produce legislation which benefits the public.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881013-0326 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 1445EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-AutoSales     10-13 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Auto Sales,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Car Sales Rise, But Incentives Played a Part in Last Year's
Numbers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: AMs version planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Big Three U.S. automakers reported Thursday
that early October car sales rose 38.7 percent compared with the
same period last year, when the flurry over big incentives ended
with the new model year.
   General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. sold
173,156 U.S.-made cars during the Oct. 1-10 period this year,
compared with 140,408 cars in early October last year.
   There were eight selling days in the period this year, compared
with nine last year.
   Through the late summer and early fall of 1987, automakers drew
car buyers into showrooms with big cash-back incentives and
financing deals with interest rates as low as 1.9 percent.
   Some consumers accelerated their mid- or late-autumn car-buying
plans to take advantage of the incentives before they expired with
the 1987 model year on Sept. 30, 1987, resulting in
lower-than-anticipated sales figures for October of last year.
   For the calendar year through Oct. 10, the Big Three reported
U.S.-made cars sales of 5,479,125 vehicles in 1988, a 4.4 percent
rise from the 5,245,693 cars they sold during the same time last
year.
   There were 239 selling days in both Jan. 1-Oct. 10 selling
periods.
   Among the Big Three in early October, Ford showed the largest
increase, with car sales jumping 70 percent to 58,407 this year
compared with 38,662 last year. Light truck sales increased 23.1
percent to 33,574 in 1988 from 30,681 the year before.
   GM showed a 31.7 percent rise to 90,183 cars in early October
this year, compared with 77,032 cars during the period last year.
GM's light truck sales rose 29.3 percent in the Oct. 1-10 period
this year, going to 41,010 vehicles this year compared with 35,693
last year.
   Chrysler Corp.'s U.S.-made car sales rose 11.8 percent to 24,566
vehicles in early October, compared with 24,714 cars during the
same period last year. Its light trucks sales went to 19,297 during
this year's 10-day period from 19,667 during the same period last
year _ a 10.4 percent increase.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
