<2ND_LINE>BC-Penn Central,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Penn Central, Republic American to Merge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Penn Central Corp. will buy Republic American
Corp. for $249 million under a sweetened agreement announced
Thursday.
   Penn Central, a telecommunications and defense industry firm
which already owns 14.3 percent of Republic American's common
shares, said it will pay $15.75 per share in cash to buy the
remainder of Republic American's approximately 18.4 million common
shares outstanding.
   The Cincinnati-based Penn Central said it will acquire Republic
American by merging it with a newly formed Penn Central subsidiary.
Republic American sells workers' compensation insurance in
California.
   Officials said they expect the deal can be completed in early
1989.
   The agreement sweetens Penn Central's earlier acquisition
proposal to Republic American, announced in July, which provoked
some objections in court by Republic American stockholders.
   Under the original proposal, Penn Central said it would give
Republic American stockholders .65 of a Penn Central common share
for each outstanding Republic American common share. The market
price of Penn Central's common stock was then about $22.50 per
share.
   The two companies announced Thursday that the Republic American
stockholders who sued to challenge the original proposal as
inadequate have agreed to settle their lawsuits in view of the new
merger proposal.
</TEXT>
