<HEAD>Soybeans Lead Crop Futures To Higher Close</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed mostly higher
Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade with soybeans up sharply on
rumors that the Soviet Union may have bought 200,000 metric tons of
U.S. soybean meal, analysts said.
   Soybean meal for near-month delivery surged more than $7 a ton
while most soybean contracts gained more than 20 cents a bushel,
pushing the price for November delivery well above $8. Most of the
buying came late in the session after talk of the possible Soviet
purchase surfaced.
   ``They usually are large purchasers of meal in the
November-December period,'' said Joel Karlin, an analyst with
Research Department Inc. in Chicago. ``Prices had gotten down to a
level that started enticing foreign demand.''
   Grain futures closed mostly higher on spillover buying from the
soybean complex, he said.
   At the close, wheat was 2 cents lower to } cent higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.35 a bushel; corn was }
cent to 2{ cents higher with December at $2.97 a bushel; oats were
3{ cents lower to 1 cent higher with December at $2.57{ a bushel;
soybeans were 9{ cents to 22{ cents higher with November at $8.11 a
bushel.
