<HEAD>Emhart To Acquire GardenAmerica</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FARMINGTON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emhart Corp. said Thursday it has
reached an agreement to acquire GardenAmerica Corp., a maker of
garden watering systems, in a deal worth $84 million.
   Under terms of a deal approved by both companies' boards, Emhart
will pay $28.25 a share for GardenAmerica's outstanding stock.
   GardenAmerica, based in Carson City, Nev., is a leading
designer, manufacturer and marketer of automatic watering systems
for commercial and home markets. Its products, including Lawn Genie
and Drip Mist, are sold in the United States, Australia, France,
Italy and Spain.
   GardenAmerica revenues were $51.4 million for the nine months
ended June 30. The company employs 1,275 people at manufacturing
plants in Carson City, El Paso, Texas and Valencia, Calif.
   Peter L. Scott, Emhart chairman and president, said the
acquistion would expand Emhart's role in the lawn and garden market.
   ``Watering systems comprise one the fastest growing segments in
the overall market,'' he noted. GardenAmerica would become part of
Emhart's consumer unit, which had revenues of $449 million last
year.
   Emhart, based in Farmington, has annual revenues of $2.45
billion. The company manufactures industrial and consumer products
and also is involved in information and electronic systems.
