<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 1726EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-HighTech-Salaries     10-13 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-High Tech-Salaries,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Salaries Soar for High-Tech Execs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 100 highest paid executives in high-technology
companies earned an average of $785,000 last year, and 17 were paid
more than $1 million, according to a survey by a trade publication.
   At the top of the list is Apple Computer Inc. chief executive
officer John Sculley, whose 1987 cash compensation was $2.14
million, Electronic Business magazine reported.
   The figures in the survey, which was compiled largely from proxy
statements, include salaries and cash bonuses, but do not include
non-pay benefits or stock options, which in many cases equal or
exceed the executives' cash compensation.
   The $785,000 average pay was up 23.5 percent from 1986, when the
top 100 earned an average of $633,000.
   The increase is partly a reflection of a good year for the
industry, which saw the top 200 electronics companies' sales rise
7.4 percent and profits soar 53.6 percent, said Linda B. Stallmann,
senior editor of the magazine.
   But, she added, the October 1987 stock market crash and changes
in income tax laws also helped drive up cash compensation.
   ``Executives are preferring cash, because sometimes the stock
options aren't as valuable as they used to be, and the new tax laws
have reduced the value of perquisites like houses or cars,''
Stallmann said.
   The magazine also found a sharp increase in the popularity of
contractual guarantees to compensate top executives in the event
their companies are taken over by hostile raiders.
   ``Because of all the mergers and acquisitions, the chief
executives are looking for more security,'' Stallmann said.
   The 17 million-dollar earners, as listed in the Oct. 15 issue of
Electronic Business, are: Apple's Sculley, $2.14 million; Unisys
chairman W. Michael Blumenthal, $1,549,000; Computer Associates
chairman Charles B. Wang, $1,431,000; Compaq Computer president
Joseph R. Canion, $1,375,000; Seagate Technology president David T.
Mitchell, $1,354,975; Seagate Technology senior vice president
Douglas K. Mahon, $1,274,120; Seagate Technology chairman Alan F.
Shugart, $1,263,951.
   Also, Unisys President Paul G. Stern, $1,195,920;
Hewlett-Packard Chairman John A. Young, $1,193,300; and Computer
Associates president Anthony W. Wang, $1,188,000; Xerox chairman
David T. Kearns, $1,165,465; Advanced Micro Devices chairman W.J.
Sanders, $1,057,080; Unisys vice chairman Joseph J. Kroger,
$1,029,337; Litton Industries chairman Fred W. O'Green, $1,022,510;
Honeywell chairman Edson W. Spenser, $1,014,185; NCR chairman
Charles E. Exley Jr., $1,001,200; and Convergent Technologies
chairman Paul C. Ely Jr., $1,000,000.
