<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 1940EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-USWSurvey     10-13 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-USW Survey,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USW Surveys Union Leaders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A University of Pittsburgh survey of United
Steelworkers of America union local leaders showed more than 90
percent would strike for stronger job security, 76 percent would
strike to avoid wage cuts, and 65 percent would strike if an
employer offered no contract improvements.
   In addition, the survey of 950 leaders showed about 65 percent
said they are influenced by labor's endorsement of political
candidates and 81 percent said they gave money to the USW's
political action committee.
   The 620,000-member union, as part of the AFL-CIO, has endorsed
Democrat Michael Dukakis for president.
   Professor Marick F. Masters of the university's Joseph M. Katz
Graduate School of Business conducted the 112-question survey among
local USW leaders from across the country attending union meetings
last summer and fall. The study for the union was released Thursday.
   Masters noted that about 85 percent of those surveyed were white
males, 75 percent were married, 65 percent were at least 36 years
old, and less than 19 percent had been laid off in the previous
three years.
   Although nearly 55 percent reported earning at least $25,000, 74
percent of those who donated money to the union's political action
committee gave $29 or less, and 27.5 percent gave less than $10,
according to the study.
</TEXT>
