<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MoneyFunds     10-13 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Funds,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Money Funds Rose $305 Million in Latest Week</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund
Report are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the
week ended Wednesday.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 451 money market mutual
funds rose $305.4 million in the latest week, the Investment
Company Institute said Thursday.
   The rise, to $267.46 billion in the seven-day period ended
Wednesday, followed a $182 million increase in the funds' assets
the previous week, according to the Washington-based mutual fund
trade group.
   The funds' assets hit a record high $280.02 billion in the week
ended Feb. 24.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 223 general purpose funds fell $80.8 million to $85.04
billion, assets of 103 broker-dealer funds increased $876.5 million
to $113.35 billion, and assets of 125 institutional funds declined
$490.3 million to $69.07 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds fell in
the week ended Tuesday to 7.47 percent from 7.48 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield rose, to 7.45 percent from 7.43
percent, Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was
unchanged at 35 days, Donoghue's said.
   Separately, the newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of
100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and
savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the
effective annual yield available on money market accounts rose to
6.05 percent as of Wednesday from 6.03 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super
NOW accounts, was unchanged at 5.11 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 7.77
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 7.76 the
previous week. Yields were 8.08 percent on 1-year CDs, down from
8.09 percent; 8.31 percent on 2{-year CDs, down from 8.33 percent;
and 8.58 percent on 5-year CDs, down from 8.59 percent.
</TEXT>
