<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Earns-Bank 2ndLd-Writethru f0230 10-13 0616</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Bank, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0230,0635</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chemical, Security Pacific, Bank of NY Post Profit Gain</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites thruout to include Continental Illinois</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Chemical Banking Corp., the nation's fifth-largest banking
company, said Thursday that it had a third-quarter profit after
losing money a year ago while sixth-ranked Security Pacific Corp.
reported record earnings during the summer period.
   Meanwhile, Continental Illinois Corp., another large banking
concern, said its third-quarter profit rose 22 percent and Bank of
New York Co. posted a 20 percent gain over a year ago.
   Chemical said that for the three months ended Sept. 30 it netted
$211.9 million, or $3.43 a share, compared with a loss of $66.4
million in 1987.
   For the first nine months, it earned $465.1 million, or $7.36 a
share, compared with a $1.08 billion net loss last year, when the
company increased its loan-loss provision to cover possible losses
from Third World loans.
   Security Pacific earned a record $167.9 million, or $1.47 a
share, in the third quarter. That was 30 percent higher than the
$128.8 million, or $1.16 a share, it earned last year.
   In the first three quarters the Los Angeles company earned
$469.4 million, or $4.13 a share, vs. $55.1 million, or 41 cents a
share in the same year-ago period.
   Continental Illinois said it earned $73.6 million, or 30 cents a
share, in the third quarter, compared with net income of $60.1
million, or 24 cents a share, in the same period last year.
   For the first nine months, it earned a record $202.3 million, or
81 cents a share, vs. a $373.7 million loss last year, when it
increased its Third World loan-loss provision.
   Bank of New York said it earned $54.2 million, or $1.39 per
share on a fully diluted basis, for the three months ended Sept.
30, compared with $45.2 million, or $1.22 a share, in the same
period last year.
   For the first nine months it netted $158.3 million, or $4.16 a
share, compared with $57.6 million, or $1.22 a share, in 1987.
   Chemical's quarterly results were bolstered by several
nonrecurring gains, including $40.4 million from the settlement of
a portion of Chemical's pension obligations and $23.3 million from
the sale of certain nonstrategic businesses. Excluding those
special items, third-quarter earnings would have been $148.2
million.
   Chemical said it also benefitted from increases in corporate
finance fees, bond trading and foreign exchange trading profits and
a lower provision for loan losses.
   Texas Commerce Bancshares, which was acquired by Chemical in May
1987, posted a third-quarter profit of $6.8 million, compared with
a $13.5 million loss last year.
   Security Pacific said its third-quarter results were helped by
higher net interest margins, little change in non-interest expenses
and a $32 million gain from the sale of some of its Hong Kong
banking operations.
   ``Our expense cotrol programs are increasing our profitability
and strengthening the corporation across the board,'' Security
Pacific Chairman Richard J. Flamson III said.
   Continental Illinois said its third-quarter results included
$28.7 million in net gains from the sales of certain domestic and
foreign operations, although those gains were partly offset by a
$15 million reduction in interest revenue from foreign loans.
   At the Bank of New York, Chairman J. Carter Bacot attributed the
increase in third-quarter earnings to strong growth in lending
activities and tighter control of operating expenses.
   Bank of New York is in the process of merging with rival Irving
Bank Corp. in a deal valued at $1.4 billion. The agreement, which
came earlier this month, ended one of the nation's longest and most
bitter hostile takeovers.
   The merger will make Bank of New York one of the largest banking
companies in the countries.
</TEXT>
