<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market weathered the news of a
wider-than-expected U.S. trade deficit in August to post some
scattered gains Thursday.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 7.12 to 2,133.36.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 8 to 7 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
751 up, 669 down and 535 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 154.53 million
shares, against 154.84 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 177.78 million shares.
   Before the market opened the Commerce Department reported that
the trade deficit expanded to $12.18 billion in August from $9.47
billion the month before.
   The latest figure slightly exceeded advance estimates on Wall
Street, and send the dollar briefly tumbling in foreign exchange.
But the dollar soon steadied.
   Analysts said the stock market appeared to have taken the news
largely into account with its decline on Wednesday, when the Dow
Jones industrial average fell 30.23 points.
   Thursday's activity came as a sharp contrast to the occasion of
the August trade report a year ago, when an unpleasanbt surprise in
the data touched off a 95-point drop in the Dow just a few days
before Black Monday on Oct. 19.
   Among actively traded blue chips, International Business
Machines rose 1[ to 118|; Sears Roebuck gained 2[ to 42], and
American Telephone & Telegraph was down \ at 26\.
   Federal National Mortgage climbed 1| to 50}, trading at new
52-week highs. On Wednesday the company reported sharply higher
earnings for the third quarter.
   Avon Products dropped 1\ to 24]. The company said it would post
losses for the third quarter and the year as a result of a $425
million charge to be taken on some discontinued operations.
   Genentech dropped 1 to 16}. The company said it had finished
production for this year of a drug used to treat blood clots
associated with heart attacks.
   Sales of the new drug have so far fallen short of lofty
expectations on Wall Street.
   Takeover rumors and speculation sparked gains in such diverse
stocks as West Point Pepperell, up 3| at 40|; Chicago Pacific, up
1} at 43{; McGraw-Hill, up 1} at 75\, and Advanced Micro Devices,
up | at 10{.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $9.19 billion, or 0.34
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained .57 to 155.34.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index rose 1.40 to 316.32, and
S&P's 500-stock composite index was up 1.24 at 275.22.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market added
.91 to 383.46. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 302.04, up .13.
