<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Lockheed     10-13 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Lockheed,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aerospace Company's Profit Up 15 Pct. in 3rd Qtr.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALABASAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lockheed Corp. said Thursday its
operating profit rose 15 percent in the third quarter while net
income, boosted by the sale of a computer operation, tripled in the
period.
   The aerospace company said earnings from continuing operations
totaled $123 million, or $2.07 a share, up from $107 million, or
$1.61 a share, in the third quarter of 1987.
   Earnings from continuing operations improved primarily because
the new federal income tax law and accounting changes have cut the
company's tax bill, said Lawrence O. Kitchen, chairman and chief
executive officer.
   Lockheed said income of $177 million from discontinued
operations boosted final net to $300 million, or $5.06 a share,
from $101 million, or $1.52 a share a year earlier.
   The third-quarter results were helped by Lockheed's sale of its
Dialog Information Services for $202 million. Partly offsetting
that one-time gain was a $26 million loss on the closing of
Lockheed Shipbuilding Co. in Seattle.
   Sales for the quarter were $2.4 billion, down from $2.7 billion
a year earlier. The company attributed the decline to the winding
down of the C-5B military transport plane production project.
   For the first nine months of the year, Lockheed earned $338
million, or $5.60 a share on continuing operations, up from $294
million, or $4.44 a share, a year earlier. Net earnings for the
nine months were $520 million, or $8.61 a share, up from $287
million, or $4.33 a share a year earlier.
   Sales in the first nine months totaled $7.6 billion, down from
$8 billion a year earlier.
</TEXT>
