<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0824</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Orange Juice Futures Soar On Rumors Of Brazilian Delivery Woes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Orange juice futures prices leaped dramatically Thursday on the
New York Cotton Exchange on rumors that Brazil, the world's largest
orange juice producer, may have problems meeting its delivery
commitments, analysts said.
   But Brazilian officials said such fears were unfounded.
   On other exchanges, cotton futures soared; soybeans moved
sharply higher, pulling grain futures along; livestock and meat
futures were mostly higher; energy futures rose; precious metals
retreated; and stock-index futures advanced.
   Frozen concentrated orange juice futures began the session on a
low note due to a greater-than-expected Florida production estimate
in the Agriculture Department's first forecast of the season and
beneficial overnight rains in Brazil.
   But rumors surfaced at mid-morning that, for unknown reasons,
Brazil might have trouble meeting its delivery commitments and a
buying binge commenced.
   ``The market shot up extremely strongly,'' said Judith Ganes, an
analyst in New York with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   The contract for November delivery of frozen concentrated orange
juice skyrocketed to its permitted limit of 10 cents a pound, which
forced a 30-minute trading halt in accordance with the exchange's
rules, she said.
   Florida commercial players turned sellers when trading resumed,
analysts said. The November price dropped sharply but climbed back
later in the session to finish at $1.8865 a pound, 7.75 cents above
Wednesday's settlement price.
   Ms. Ganes said she had learned that a fire at the Bank of Brazil
in Rio de Janeiro may have destroyed some documents pertaining to
the orange juice business.
   ``However, I feel that in no way should that affect Brazil's
ability to deliver orange juice,'' she said.
   Brazilian citrus traders and government officials reportedly
said shipments of frozen concentrated orange juice were moving
normally. A fire destroyed the import-export branch of the Bank of
Brazil in Rio but that did not affect the issuing of licenses,
according to bank officials.
   Cotton for delivery in December and March soared the
2-cents-a-pound limit on technical factors and on talk of Chinese
buying, said Ernest Simon, cotton specialist with Prudential-Bache
Securities in New York.
   December cotton settled at 55.75 cents a pound.
   Soybean futures surged on the Chicago Board of Trade on rumors
that the Soviet Union might have bought 200,000 metric tons of U.S.
soybean meal, analysts said.
   Soybean meal for near-month delivery surged more than $7 a ton
while most soybean contracts gained more than 20 cents a bushel,
pushing the price for November delivery well above $8. Most of the
buying came late in the session after talk of the possible Soviet
purchase surfaced.
   Grain futures closed mostly higher on spillover buying from the
soybean complex, he said.
   Wheat settled 2 cents lower to 1 cent higher with December at
$4.35\ a bushel; corn was 1 cent to 2{ cents higher with December
at $2.97\ a bushel; oats were 3{ cents lower to 1 cent higher with
December at $2.57{ a bushel; soybeans were 9 cents to 22 cents
higher with November at $8.12 a bushel.
   Frozen pork belly futures finished sharply higher on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange as traders bought contracts in reaction to an
exchange report showing some movement of bellies out of storage
last week, analysts said.
   The market had been expecting more bellies to be placed in cold
storage, said Philip Stanley, an analyst in Chicago with Thomson
McKinnon Securities Inc.
   Higher cash prices also boosted the pork complex while the
cattle market finished mixed in directionless trading.
   Live cattle settled .05 cent lower to .57 cent higher with
October at 73.17 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .25
cent higher with October at 81.97 cents a pound; hogs were .22 cent
to .58 cent higher with October at 40.57 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were 1.33 cents to 1.40 cents higher with February at 49.40
cents a pound.
   Unleaded gasoline led energy futures higher on the New York
Mercantile Exchange due to concern about tightening gasoline
supplies.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled unchanged to 10 cents
higher with November at $14.21 a barrel; heating oil was .08 cent
lower to .91 cent higher with November at 41.75 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .40 cent to 1.49 cents higher with November
at 44.15 cents a gallon.
   Precious metals futures declined modestly on the Commodity
Exchange in New York in light trading.
   Gold settled $1.50 to $1.80 lower with December at $410.40 a
troy ounce; silver was 1.7 cents to 2 cents lower with December at
$6.375 a troy ounce.
   Stock-index futures advanced slightly on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for December delivery of stocks on the
Standard & Poor's 500 index settled .80 point higher at 277.
</TEXT>
