<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AutoSales Bjt   10-13 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Model Year Starts Strong, But Analysts Cautious</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Automakers reported Thursday their sales of
U.S.-made cars and trucks jumped 31.5 percent in early October from
a year earlier, but that was a time when buying had slowed after a
race for big incentives ended.
   Companies making cars and light trucks in the United States said
they sold 278,932 vehicles during the Oct. 1-10 period this year,
which was the first period in the 1989 model year. They sold
238,707 during the same time last year.
   The percentage comparison is based on daily sales rates because
the period is so short. There were eight selling days in the period
this year, compared with nine last year.
   At the end of September last year, when the 1987 model year came
to a close, many popular, cut-rate financing and cash-back
incentives expired. Those offers drew in a lot of consumers and
buying dropped after new models went on sale.
   ``You were heading into the nothingness stage last year, where
all the programs were expiring and inventories were getting down to
a very low level,'' said analyst Charles Brady at the investment
firm Oppenheimer & Co. in New York.
   ``Now all of a sudden, their comparison looks phenomenal,''
Brady said.
   Sales of U.S.-made cars rose 36.8 percent in early October
compared to the same period last year, rising to a total of 183,652
cars from 151,043.
   Kathleen Heaney of Nikko Securities Co. International Inc.
agreed that some car buyers who were planning on purchasing cars in
late autumn last year headed to showrooms in September 1987 to take
advantage of incentives for '86 models.
   ``Probably the whole month of October is going to be very high
because the basis of last year was very low,'' she said.
   Heaney also said U.S. automakers put incentives on their 1989
models shortly after they were introduced and that accounted for
some of the sales boost early this month.
   ``This year there was nothing really new (on showroom floors),''
she said. ``I guess that was part of the reason for them putting
the incentives on this year.''
   For the calendar year, domestic automakers have sold 5,927,753
cars, compared with 5,666,841 last year _ a 4.6 percent increase.
   For early October, Ford Motor Co. showed the largest increase,
with car sales jumping 70 percent on a daily basis to a total of
58,407 from 38,662 last year. Light truck sales increased 23.1
percent, to 33,574 from 30,681.
   General Motors Corp. showed a 31.7 percent rise in car sales, to
90,183 from 77,032. GM's light truck sales rose 29.3 percent, to
41,010 from 35,693.
   Chrysler Corp.'s U.S.-made car sales rose 11.8 percent, to
24,566 from 24,714. Its light trucks sales dropped 10.4 percent,
falling to 19,297 from 19,667.
</TEXT>
