<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Dial508     10-13 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dial 508,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On Saturday, Add Those Extra Digits Or Else</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Starting Saturday, your fingers will have to do an
extra three digits of walking when calling about half of
Massachusetts.
   If they don't, this is the computerized voice you'll hear:
   ``The area code for the number you dialed has been changed to
508. Please hang up and dial the area code 508 for the number you
are calling.''
   Make that 1-508.
   The long-planned addition of a new area code for about 190
communities in eastern and central Massachusetts was undertaken by
New England Telephone Co. to avoid the inevitability of running out
of new telephone numbers.
   The 508 service was activated in July, but using the new code
was voluntary. As of Saturday, callers will hear the recording
unless they dial the extra digits.
   Three towns _ Walpole, Dover and North Reading _ all appealed
their placement in 508 to the state Department of Public Utilities.
They all lost. Wilmington put its appeal on hold but said it would
not pursue it after the others failed.
   ``We feel it's a great inconvenience,'' Wilmington Town Manager
Buzz Stapczynski said Wednesday. ``Most of our business is
conducted with Boston _ 99.9 percent of the calls I make are to
Boston.''
   Bitterness and embarrassment over being removed from Boston's
617 area code _ along with new letterhead, business cards and truck
lettering _ are some of the aftereffects of the new code.
   ``We in fact are part of Greater Boston,'' asserted Hartnell
Bartlett, selectmen chairman in North Reading, which spent $20,000
to fight the change. ``Everything we do is within that region.
We're the only community with a 508 exchange listed in the Greater
Boston telephone directory.''
   More than the inconvenience of dialing the extra digits,
officials in border towns complained they were being exiled to
exurbia by virtue of the less serious area code.
   ``It obviously has a significant cost on businesses and a
psychological impact,'' Bartlett said. ```Gee, North Reading must
be up there someplace. It's in another area code.'''
   Stapczynski said Wilmington is part of the Boston-based
Massachusetts Water Resources Authority, the Massachusetts Bay
Transportation Authority and the Massachusetts Planning Commission.
   ``We don't relate to Lowell or Haverhill or Lawrence or any of
those places,'' he said.
   But Stapczynski said the town decided against fighting the new
code because of the expense and almost-sure defeat. ``Why fight the
bureaucracy and spend a ton of money and come out with the same
decision?'' he said.
   New England Telephone Co. spokesman Peter Cronin said the
company sought to maintain a near equal number of telephone lines
in the two regions, minimize confusion and consider business and
residential trends when deciding what towns were moved to 508.
   ``The line had to go someplace and we felt we had established
very fair criteria and very faithfully followed those criteria,''
he said.
   Callers will not have to pay more money when calling into the
new area code, Cronin said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
