<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Trade-Markets 1stLd-Writethru   10-13 0625</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru,0648</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls on Report of Wider Trade Deficit</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-6 to CORRECT Dow close and update bond yields;
picks up 7th graf pvs, The dollar ....</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell Thursday but other markets
reacted calmly to a report that the nation's persistent trade
deficit widened in August.
   One year ago, an unexpected rise in the trade deficit served as
one of the catalysts for the stock market crash.
   The Commerce Department reported that the merchandise trade
deficit widened to $12.2 billion in August from $9.5 billion in
July, confirming fears that had pushed stocks, bonds and the dollar
down earlier in the week.
   The news pushed the dollar still lower. But the stock and bond
markets took the news in stride.
   More stocks rose than fell on Wall Street as the Dow Jones
average of 30 industrial stocks rose 7.12 points to 2,133.36. The
average had fallen 30.23 points on Wednesday.
   In the bond market, interest rates rose immediately after the
report, but then partly retreated. One closely watched measure of
rates, the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond, rose to 8.92 percent
from 8.90 percent late Wednesday.
   The dollar was ready to be nudged down further because the mood
of the market had seemingly shifted against it this week.
   ``The market's still not totally sure about it ... (but) the
first reaction is, we've got to sell the dollar,'' said Rimmer de
Vries, chief economist of Morgan Guaranty Trust Co.
   By late in the day, the dollar was down to less than 127.5
Japanese yen and 1.82 West German marks, compared to more than 129
yen and 1.83 marks on Wednesday.
   Hopes for big reductions in the trade deficit had helped push
the dollar higher through June, July and August. The dollar peaked
around Sept. 1, then drifted slowly downward before falling steeply
this week toward its level of early summer.
   Sentiments about the dollar are subject to change without
notice, and some analysts said Thursday that they believed the
underlying trend in the dollar was still for a stable or higher
currency.
   ``This is not a sufficiently bad number to change the
psychology,'' said Lawrence Krohn, senior economist for Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Dollar traders and speculators have plenty of room to interpret
the latest trade figures because economists have sharply
conflicting projections for how much the trade deficit will shrink
in coming years.
   Economists are divided between ``long laggers,'' who expect the
deficit to keep dropping sharply because of the lagging reaction to
the dollar's decline since 1985, and ``short laggers,'' who believe
all the benefits from the dollar drop have already come.
   De Vries, who called himself a ``short lagger'' Thursday, said
the dollar's decline is good because it will make U.S. goods more
competitive in world markets and help shrink the trade deficit.
   ``I'm glad about it. We ought to make a lot more headway on the
trade balance,'' de Vries said.
   The all-time high in imports in August outweighed exports, which
also set a monthly record. The heavy imports indicated that
Americans have not lost their taste for imported goods in spite of
a rise in their prices from the depreciated dollar.
   The imbalance between what the United States imports and what it
sells abroad was up by $2.7 billion over a July deficit of $9.5
billion, which had had been the smallest monthly imbalance in more
than three years.
   From the point of view of inflation-wary investors, the
combination of strong exports and strong imports was ``probably the
worst combination you could get'' because it signals possible
overheating of the economy, said Michael Moran, chief economist of
Daiwa Securities America Inc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
