<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 2034EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Consolidated     10-13 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Consolidated,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minorco Rejects Claim of South African Domination Of Gold Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investment company making a hostile bid for
Consolidated Gold Fields PLC on Thursday disputed Consolidated's
claim that the takeover would lead to South African domination of
world gold and strategic metals markets.
   Minorco S.A., a Luxembourg-based firm controlled by Anglo
American Corp. of South Africa and DeBeers Consolidated Mines Ltd.,
made the arguments Thursday in an additional filing with the
British government's Office of Fair Trading.
   Anglo American and DeBeers are the gold and diamond mining
interests of South Africa's Oppenheimer family.
   The fair trading office has the power to recommend an
investigation of the bid on competition or public-interest grounds.
   ``The suggestion that Anglo American, Gold Fields and Minorco
together could influence the world price and free availability of
gold is not supported by the facts,'' Minorco contended in its
filing.
   Minorco, meanwhile, disclosed that it had purchased more of
London-based Consolidated Gold Fields' shares on the London Stock
Exchange to lift its holding to 62.6 million shares, or 29.32
percent.
   Minorco's cash-and-share bid values Consolidated Gold Fields'
entire share capital at about 2.9 billion pounds, or $5 billion.
   Consolidated Gold Fields told the office Oct. 6 that success of
the Minorco bid would give the Anglo American group control of 35
percent of the Western world's gold supplies, compared with the
group's current 20 percent share.
   But Minorco said Thursday that calculation wrongly included
Consolidated Gold Fields' interests in companies in which it has a
minority stake, including Newmont Mining Corp. of the United
States, Renison Gold Fields of Australia, and Gold Fields of South
Africa Ltd.
   Minorco said it would sell Consolidated Gold Fields' holdings of
49.3 percent in Newmont and 38 percent in Gold Fields of South
Africa if the bid succeeds. It would keep the 49 percent share of
Renison.
   The sell-off would leave Minorco with an attributable interest
of 1 percent of the West's gold production, coupled with the 20
percent share held by Anglo American.
   Minorco also rejected the claim that the bid would lead to South
African domination of certain strategic minerals and metals,
particularly the mineral sands from which zircon and titanium are
extracted.
   Consolidated Gold Fields' shares closed 6 pence (10.48 cents)
lower at 12.45 pounds ($21.75) Thursday on the London Stock
Exchange. Minorco's offer is currently worth 12.66 pounds ($22.12
dollars) per share.
</TEXT>
