<HEAD>Gannett Earnings Up 6.5 Percent in Third Quarter</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS lead and headline to CORRECT percentage to 6.5 percent;
picks up 2nd graf pvs, ``Net income ...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gannett Co.'s profit rose 6.5 percent in the
third quarter as higher broadcasting and billboard revenues
outpaced gains in the sale of newspaper ads, the media company said
Thursday.
   Net income totaled $75.1 million, or 47 cents a share in the
quarter ended Sept. 25, up from $70.5 million, or 44 cents a share
a year ago.
   Revenue rose 7 percent to $804.3 million, from $751.1 million in
the third quarter of 1987.
   John J. Curley, president and chief executive of the media
conglomerate, called the company's performance satisfactory
``despite a soft economic environment.''
   Gannett said total newspaper advertising revenue rose 5 percent
to $455.6 million, from $431.7 million in 1987's third quarter.
Earnings in the newspaper group were up slightly, while advertising
linage increased 1 percent.
   Advertising revenue at USA Today, the flagship of the company's
89 daily newspapers, rose 17 percent partly because of rate
adjustments, even though total ads decreased to 867 pages from 871
pages.
   Broadcasting revenues increased 10 percent in the quarter, to
$89.7 million, while outdoor advertising increased 21 percent, to
$65.2 million.
   For the first nine months, Gannett said net income increased 16
percent to $246.6 million, or $1.52 a share, compared with $212.8
million, or $1.32 a share in the year-ago period.
   Revenue rose 7 percent to $2.41 billion, from $2.24 billion a
year ago. Results for the nine months included a non-recurring gain
on the sale of the company's investment in Cowles Media, the
company said.
   In addition to the daily newspapers, Gannett publishes 35
non-daily newspapers and a newspaper magazine. The company also
operates 10 television stations, 16 radio stations, Gannett News
Service and the largest outdoor advertising company in North
America.
</TEXT>
