<2ND_LINE>BC-Venezuela-OPEC,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Energy and Mines minister backs extraordinary OPEC meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Venezuela's Energy and Mines minister,
Julio Cesar Gil, said Thursday his country would back a special
meeting of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries to
discuss low oil prices.
   According to the state run news agency Venpress, Gil said such a
meeting, called for by Libya, would be backed by Venezuela ``as
long as there is sufficient preliminary preparation ... that
results or accords reached can be carried out by all the members.''
   ``The government of Libya has called for the meeting and at this
moment the secretary general of OPEC is carrying out the necessary
consultations with the member nations to determine the feasibility
of such a meeting,'' said Gil.
   OPEC's long range strategy committee will meet Oct. 20 in Madrid
in conjunction with the organization's pricing committee to revise
production and pricing strategy, OPEC announced this week.
   The extraordinary OPEC conference would probably be held
sometime before the ordinary meeting of all member nations
scheduled for late November.
   When asked what the purpose of such an extraordinary meeting
would be, Gil replied ``there's only one point, and that's to
examine the price situation.''
</TEXT>
