<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Goodrich     10-13 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Goodrich,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Goodrich's Profit Up 43 Percent in Third Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BF Goodrich Co. on Thursday reported a 43
percent jump in its third-quarter profit from a year earlier,
boosted by strong performances in its core chemical and aerospace
businesses.
   The plastics, chemicals and aerospace company said its net
income in the quarter ended Sept. 30 rose to $60.8 million, or
$2.32 a share, from $42.4 million, or $1.71 a share, a year earlier.
   Third-quarter revenue increased to $640.4 million from $527.4
million.
   ``Not only are current earnings meeting our expectations, but
developments necessary for long-term profitability are
progressing,'' said Chairman John D. Ong.
   Last month, the company adopted a plan aimed at protecting
employees in the event of a hostile takeover. The plan covers 4,000
salaried workers at the company.
   Rumors in September linked heavy activity in Goodrich stock with
Anglo-French financier Sir James Goldsmith and British conglomerate
Hanson Trust PLC. Goldsmith, who is known to own an undisclosed
amount of Goodrich shares, dispelled the rumors by saying he is
supportive of Goodrich management.
   In the first nine months of the year, Goodrich earned $158.5
million, or $6.02 a share, up sharply from $84.5 million, or $3.33
a share, a year earlier.
   Nine-month revenue rose to $1.8 billion from $1.5 million.
</TEXT>
