<1ST_LINE>u f AM-TaxBill 1stLd-Writethru f0244 10-13 0553</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tax Bill, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0244,0565</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Negotiators Agree On Iraq Sanctions, Virginia Battlefield</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Top 6 grafs new with more agreements; pickup 4th graf pvs,
bgng: ``Tax-writers hope...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senior tax negotiators from the House and
Senate reached agreement Thursday on legislation imposing limited
economic sanctions against Iraq and seizing a portion of a historic
battlefield in northern Virginia, aides said.
   Working on a miscellaneous tax bill, negotiators also approved a
tax break for free-lance writers, photographers and artists and an
increased mileage deduction for rural mail carriers who use their
own cars on their routes.
   Free-lancers would be permitted to deduct expenses of a project
in the year they are incurred, rather than wait until a book,
painting or other work starts producing income. The provision
overturns a change brought about by the 1986 tax overhaul.
   Under the agreement, rural letter carriers would be permitted to
deduct 33.75 cents per mile, 50 percent more than the usual rate
allowed for business mileage.
   Also approved by senior negotiators was agreement to eliminate
restrictions on the amount of long-term bonds the Treasury
Department may issue at rates above 4.25 percent.
   Aides said the two senior Democrats and two senior Republicans
from each house agreed on these provisions, which still are subject
to endorsement by other negotiators.
   Tax-writers hope to complete the compromise tax bill in time for
the House and Senate to give it final approval next week before
adjourning for the year.
   On a 50-25 vote last week, the Senate ordered the seizure of 540
acres of land in Prince William County, Va., to block construction
of a shopping mall on the site where Gen. Robert E. Lee had his
headquarters during the Second Battle of Manassas in August 1862.
   The Reagan administration opposes the seizure as too expensive,
favoring the taking of only about 80 acres. Interior Secretary
Donald P. Hodel has said he will recommend that President Reagan
veto legislation to which the Manassas amendment is attached.
   The sanctions against Iraq were approved by the Senate last week
on an 87-0 vote, the third time senators have thus registered their
displeasure with Iraq's use of poison gas against its Kurdish
minorities. However, the sanctions exempt U.S. farmers and
manufacturers of farm equipment by allowing continued exports of
farm products.
   The bill would immediately bar exportation of high-technology
equipment and munitions and require that U.S. representatives in
international organizations oppose loans to Iraq.
   The president would be required to impose additional sanctions
by yearend if Iraq continues to use chemical weapons. Those
sanctions could include a cutoff of export-import credit,
restricting imports from Iraq and downgrading U.S. relations with
Iraq.
   Final provisions of the tax bill are being hammered out behind
closed doors by Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., chairman of the
House Ways and Means Committee; Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., chairman
of the Senate Finance subcommittee on revenue measures, and senior
Republicans on the two committees, Rep. Bill Archer of Texas and
Sen. Bob Packwood of Oregon.
   The bill is designed chiefly to correct errors in the 1986 tax
overhaul law. It contains dozens of relatively minor targeted tax
cuts and tax increases. The Senate version also would create a
``bill of rights'' for taxpayers involved in disputes with the
Internal Revenue Service.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
