<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Revco     10-13 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Revco,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Revco Losses Nearly Doubled In First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TWINSBURG, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First quarter losses for Anac Holding
Corp., parent of Revco D.S. Inc., nearly doubled over the same
period last year because of extraordinary costs related to Revco's
Chapter 11 filing, the company reported Thursday.
   Anac posted a $27.9 million net loss, greater than the $14
million loss in the same three-month period last year.
   The quarterly operating profit before depreciation and
amortization was $6.1 million, compared with $31.3 million in the
same period last year, according to Gregory K. Raven, Revco's
executive vice president-finance and chief financial officer.
   Anac had $583.7 million in sales for the quarter compared to
$522.8 million in its first fiscal quarter of 1987.
   Raven blamed the losses on ``extraordinary costs and temporarily
low inventory levels directly related to the company's failure to
make a subordinated debt interest payment on June 15, 1988, and its
voluntary filing for Chapter 11 protection'' from creditors in
bankruptcy court.
   Revco filed for Chapter 11 protection on July 28, about a month
after it failed to make an interest payment on about $700 million
in outstanding high-risk junk bonds used to finance its $1.5
billion leveraged buyout in 1986.
   In a leveraged buyout a company is acquired largely through
borrowed funds repaid from a target company's profits or asset
sales.
   The Twinsburg-based company sought protection from creditors
after talks with bondholders broke down, becoming the largest
company involved in a leveraged buyout to take such action.
   Revco operates nearly 2,000 drugs store in 27 states.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
