<1ST_LINE>u f AM-HCABuyout     10-13 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-HCA Buyout,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Management Group Makes New Offer to Buy HCA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investor group led by Hospital
Corporation of America's senior management has made a new,
sweetened offer to buy the hospital chain for more than $3.6
billion, the company said Thursday.
   The new offer of $51 a share in cash and securities for all of
HCA's 70.6 million outstanding shares comes a week after a special
committee of the company's board of directors rejected the group's
initial, $47 a share cash offer.
   HCA stock closed at $44.50 a share Thursday, unchanged from
Wednesday's close in New York Stock Exchange trading.
   The latest offer would pay $43 cash plus securities the group
valued at $8 for each HCA share, the company said in a news
release. The group has commitments for all the debt and equity
financing needed to complete the buyout, HCA said.
   The offer is valid until 5 p.m. EDT Tuesday and is contingent
upon approval by shareholders and the HCA Board.
   A special committee of independent directors of the board
planned to meet at an unspecified date to consider the proposal.
   The special committee on Oct. 6 rejected a $3.3 billion
leveraged buyout proposal from the group, led by HCA Chairman
Thomas F. Frist, and said it wasn't ``in the best interest of the
HCA shareholders.''
   HCA officials could not be reached for comment on the proposal
late Thursday.
   HCA, which owns or operates nearly 400 hospitals worldwide,
making it one of the world's biggest hospital chains, set up the
special committee to consider buyout offers when the first one was
proposed in mid-September.
   HCA reported in July that its profits for the quarter ending
June 30 increased by 15 percent, partly because of increased
inpatient and outpatient revenue.
   HCA sold 104 of its less profitable hospitals just over a year
ago to a new employee-owned company, HealthTrust Inc.
</TEXT>
