<1ST_LINE>r f BC-CampbellPurchase     10-13 0163</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Campbell Purchase,0171</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Campbell Acquires Foreign Seafood Processor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campbell Soup Co. announced Thursday it had
acquired a Belgian seafood processor for an undisclosed amount of
cash.
   Morubel NV, based in Oostende, Belgium, is a privately-held
supplier of frozen prawns to major retail chains and food service
customers in Belgium, France, Germany, Italy and Great Britain. It
had 1987 sales of $44 million.
   Morubel is a major supplier to Campbell's seafood division,
which processes cold water prawns, squid, lobster tails and breaded
scampi.
   ``It's a continuing part of growth strategy,'' James H. Moran, a
Campbell spokesman, said of the acquisition.
   In the year ending July 30, Campbell has made domestic and
international acquisitions totaling $528 million, Moran said.
   Campbell International President John W. Argabright said the
acquisition ``greatly strengthens the seafood business of our
United Kingdom division, ... and gives us access to the growing
frozen seafood specialty market in Europe.''
   Morubel's two facilities in Oostende employ 174 people.
</TEXT>
